<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denver Newspapers Joining Forces  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE TSAI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Denver's two newspapers announced plans Thursday
to form a joint operating company, acknowledging their bitter yet
colorful competition eventually would have forced one of them out
of business.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, The Denver Post and the Denver Rocky
Mountain News would maintain separate news operations but would
equally share business functions, including advertising and
circulation sales, production and newspaper distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The News and The Post have been waging a battle for
circulation and ad revenue unlike any other,'' said Ken Lowe,
president and chief operating officer of E.W. Scripps Co., which
owns the News. ''We've done everything we know to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite our best efforts, the reality of two-newspaper
economics today dictates that we take another tack.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the News has lost $123 million, compared with a $200
million profit for the Post, the newspapers said. The Post is owned
by MediaNews Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The News planned to apply Friday for a joint operating agreement
because it is ''in probable danger of financial failure,'' said
Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act, the attorney
general can grant antitrust law exemptions to allow financially
troubled newspapers to merge their production and commercial
operations.
</P>
<P>
   William Dean Singleton, MediaNews chairman and chief executive,
said the newspapers are also facing stiff competition from a
multitude of sources, ranging from television to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just a newspaper battle anymore,'' Singleton said.
''It's newspapers battling the rest of the communications
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 100 years, the two newspapers have fought for turf
in one of the longest-running newspaper wars in the country. Only a
handful of major cities still have competing newspapers, including
Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both are morning papers. The Post switched from an afternoon
paper in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The News has a daily circulation of 446,465 and a Sunday
circulation of 552,085. The Post's daily circulation is 413,730 and
its Sunday circulation is 558,560.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, each paper would publish separate morning
editions Monday through Friday. Weekend editions would be published
under a joint masthead, with the News publishing on Saturday and
the Post publishing on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Post and the News would form the Denver Newspaper Agency to
handle the joint operations. Executives said they did not expect
job cuts in the newsrooms, but cuts are possible in other areas.
The News has 1,785 employees, while the Post has 1,870.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1859, the News won readers early on with headlines
like ''The Utes Must Go,'' referring to American Indians. It also
defended military raids on Indian camps.
</P>
<P>
   The Post, founded in 1892, took the circulation lead at the turn
of the century ''with its buckets of blood'' campaign, using
screaming banner headlines in red ink like ''Does it hurt to be
born?'' said Tom Noel, University of Colorado-Denver history
professor.
</P>
<P>
   The battle waged throughout Colorado's economic booms and busts,
heating to a boiling point in the 1990s, when both papers offered
subscriptions at ridiculously low costs. The News has sold
subscriptions for a penny a day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the News withdrew from its statewide circulation to
focus on counties along the Front Range, encompassing metropolitan
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ''That competition has not occurred in a vacuum and, over the
last few years, we found ourselves battling for both market share
and mind share,'' Singleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, each newspaper received a Pulitzer Prize for
coverage of the April 1999 Columbine High School shooting attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0001 </TRAILER>
