<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Opposition Candidate Leads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- For the first time, a major poll released
Thursday placed an opposition candidate for president ahead of the
party that has governed Mexico for 71 years, although the lead was
small enough to be a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   With the July 2 election less than two months away, the survey
showed Vicente Fox of the center-right National Action Party
favored by 46.3 percent of those polled, while Francisco Labastida
of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party was favored by 41.6
percent. That would put the result within the 3.2 percent margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   ''If these numbers hold, Mexico is headed for a major change,''
pollster John Zogby said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   His company Zogby International carried out the survey for the
Reuters news agency. The survey conducted personal interviews of
1,062 likely voters between April 29 and May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing far behind was Cuauhtemoc Cardenas of the left-center
Democratic Revolution Party, who was supported by 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most Mexicans have never known a president who was not a member
of the governing party, known as the PRI. It has run Mexico since
its creation as a tool of the presidency in 1929, and although it
has long since severed formal ties to the government, it remains
the dominant political force in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's momentum got another boost Thursday when a minor-party
candidate called on all five opposition groups to form a united
front against the governing party.
</P>
<P>
   But Porfirio Munoz Ledo of the tiny Authentic Party of the
Mexican Revolution stopped short of endorsing Fox, with whom he met
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Ledo called for an ''alliance of candidates committed to
democratic transition.'' It is too late by law for the parties to
join a true coalition, but they can informally endorse one of the
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Interior Ministry publicly accused Munoz Ledo
of trying to take over the leadership of the party he represents.
Munoz Ledo called it a dirty trick designed to destabilize his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the leader of the party, Carlos Guzman, said
Munoz Ledo no longer had the support of the Authentic Party. Guzman
asked him to resign as candidate, but by law cannot force him to.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz Ledo is a former president both of the PRI and of the
Democratic Revolution Party.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Zogby survey, the Labastida campaign released
its own poll Thursday showing the PRI candidate comfortably ahead
with 45 percent of the vote, while Fox received 39 percent and
Cardenas had 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted by the Pearson polling firm of Mexico,
surveyed 1,590 potential voters between April 28 and May 2 and had
a margin of error of 2.8 percentage points, Pearson president
Manuel Barberena said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Barberena said the poll was conducted in 150 municipalities in
almost every state of the country. Javier Trevino, a top official
in the Labastida campaign, said the Zogby poll was overly
concentrated in the cities.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters said support for Fox was highest in the cities, but
insisted the poll was weighted to account for that.
</P>
<P>
   The Zogby poll was the first report by a major polling
organization to appear since a nationally televised debate between
presidential candidates on April 25. Less reliable telephone
surveys after that event showed many voters felt Fox won that
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-five percent of those who answered the Zogby-Reuters poll
said they had seen the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 15 percent of those polled -- including those who didn't
watch the debate -- said they thought Fox had won the debate, the
highest figure for any of the six candidates who took part. About 8
percent said Labastida had won.
</P>
<P>
   Fox had been surging even before the debate. A poll published a
day before the debate in the newspaper Reforma showed Labastida
only 3 percentage points ahead. That poll had a 2.5 percent margin
of error.
</P>
<P>
   Reforma's next poll is not due to appear for more than a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
