<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Medic Pleads Guilty to Murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) -- A Navy medic admitted Thursday
that he killed his wife after an argument and conspired with his
former girlfriend to conceal her death.
</P>
<P>
   Petty Officer 2nd Class David Tate pleaded guilty during a court
martial at Camp Pendleton. He faces a military prison sentence of
at least 20 years when he is sentenced June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Tate testified that he and his wife, Cynthia, got into a shoving
match at their Camp Pendleton home the night of Feb. 13, 1999. Tate
said he took a gun from her, shot her and then hid her body in a
sewage drain.
</P>
<P>
   Tate was accused of conspiring with his former girlfriend, Petty
Officer 3rd Class Andrea Bart, to cover up the killing.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty to, among other charges, premeditated murder,
adultery, and conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   Following the slaying, Tate, of Colorado Springs, Colo.,
reported his wife missing and told investigators that she had left
a note saying she was going to Las Vegas with friends.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, Tate attended a prayer vigil in a base chapel, and
in media interviews appealed for help in finding his missing wife.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on a tip, Navy investigators discovered Cynthia Tate's
body in July near a reservoir on the base, 30 miles north of San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Tate and Bart, of Midlothian, Va., were Navy medics assigned to
the Headquarters and Service Battalion, 1st Force Service Support
Group at the Marine Corps' Camp Pendleton.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps said Bart, 28, is expected to plead guilty to
offenses related to the slaying when her case is heard May 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
