<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tamil Rebels Close on Jaffna  </HEADLINE>
By KRISHNAN GURUSWAMY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Tamil Tiger rebels said Friday they were
closing in on Jaffna city, while Sri Lankan jets stepped up bombing
sorties on rebel positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sri Lankan soldiers! You are occupying our land,'' said a
Voice of Tigers rebel radio broadcast Thursday. ''Our cadres are
advancing. We will capture Jaffna. You must surrender or
withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   Sustained bombing by the Sri Lankan air force on the rebels'
backup units is seen as delaying their final march into the city.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast, listened to by residents in the northern town of
Vavuniya reached by telephone, said Friday that the rebels captured
Nedunkulam area, which is only half a mile from the administrative
center of the city. The radio said rebels can march into the city
center any moment.
</P>
<P>
   The radio said Thursday that the rebels had captured four other
towns located from half a mile to four miles away.
</P>
<P>
   It was the closest to Jaffna that the guerrillas have reached
since they lost their former capital in the north to the military
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, or LTTE, said they killed
many soldiers and that several hundred civilians fled the embattled
areas. The radio said the rebels lost 13 fighters in the past 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   There was no Sri Lankan government statement on the latest
situation in the north. But the government's chief spokesman and
censor, Ariya Rubasinghe, said ''troops continue to offer stiff
resistance displaying firm determination to destroy the
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The contradictory claims could not be independently verified
because neither side allows journalists into the battle zone.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the International Committee of the Red Cross urged
the warring parties to ensure that civilians and their property are
protected.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after fierce assaults, the rebels said they had
seized a vital bridge three miles outside Jaffna, which would bring
the city's only airport within range of their guns and block a
major exit route for the defenders. The government denied the rebel
claim.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, the government raised taxes to
bring in additional money for defense.
</P>
<P>
   It also banned live broadcast of news and current affairs
programs about national security. Censorship is already in force in
Sri Lanka on all news organizations operating in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Four days ago, the government rejected the offer by the Tigers
to a temporary cease-fire to allow the 40,000 troops to surrender
Jaffna Peninsula, home to most of the 3.2 million Tamil minority.
</P>
<P>
   The next day the rebels began to push toward the government line
on several fronts. The fighting has left more than 100 people dead
this week, according to government and rebel reports.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels want to carve out a homeland in the north and the
east of the country where they say the Tamils will not face
discrimination from the majority Sinhalese.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the terrorists are making desperate attempts to
advance further, troops are determined and, so far, all such
attempts have been repulsed,'' spokesman Rubasinghe's statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: government site, http://www.priu.gov.lk
</P>
<P>
   rebel sites, http://www.tamilnet.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.eelamweb.com
</P>
</TEXT>
