<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies' Brogna Breaks Left Wrist  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Philadelphia first baseman Rico Brogna was
placed in the 15-day disabled list Thursday with a broken left
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Brogna injured himself Wednesday when he was hit by a pitch from
Matt Blank in the ninth inning of the Phillies' 8-0 win over the
Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I got to the hospital and couldn't move it without it
hurting, I had a feeling it was broken,'' Brogna said. ''I still
hoped it wasn't, but I had that feeling. It was a different pain.
I've been hit before, but this was different.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogna returned to Philadelphia on Thursday with a cast on his
left arm that extended from his biceps to his hand. He will have
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's disappointing but right now there's nothing I can do but
wait until it heals,'' Brogna said. ''Hopefully I won't be out too
long so I can play a good portion of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury will likely sideline Brogna, 30, until the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's one of the best first basemen in the league,'' Phillies
manager Terry Francona said. ''I don't know if people realize it
but even when he's 0-for-4, he saves runs with his defense. And
that's really hard to replace.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Chris Pritchett was recalled from Triple-A
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in pretty good shape,'' Francona said. ''Brogna's one of
our best players. He's driven in 100 runs two years in a row and
his defense is as good as anybody's. He's an important part of our
team but we have guys -- Kevin Jordan filled in for Rolen last year
and Brian Hunter's here now, and Pritchett -- we'll just kind of mix
and match those guys and they'll do OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Francona said that calling up phenom Pat Burrell, who has been
playing left field for the Red Barons, wasn't an option at this
point.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's going to play some first in Triple-A now,'' Francona
said. ''But he's hitting .230. We all acknowledge he's going to be
a good player but bringing a kid before he's ready, that wouldn't
be a good move.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies have won five of seven to raise their record to
12-20. Brogna, hitting .246 and leading the team with 13 doubles,
was particularly disappointed with the timing of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tough because we were starting to get great pitching and
the hitting was coming around,'' Brogna said. ''In the upcoming
weeks I'll be around to encourage my teammates as much as
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
