<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hermanson Assumes Closer's Role  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- With their bullpen wracked by injuries, the
Montreal Expos have given staff ace Dustin Hermanson the
responsibility of closing out their games.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to know if I would be comfortable with it,'' said
Hermanson after he was approached by team officials to fill in for
injured closer Ugueth Urbina.
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson, who was scheduled to start Friday against Chicago's
Kerry Wood, was available out of the bullpen during Wednesday
night's 8-0 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they handled it well,'' Hermanson said. ''I thought it
wouldn't be a problem. I have the mentality of a closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Urbina, last year's NL saves leader with 41, will have an
arthrogram performed on his injured right elbow as soon as it can
be scheduled, possibly as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He felt pain in his right elbow after throwing his first pitch
while warming up during Tuesday night's 3-2 win. X-rays of the
elbow were taken the following day and an MRI was performed on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The MRI really was fairly clear,'' Expos general manager Jim
Beattie said following Thursday's 5-4 loss to the Phillies. ''They
didn't see much in there so he's going to be scheduled for an
arthrogram. Then based on that, it will tell us whether a surgical
procedure is necessary or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquired from Florida just before the beginning of the 1997
season, Hermanson was converted into a starter with Montreal. He
responded by going 14-11 with a 3.13 ERA in 1998. He led the staff
with 34 starts last season, despite going 9-14 with a 4.20 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson, who had no saves in 34 relief appearances with San
Diego from 1995-96, saved 21 games for Triple-A Las Vegas in 1996.
He has made 99 career starts, all with the Expos, and is 3-3 with a
4.81 ERA this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he is ready for it,'' Expos manager Felipe Alou said.
''He's set to go. He struggled his last two outings as a starter.
Whether the Urbina thing is serious or not, he's going to be
unavailable for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Urbina, 26, had bone chips removed from his right elbow in
December 1996 after experiencing pain while pitching in his native
Venezuela. He struck out the side while recording his eighth save
in his last outing, Sunday at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   The injury is the latest of a series that have plagued the
Expos' bullpen this season.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Lloyd, signed as a free agent be to Montreal's setup man,
hasn't pitched this season. He had arthroscopic surgery on his left
shoulder May 4 and won't return for at least three months.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Strickland, the Expos' current setup man, also had an MRI
performed on his injured right shoulder Thursday, which detected a
torn labrum. Strickland will have arthroscopic surgery next
Wednesday and is not expected to return this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hermanson's move to the bullpen moves Mike Thurman's season
debut up to Friday. Tony Armas Jr. will be recalled from Triple-A
Ottawa to start on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the biggest thing is adjusting my routine again,''
Hermanson said. ''I have an idea about how the routine goes. I
won't do anything extra. I won't go out like an animal and blow
myself out right away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0014 </TRAILER>
