<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lab Hazardous Materials Said Safe  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE KOIDIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- With a massive wildfire out of control
in Los Alamos, federal officials sought to assure the public
Thursday that the storied nuclear laboratory at the heart of the
town is safe, with explosives and plutonium stored in fireproof
bunkers and vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not an issue about national security or release of
radiation. That is not occurring,'' Sen. Jeff Bingaman said. ''The
lab is going to survive this in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The lab, however, did suffer some fire damage Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've lost a number of transportables,'' lab spokesman John
Gustafson said of trailers and portable buildings. ''No major
structures have been affected, and certainly none of them lost.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2,000 buildings dot mesas and canyons on the
43-square-mile property. The location, 35 miles northwest of Santa
Fe, was chosen by physicist J. Robert Oppenheimer because of its
remoteness and isolation.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for the first time since it was established in 1943,
the lab was shut down by fire. Only emergency personnel continued
to work. The lab has about 7,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   All 11,000 people in the town of Los Alamos, an outgrowth of the
lab, and another 7,000 in suburban White Rock fled as wildfires
swept through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Lab director John Browne said the blazes spread through an area
of the lab property where high explosives are stored in concrete
bunkers. And flames also jumped to within 300 yards of the
plutonium facility, said Kay Roybal, a spokeswoman for the lab.
</P>
<P>
   She added that firefighters kept the wildfires at bay by burning
nearby grasses to eliminate possible fuels, and that by afternoon
the flames had shifted.
</P>
<P>
   Gustafson said lab officials are monitoring air emissions for
radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took preliminary measurements ... and all those numbers
showed results consistent with background readings from natural
sources of radioactivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Rhoades, director of the lab's Bradbury Science Museum,
said the facilities are safer today than years ago; after a 1996
fire that charred 16,683 acres and reached the perimeter of the
lab's property, timber was removed from around structures and
firebreaks were constructed.
</P>
<P>
   He feels confident there is no way fire could reach into the
bunkers or vaults to ignite explosives or radioactive materials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're designed to withstand for something like four to six
hours a fire burning right on top of the building,'' Rhoades said.
''It's like trying to light a steel ballbearing on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Mello, executive director of the anti-nuclear Los Alamos
Study Group, said he does not fear a disaster but claimed
firefighters could inhale smoke tainted with chemicals. He said the
fire has swept over an area where uranium has been blown up in the
past and landed in the soil and trees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not know whether toxic materials have been burned,''
Mello said. ''It's possible, it's even likely to some extent, but
it's not something to be panicked about.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos is one of three government nuclear weapons labs under
the Energy Department; it is managed by the University of
California. More than half of its $1.26 billion annual budget goes
toward nuclear weapons programs, with the rest dedicated to
research in environmental cleanup, alternative energy sources and
biomedical sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Los Alamos has been used to design, develop and
test America's nuclear warheads. The key defense mission now is to
maintain the nuclear weapons stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos also has been the focus of a security and espionage
controversy stemming from the apparent loss of nuclear warhead
secrets to China in the 1980s. A lab scientist was fired last year
after being suspected of mishandling nuclear weapons secrets. He
has pleaded innocent to federal charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0027 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressmen, financier, but no Pataki eyeing Senate race  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amid speculation that Rudolph Giuliani may
scrap his Senate race against Hillary Clinton, potential Republican
alternatives, including at least two congressmen and a
near-billionaire, are waiting in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would seriously consider running,'' U.S. Rep. Peter King of
Long Island said Thursday. ''I've been making some phone calls and
doing some television appearances to get my name out there. If
there's some significant support, I'll definitely go.''
</P>
<P>
   King's fellow Long Island congressman, Rick Lazio, telephoned
state GOP Chairman William Powers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He asked if I would call him'' if Giuliani dropped out, Powers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a political adviser to Theodore Forstmann said the
Wall Street financier will also consider entering the race if the
New York City mayor gives it up. Forbes magazine estimated
Forstmann's net worth at $925 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Sue Kelly of Westchester County was mentioned as a
possible alternative, but showed little interest, while former
state Housing Commissioner Joseph Holland said ''it is something I
would seriously consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Not interested is Gov. George Pataki, insisted one of his top
political advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's already told everybody, no,'' Zenia Mucha said Thursday
when pressed on whether the governor might reconsider last week's
declaration that he wouldn't enter the race if Giuliani dropped
out. ''It's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, with polls indicating Pataki is by far the top
choice among Republicans to replace Giuliani and the strongest
candidate against Clinton, the governor will face pressure to
reconsider if GOP leaders need a new standardbearer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is suffering from prostate cancer and announced
Wednesday that he and his wife are discussing a possible
separation.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani continued to say Thursday he had made no decision
yet about the race, a senior Republican official close to the
mayor, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Giuliani was
leaning toward quitting the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''His heart, his soul, his body are not in this thing,'' said
the official.
</P>
<P>
   State GOP leaders denied making contingency plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Contrary to everybody else's popular belief, I believe he's
running,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our (state) convention is May 30,'' the state GOP chairman
added. ''I expect we'll come out of that convention with Rudy as
our candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, an early Giuliani
supporter who was worrying Tuesday that the mayor's marital woes
could hurt his Senate candidacy, said Thursday ''there are no plans
other than to support Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one senior adviser to state GOP leaders, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said contingency planning was underway
with the likely replacement candidate being Lazio, who already has
more than $3 million in his campaign coffers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm kind of at peace about this,'' Lazio said in Washington.
''I feel as if this is the mayor's decision. If it is meant to be,
it will be obvious. And, if it is not meant to be, that will be
obvious as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had, with Pataki's tacit approval, been pursuing the GOP
Senate nomination until August when the governor, under pressure
from national GOP leaders, threw his political muscle behind
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   King said Thursday that while he has only $600,000 in his
campaign account, whoever becomes the GOP candidate won't have to
worry much about money because of the anti-Hillary Clinton
sentiments nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann shouldn't have to worry about money. Forbes magazine's
latest list of the 400 richest Americans had him tied at No. 282.
His adviser, who asked not to be identified, said Fortsmann would
largely finance his own Senate campaign if he ran and that it would
focus on education issues.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann, 59, senior partner of Forstmann, Little &AMP; Co., has
been an advocate of educational alternatives such as school
vouchers. He and John T. Walton, an heir to the Wal-Mart fortune,
founded the Children's Scholarship Fund in 1998. Last year, it gave
out $160 million in scholarships to 40,000 families so their
children could attend private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Holland, under a cloud of personal financial problems, resigned
as Pataki's housing commissioner in 1996. He was one of the
administration's highest-ranking black officials. He is now a
private-practice lawyer, consultant and motivational speaker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0047 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court cautions against double-counting value of licenses  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's highest court has cautioned that
judges should not ''double count'' the value of professionals'
licenses when determining how to divide up the assets of divorcing
couples.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals made the admonition in a 6-0 ruling
Thursday that will be of intense interest to divorcing lawyers and
other licensed professionals in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The case before the judges concerned how the assets of lawyer
Harold Grunfeld and his wife Rochelle were divided when they
divorced in 1992 after 21 years of marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Rochelle Grunfeld, who stopped working as a teacher to raise the
couple's two children, was awarded half the value of the Park
Avenue law firm Harold Grunfeld founded, Grunfeld, Desiderio,
Lebowitz &AMP; Silverman. In addition to that asset, half of which was
valued at $1.29 million, Rochelle Grunfeld was also awarded $15,000
a month in alimony.
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court justice rejected Rochelle Grunfeld's attempt to
also get half the estimated value of her ex-husband's license to
practice law. But a midlevel appeals court later ruled that she was
indeed entitled to half the projected value of the license, winning
her another $773,500.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals said Rochelle Grunfeld was, in essence,
already collecting against the value of her ex's law license by
getting the $15,000 a month -- $180,000 a year -- in alimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the extent, then, that those same projected earnings used
to value the license also form the basis of an award of maintenance
(alimony), the licensed spouse is being twice charged with
distribution of the same marital asset value,'' the court said in a
ruling by Judge Howard Levine.
</P>
<P>
   The court sent the case back to the Supreme Court for a
recalculation of payments. It said Thursday it could not determine
how much of Harold Grunfeld's income came from sources other than
his law income, and it said the lower court should factor that into
the equation of how much he owes his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Rochelle Grunfeld's lawyer Franklin Bonem said the ruling was a
good one overall for his client.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wish we could have gotten 100 percent, but we got close to
it,'' Bonem said. ''We couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld's lawyer was out of the country Thursday and not
available to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The value of professional licenses in divorce matters are
determined by taking the average lifetime income of a college
graduate, comparing it with the higher average lifetime income of a
person licensed in a profession like the law or medicine, and
counting the difference as the value of the license. The age of the
people involved are also factored into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   In other rulings by the Court of Appeals Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   LEAD
</P>
<P>
   The court said the mother of a child in a lead paint poisoning
case should not have to undergo an IQ test to determine if
heredity, and not lead, caused defects in the child. However, the
court declined to issue a blanket rule saying IQ testing is
inappropriate in all such cases.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPERTY
</P>
<P>
   The court reversed a lower court ruling which determined that
investors Bluebird Partners, L.P., improperly bought up tens of
millions of dollars in bonds issued by Continental Airlines after
the airline filed for bankruptcy protection in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bluebird Partners sued United Jersey Bank for its conduct as
trustee for the airline bonds, saying the bank had violated its
fiduciary responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The bank countered that Bluebird Partners violated one of the
most venerable legal doctrines, namely one called ''champerty.''
''Champerty'' prohibits the buying and selling of rights in a law
suit, which United Jersey Bank said Bluebird Partners did by buying
the discounted Continental Airlines bonds with the intent of suing
the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals said it could not tell whether
champerty was committed by ''all this strategic jockeying and
financial positioning'' and it ordered a lower court to make that
determination.
</P>
<P>
   ''To say the least, a finding of champerty as a matter of law
might engender uncertainties in the free market system in
connection with untold numbers of sophisticated business
transactions,'' the court said, ''a not insignificant potentiality
in the state that harbors the financial capital of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
