<HEADLINE> Court decides mothers' IQ may be tested in some lead paint cases  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Landlords and municipalities fending off
certain lead paint lawsuits can require IQ tests of mothers to
determine whether lead-exposed children with mental problems are
victims of toxins or heredity, the state's highest court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   While deciding in favor of a Manhattan woman, saying she could
not be forced to take an intelligence exam, the Court of Appeals'
specified that it was not ruling out parental IQ testing in all
lead-poisoning cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each request must be evaluated on a case-by-case basis,''
Judge Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick wrote for the court. Five other
members of the panel concurred and Judge Joseph Bellacosa did not
take part in the ruling released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding to allow maternal IQ testing, the court rejected the
reasoning of a lower court which said the parents could not be
tested. The court cited New York's strong policy supporting open
disclosure and even said the woman's IQ was not confidential, just
not relevant or questionable in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling was against the landlord, it was seen as a
success for New York City and a powerful coalition of corporate and
insurance groups that sided with the apartment owner becauase it
did not deny IQ testing in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm heartened that the court left the door open,'' said
attorney Andrew Zajac, who filed a friend-of-the-court brief for
the Defense Association of New York. ''We think it's crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence examinations of mothers and other close relatives
are important to the city's defense in the 1,300 similar lead paint
claims it faces, it argued in a friend-of-the-court brief.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are gratified,'' said New York City counsel Margaret King.
''We would view this as a qualified victory.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the mother, Prudencia Andon, said she would now
move forward with her suit against 302-304 Mott Street Associates,
owner of the lower Manhattan apartment building where she lived.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Andon claimed her then 1-year-old son, Antonio, had
learning disabilities, delayed speech and language, and behavioral
problems because of lead paint in the apartment. The arguments over
the IQ test were brought up in pretrial motions.
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court had ruled that an IQ test could be
administered. But the Appellate Division had reversed that ruling,
saying that the test would raise questions that would long delay
the case's resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Andon's attorney Alexander Wulwick had argued that forcing the
IQ test on the mother would ''extend to the hotly debated question
of whether and to what degree, IQ is inherited ... with each side
producing competing experts'' on nature vs. nurture.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling also agreed that the landlord's expert
witness, a doctor, did not offer enough evidence to support his
opinion that the mother's IQ was ''extremely relevant'' in this
case.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Trial Lawyers Association had weighed in on
the case on behalf of the mother. That group did not return a call
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   About three-quarters of housing built before 1978 contains
lead-based paint, the Environmental Protection Agency says. If not
maintained, the federal agency said, the paint can lead, especially
in young children, to permanent brain, nervous system and kidney
damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0047 </TRAILER>
