<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox Chief Thoman Fired  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Thirteen months after stepping down as
chief executive of Xerox, Paul A. Allaire is stepping back into the
job.
</P>
<P>
   The move was announced Thursday following the firing of CEO Rick
Thoman.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman, 55, a former chief financial officer at IBM, was hired
as the No. 2 executive at Xerox in June 1997. A cost-cutter who
helped reverse IBM's declining fortunes, he was seen as a leader
who could help Xerox regain its dominant position in the small and
large office machine markets.
</P>
<P>
   But since his arrival, Xerox has struggled with slumping sales
and a balky sales force restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman was asked by members of the board of directors to resign,
a source familiar with Thursday's events told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox spokeswoman Christa Carone would not comment on Thoman's
departure. The company released a statement after the stock market
closed Thursday saying the board had accepted Thoman's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said Allaire would take the job back on an interim basis.
He has also agreed to remain as chairman for two years, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
   The board promoted Anne M. Mulcahy, a 24-year Xerox veteran who
is now president of the company's general markets division, to
president and chief operating officer, and nominated her for
election to the board to replace Thoman.
</P>
<P>
   Carone would not say whether Mulcahy is being groomed for the
CEO job. But she acknowledged that there is no search for a
permanent CEO and no successiarge of $625 million to
cover the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Before extraordinary charges, Xerox had quarterly earnings of
$220 million, or 30 cents per share, down 36 percent compared with
$343 million, or 48 cents per share, a year earlier. Revenues in
the quarter rose 3 percent to $4.43 billion, up from $4.30 billion
in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, best known for its copiers, has struggled against
Hewlett-Packard and Canon in the small and home-office markets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts differed on whether Thoman was to blame for the
company's slide or whether he became the fall guy for problems that
started before he took over.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Enderlin, an analyst at Ryan, Beck-Southeast, said Thoman
made some good moves, including the acquisition of Tektronix Inc.'s
color printer division, rolling out new products and broadening
distribution channels. But he said Thoman's departure might be a
good move for the company.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to imagine things going worse for them at this
point,'' he said. ''Xerox has always had a sort of bureaucratic
culture and I think Thoman sort of imbedded that rather than trying
to overcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said Thoman was simply unable to overcome the company's
sluggishness in moving from an old-style copier company to a
digital business machines maker.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kmetz, an analyst at IDC, a market research and consulting
firm in Framingham, Mass., said Thoman was clearly hired to make
Xerox a digital player, with digital copiers, printers,
multi-function fax machines and inkjet devices.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he had ideas on how to do that ... but obviously, it
didn't work out for the best,'' Kmetz said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the company seems to be correcting problems
associated with the realignment of its sales force along industry
lines rather than geographical boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no question that Xerox is going to rally from this at
some point down the road, but they've got a lot of work to do,''
Kmetz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're playing in a market where their bread and butter has
been the copier world ... Now, it's a matter of organizing the
company so it can be lean and mean in the digital marketplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0047 </TRAILER>
