<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford: SUVs Pose Hazards  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Ford Motor Co., in a startling admission, says
sport utility vehicles are environmentally unfriendly, chug gas and
can be a danger to drivers in smaller vehicles. The automaker also
said its high-profit business in SUVs doesn't always jibe with its
desire to be more environmentally responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The critical comments were delivered in a book given to
shareholders who attended Ford's annual meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a 98-page book, ''Connecting With Society,'' the company
concedes that SUVs burn more gas and emit more pollution than cars
and can pose a danger to smaller vehicles in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford admits that ''with a few exceptions, its products are not
industry leaders in fuel economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The book even quotes a Sierra Club press release that ''the
gas-guzzling SUV is a rolling monument to environmental
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We take our social responsibility seriously,'' Ford chairman
William Clay Ford Jr. said after the meeting. ''Our approach to
SUVs and the environment has not always been responsible, but now
we're in the leading position.''
</P>
<P>
   The automaker's SUVs were the major engine behind the company's
record profits of $7.2 billion last year; some models can carry
profit margins of nearly $15,000. Demand for several models,
including the hulking Excursion, has almost outpaced supply.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker said the book was part of the company's effort to
be more ''transparent'' about the problems its facing and it's
proposed solutions. The book also promotes several environmentally
friendly steps made by the automaker, such as making its SUVs meet
low-emission standards and increasing the number of recyclable
parts.
</P>
<P>
   But William Clay Ford Jr. and Jac Nasser, the company's
president and CEO, said the company would continue to build and
market SUVs to meet customer demand. They said that if the
automaker limited its SUV sales in the name of environmental
concerns, competitors would simply pick up more customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're never going to please everybody,'' Ford said. ''But we
do pledge to work on it. ... Our customers love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Nasser also said the company would announce changes
today at its Dagenham, England factory, which employs over 6,000
workers. They declined to give specifics, but said the company
would take a charge against earnings. Workers there have feared the
company would close its assembly operations, cutting thousands of
jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0048 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Telergy going public to raise $250 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Telergy Inc. has formally declared its
intention to raise $250 million in an initial public stock
offering, the first step toward becoming a public company.
</P>
<P>
   The stock offering is intended to provide the 5-year-old DeWitt
company with money to continue building its telecommunications
network, to expand its sales force and possibly to acquire other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Timing of the sale is uncertain, but it is expected this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Telergy is preparing for an IPO after two months of turbulence
in the stock markets that has resulted in many stocks losing value
and IPOs being postponed or canceled.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts think the long-term outlook for
telecommunications companies is generally strong, in part because
it provides the infrastructure for the growing Internet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Telergy's preliminary prospectus, filed late Wednesday with the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission, did not indicate how many
shares the company will sell, or at what price. The document also
does not indicate what percentage of the company's total stock will
be represented by the IPO. Some 3.38 million shares have been
issued to employees and private investors.
</P>
<P>
   SEC rules forbid company officials from elaborating on their
written report to regulators. Details are expected to be submitted
in future documents.
</P>
<P>
   The document does not require Telergy to make the IPO final by
any particular date, or at all.
</P>
<P>
   Telergy was founded in 1995 by brothers Brian, Kevin and William
Kelly. By joining forces with utility companies -- first Niagara
Mohawk Power Corp., then others -- Telergy obtained rights to build
a fiber-optic network along the poles and underground transmission
routes controlled by the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Telergy owns a network of fiber-optic cables and
telecommunications equipment that extends 1,800 miles in New York,
New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Maryland and Washington, D.C. The company
uses its network to provide a wide array of services, from simple
voice calls to high-tech video streaming and data storage.
</P>
<P>
   After the IPO, Telergy plans to finish building its network by
the end of 2001. At that point, it will cover about 3,200 miles in
an area from Washington, D.C., to Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   According to the document filed Wednesday, each of the Kelly
brothers owns about 480,000 shares, or about 14 percent, of the
company's outstanding common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Other major individual shareholders include former Avis
executive and state Republican Party chairman J. Patrick Barrett,
the company president, who has an option to acquire 6.8 percent of
the outstanding shares, and director Frank Zaccanelli, a minority
owner of the NBA's Dallas Mavericks, who has an option to acquire
4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other individual investors include John O'Mara, former state
Public Service Commission chairman, who serves as a director and
has options to acquire 30,000 shares of Telergy stock. Terence
McAuliffe, one of President Clinton's top fund-raisers, serves as a
director and owns or has warrants to acquire 12,728 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Opinac North America, a subsidiary of Niagara Mohawk, has
invested $40 million in Telergy and owns 13 percent of the stock
outstanding. Global Crossing also has invested $40 million, and
owns 14.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company lists assets of about $219.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Telergy had 1999 revenues of $7.9 million, and posted a net loss
of $62.9 million. Since its inception in 1995, the company has had
net losses of about $105.5 million, according to documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0049 </TRAILER>
