<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Henry Nicols remembered for his humor and his heroism  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- He spoke out about AIDS when few others
would. He touched millions with his courage. And he never stopped
smiling through all the ups and downs of his all-too-brief life.
</P>
<P>
   For the compassion, humor and grace that Henry Nicols
demonstrated in the face of tragedy, the Eagle Scout who boldly
told the world nine years ago that he had AIDS was honored Thursday
at his emotionally draining funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's overwhelming grief at the loss of my only son, my
youngest child,'' his father, Hank, said, his voice breaking as he
spoke. ''It is, I think, impossible to imagine this grief. It's the
most difficult thing I've ever done, and much more difficult than
the most difficult thing I ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yet at the same time, there's a sense of overwhelming love and
support,'' he said. ''Our friends, our community, the world --
everyone has been so good to us. Henry was dealt a very difficult
hand. I think he played it as best he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicols, 26, died Monday from injuries he suffered in a car
accident two weeks ago. He had contracted the dreaded HIV virus
that causes AIDS during a 1984 blood transfusion to treat his
hemophilia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The loss is especially new, so fresh, so recent that it's
overwhelming,'' his sister, Jennifer, said in her eulogy. ''He
touched so many lives, gave so much hope and understanding. Today
we're able to see the dividends. It's tragic that his life was cut
so short, but while he was with us he was like Peter Pan. He was
magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicols began to deliver that magic at age 17, turning heads with
his announcement March 8, 1991 that he had full-blown AIDS. It was
a time when relatively few people knew much about the virus, and
fewer still knew anyone infected with it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can say he made anything safe, he made it safe for
people to have AIDS,'' said Bill Cramer, a local scoutmaster. ''He
took it in his teeth and he ran with it at a time when people were
running for cover.''
</P>
<P>
   And he never stopped, traveling the world to promote AIDS
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of doctors thought it was pretty grim,'' his other
sister, Diana, said. ''They thought he would just get AIDS and die.
He used to joke that he had the life expectancy of a hamster.''
</P>
<P>
   The funeral mass, which was tinged with a sense of wonderment,
was attended by scores of boy scouts, family and friends -- more
than 300 people in all. They packed every corner of the small red
brick church where Henry was baptized to celebrate his memorable
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''Henry Nicols accomplished, in a few years, work that is
exceptional, helping to change attitudes and turn fear, ignorance
and prejudice into understanding and compassion for people
afflicted with AIDS,'' Friar John Roos said. ''Henry has climbed
many mountains, and he's overcome mountains of adversity and
misfortune, very high mountains that would really have brought
discomfort to most of us. That merits from all of us deep
admiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicols, who was an avid mountaineer, dedicated his Eagle Scout
community service project to educating people about HIV and AIDS,
always rejecting the label of ''innocent victim.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Henry was the brother I never had,'' 18-year-old boy scout
Michael Henrici said, tears welling in his eyes. ''He's not gone as
long as we remember everything he taught us.''
</P>
<P>
   And although Henry was hospitalized repeatedly, he never lost
hope and never stopped planning for the future. He even had it
figured out that he would be old enough to run for president in
2008 and told a group of seventh-graders during an AIDS lecture
that he planned on it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Henry never planned to die,'' Hank Nicols said. ''Even though
he had a terminal illness that could be devastating, he lived life.
Every single day was very important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, at a brief graveside ceremony, Nicols was laid to
rest on a hillside overlooking Otsego Lake. As a bugler played
taps, Henrici folded the American flag that had been draped over
the oaken coffin and handed it to Henry's parents.
</P>
<P>
   A lone bagpiper off in the distance then began to play the hymn
''Amazing Grace'' as a dozen of Henry's mountain-climbing buddies
slowly lowered his casket into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   That brought more tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''I''m glad that we had those 11 days to reflect,'' Hank Nicols
said of his son's final days in the hospital. ''The last day, which
was the most difficult, we were all with him. We could pet him and
touch him and tell him that we loved him. We were with him when he
died, and there was a great deal of comfort in that.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we did not bury my son today. We buried his body and he's
dead. But I think the good that he's done and the good that he's
continuing to do is what's important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0049 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conditions Sought in Time-AOL Deal  </HEADLINE>
By LOUINN LOTA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. is asking federal
regulators to require America Online and Time Warner to agree to
provide other Internet service providers access to their high-speed
cable lines as a condition of approval of their merger.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's request was part of a filing on the proposed merger
Thursday with the Federal Communications Commission Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Disney is not opposing the proposed merger. We do think the
Federal Communications Commission should impose meaningful and
enforceable conditions ... and rather than vague promises of open
access, we think that spelling out what is acceptable and
unacceptable is vital in this proposed merger so that consumers
know what they're getting,'' said Disney spokesman John Dreyer.
</P>
<P>
   He said the open access question was specifically aimed at
keeping high-speed broadband lines, which are able to distribute
Internet video, sound and data simultaneously, open to competing
content providers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators have refused to broach the issue of mandatory
sharing of cable companies' high-speed lines.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, companies that want access to cable companies'
high-speed lines must negotiate agreements with them. The cable
industry favors continuation of this voluntary approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''This really is about what happens when there is broadband
distribution of content, full broadband that is interactive. What
if there's only one cable provider where you live? With broadband,
there won't be full competition,'' Dreyer said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's cable systems include WB Network, Warner Bros.
Studios, cable networks and print media holdings. AOL is the
nation's largest Internet Service Provider.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, AOL said the companies have made clear that
their ''commitment to open access and content diversity couldn't be
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies ''are also committed to offering consumers a broad
choice of the best content available regardless of who produces it,
and to distributing our own content as widely as possible on as
many platforms as possible regardless of affiliation,'' the
statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
