<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defeated But Not Down  </HEADLINE>
By ERICA BULMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Following a 4-1 quarterfinal
elimination at the hands of Slovakia, the United States came off
the ice defeated but not down.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that was on the brink of relegation into the world
hockey 'B' pool only two years ago, the United States' undefeated
march to the World Hockey Championships quarterfinals was in itself
a significant exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course it's disappointing when you play the whole
tournament without losing one game, then bam! you're out,'' said
Calgary Flames defenseman Phil Housley, the NHL's career American
scoring leader. ''But that was the only negative thing of the whole
tournament. We were strong, we played great and we're still proud.
There's nothing to be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   ''We turned some heads here and it's definitely one of the best
showings the USA has ever had here,'' Housley said. ''I told the
guys for us to hold our heads high. We went almost undefeated. We
beat the Russians and the Swedes at the 2000 world championships.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the team finished fifth, one spot up from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Having beaten both the star-studded, though ill-fated, Russian
team 3-0 as well as 1998 world champion Sweden 5-3, and holding a
4-0-2 record, the U.S. team thought a medal of some color was
awaiting. And the Americans appeared to be on the road to success
when they scored the opening goal in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   But their hopes were snuffed when the tough Slovaks gained an
important, decisive psychological edge, scoring three times in less
than four minutes to take a 3-1 lead in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Disheartened and incapable of answering, the United States saw
all its hard work and success suddenly go for naught.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough loss, the Americans left the newly built Ice
Palace with optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years ago, the United States made headlines after
leaving the worlds beaten, bruised and on the brink of relegation
to the international 'B' pool.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the team grabbed attention for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   Playing disciplined, organized hockey, coach Lou Vairo's squad
displayed the cohesion and team spirit that helped make up for the
lack of stars.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a good group of players where no one stood out,'' said
Housley. ''There were no Dennis the Menaces, no stars. We came
together as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone was skilled and everyone could skate and handle the
puck, which is important in a tournament like this. And there were
a lot of scouts and GMs watching and it should help all their
careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Americans, finished sixth after the NHL's top
stars turned down an invitation to play.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, with few exceptions, the United States' best
players skipped the annual championship in Europe or couldn't make
it because their teams were still locked into the Stanley Cup
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So the Americans ended up with 13 NHL grinders, and filled out
the lineup with minor, college and European league players.
</P>
<P>
   But unconcerned by the lack of big names on the team, Vairo
refused to consider trading in those players who led the United
States to the quarterfinals with NHL players newly eliminated from
the Stanley Cup playoffs, as the tournament's rules allow.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a big factor in our good performance,'' Hendrickson
said. ''He wasn't going to trade us in. We had the feeling this was
our tournament, our chance to make it big, our chance at the title.
</P>
<P>
   ''And it made us stronger and tighter as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of solidarity that was sadly lacking in the
Russian team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had what the Russians didn't have and that was cohesion,''
said Vancouver Canuck Darby Hendrickon. ''We played as a team. We
played with heart.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the best and I won't be leaving here with bitterness or
regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a performance U.S. hockey badly needed.
</P>
<P>
   Following their stunning victory over Canada in the final of the
inaugural World Cup of Hockey in Montreal in September 1996,
Americans in international hockey had been caught in a slow,
downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   With virtually an identical team from the World Cup playing at
the Nagano Games, the United States failed to medal, and sullied
its image by trashing rooms in the Olympic Village following its
quarterfinal elimination by the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, no Olympians went to Switzerland for the
world championships and the players who did go sustained a string
of embarrassments, including a humiliating 4-0 loss to Italy, a
team with no NHL players, and an unprecedented 3-1 round-robin
defeat by France.
</P>
<P>
   Losing in the relegation round, the United States was forced to
compete in a last-chance tournament the following autumn in order
to claw its way back into the 'A' pool.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has won the championships twice since they
began in 1920. They last medaled in Vienna in 1996, when they took
the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a disappointing outcome, because I think we deserved a
medal,'' Housley said. ''But we talked in the locker room and we
feel good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurst Takes Two-Stroke LPGA Lead  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) -- Kristal Parker can only hope she can
ignore the pain in her neck for three more days.
</P>
<P>
   Parker woke up Wednesday morning with a recurrence of the
sciatica that first developed in 1998 during a pregnancy. She
headed to the LPGA Tour's health center for treatment, then waited
until 40 minutes before her tee time in the final group of
Thursday's opening round before deciding to play.
</P>
<P>
   She played through pain that came every time a club struck the
ground and shot a 5-under 67 in the new Electrolux USA
Championship, tied with Cindy Figg-Currier two strokes behind
leader Pat Hurst (65).
</P>
<P>
   ''For the most part, I was just trying to keep it positive; mind
over matter kind of mentality out there,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Mallon, who won the final Sara Lee Classic in Nashville last
year, was among six players at 69. Karrie Webb was eight strokes
back with a 73 in her attempt to win her fifth LPGA tournament and
seventh title this year after winning in Japan last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The pain hit Parker last week, forcing her to withdraw from the
Phillips Invitational. Parker, whose best tour finish was second in
1996, played a practice round at The Legends Club's Ironhorse
Course on Tuesday only to have trouble swinging during practice on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After deciding to play, she didn't waste any time and birdied
five of the first nine holes. She had her chances to catch Hurst,
but bogeyed the par-4 sixth when her second shot went right and she
couldn't get up and down.
</P>
<P>
   Parker got the stroke back on the next hole when her chip hit
the pin, leaving her a tap-in birdie. She missed a chance to pull
within a stroke when she left a 15-foot putt short.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the pain, Parker happily took her 67, which matched
her best score this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I probably had about six or seven swings out there in a lot of
pain,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She headed straight to the health center for more treatment and
Advil. Whether she can avoid her third cut of the year or survive
until Sunday is in God's hands, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Usually, the only way I get rid of it is rest it, and that's
obviously not going to come right now,'' Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst showed she has nearly recovered her stroke following the
birth of her first child last June. On a day where gusting winds
slowed play and forced golfers to move up at least a club or two,
Hurst had what she called nearly a perfect day with six birdies, an
eagle and a bogey for her lowest round this year.
</P>
<P>
   The draw is almost gone, and she's back to the fade she prefers.
A change to a crosshanded grip has helped her putting the past
month. She is visualizing shots better, as well, and admits it was
too soon when she came back to the tour less than two months after
giving birth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mentally and physically, I just wasn't there yet,'' Hurst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst has shown flashes this year of the golfer who won her
first major in 1998 at the Nabisco Dinah Shore and had 11 top-10
finishes. She had her best finish at the Welch's/Circle K
Championship with every round in the 60s as she came in second
behind Annika Sorenstam.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a matter of getting the putts to drop,'' she said.
Divots: When Webb finished her round, she walked past reporters
without talking. ... Cindy McCurdy withdrew Wednesday night when a
case of viral meningitis that sickened her earlier this year
returned. McCurdy, who had played the past two weeks, went to a
hospital in Atlanta. ... Becky Iverson withdrew after six holes due
to illness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0105 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Seeks 1st Playoff Road Win  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- The last time the Los Angeles Lakers went on the
road in the playoffs, it was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   They will try to erase the memory of that ugly trip to
Sacramento tonight when they play the Phoenix Suns in Game 3 of the
Western Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a great team and two great, great players,'' Suns
coach Scott Skiles said. ''I feel they would like to get this thing
over with. They had the experience in Sacramento where they went
there and Sac put two on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like they're going to come here and want to get this
one and get a big leg up, and then maybe get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers lost those two in Sacramento to force a deciding Game
5 of their first-round series, a game Los Angeles won handily.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns already have put a scare into the Lakers, losing 97-96
in Game 2 Wednesday night on Kobe Bryant's 15-footer with 2.6
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   That put Los Angeles up 2-0 in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who has averaged 37.5 points and 17 rebounds
in the two victories, said a split of the two games in Phoenix
would be good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as we can get one of these games, we'll be happy,''
O'Neal said. ''If we can get two of the games, it will be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix rallied in the fourth quarter to nearly beat the Lakers
with tight full-court defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't have a lot of ball-handlers,'' the Suns' Penny
Hardaway said. ''Even Kobe isn't a terrific ball-handler. We just
have to put the pressure on them and take them out of their rhythm,
not let them just come down and pass and cut. Then it becomes a
different ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson said many of his team's fourth-quarter
miscues in Game 2 were self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Three of the turnovers we had were completely unforced,''
Jackson said. ''Yes, their pressure defense activated them, got
them motivated. Can they do it for 48 minutes?''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles said no, ''we have to pick our spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway was still shaking his head that no foul was called
against O'Neal on the Suns' next-to-last possession in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've gone over in my mind a million times what would have
happened if they'd call that foul or if I'd taken the baseline when
I had it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were leading 96-95 when Hardaway drove to the basket
and O'Neal, his old teammate in Orlando, stood in the way. Hardaway
said O'Neal hit him in the shoulder, causing him to lose control of
the ball as he shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the MVP. He just had received the trophy before the
game,'' Hardaway said. ''There was a lot of pressure on the refs
not to make that call even though it was a foul. Hopefully we'll
get that call when we're here at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The foul wasn't flagrant enough for the officials to make it in
front of the pro-Lakers crowd at that point in the game, Hardaway
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the first quarter, that call would be made, easy,''
Hardaway said. But late in the game, ''you'd have to get your head
taken off or knocked to the floor or something so the fans won't
react to it if they call it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles said videotape showed it was obviously a foul.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's frustrating, but all year long we've had a hard time
getting to the foul line for whatever reason,'' Skiles said.
''Maybe that reputation is hurting us or something. That's clearly
a foul, but it's just one of those things.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Lakers can point to plays that clearly are fouls on us.
It's not like there's a conspiracy or anything. It was just, in my
opinion, a call that should have been called and was missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix guard Jason Kidd, who played 43 minutes with no ill
effects on his surgically repaired left ankle, said he felt fine,
but a little tired, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles said the strong fourth quarter should provide some
momentum for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly we were right there, and if a phenomenal player
wouldn't have made a great play, we would have won the game,''
Skiles said. ''Kobe made a great, great shot. Hopefully our guys
take something out of that.
</P>
<P>
   ''NBA basketball is not a place where you take away moral
victories. You win or you lose. It's as simple as that. We lost and
yet the guys have a real positive feeling this morning. I think the
guys in that locker room believe and feel that they're going to win
the series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
