<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With a smile and a serious side, Egan takes Manhattan  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Newly-designated Archbishop Edward Egan recalled
his first encounter with Cardinal John O'Connor inside St.
Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor joked that he was unimpressed by Egan's fluency in
several languages.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cardinal said, 'He speaks Italian, French and all of
this,''' Egan recounted Thursday. ''Then he said, 'I'm going to
give him six months to learn our language.'''
</P>
<P>
   Egan, speaking hours after Pope John Paul II named him as head
of the New York Archdiocese, demonstrated his conversance in New
York-ese during his first meeting with the local media.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing a dry Irish wit with conservative church doctrine, Egan
arrived Thursday to assume the mantle of the late cardinal and the
spiritual leadership of 2.4 million followers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody told me there would be a few microphones here,'' Egan
deadpanned as he stood before a bank of cameras at his first news
conference. ''I love New York understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   The gray-haired, balding Egan, dressed in black with a simple
white cleric's collar, joked with reporters in the Cathedral High
School gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   But he turned serious when asked about the issues confronting
him as occupant of the Catholic Church's highest-profile U.S.
pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   On abortion and birth control, the 68-year-old Egan predictably
backed Pope John Paul II's opposition to both. Asked by a Vatican
radio reporter if he would be pro-life, Egan said emphatically,
''Without any question, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal also expressed optimism that he would not close any
of the archdiocese's schools, a question raised because he had
reorganized the Catholic schools during his 12 years in Bridgeport,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, who is to be installed June 19, becomes the 12th man to
lead New York's Catholics. He received generally positive reviews
from those who know him.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an imposing figure and a great preacher,'' said Monsignor
Timothy Dolan, an American who heads the North American Pontifical
College in Rome. Noting the similarity to O'Connor, Dolan added,
''When Ed Egan walks into a room, he doesn't go unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pieczynski, spokeswoman for the Chicago-based church
reform group Call to Action, described Egan as ''very
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is that he is very personable, but also very
rigid in his approach to issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, who spent 12 years leading 367,000 people in the diocese
of Bridgeport, stopped by St. Patrick's Cathedral on Thursday
afternoon and led a small group of visitors in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of about 40 people applauded the newly-named
archbishop, who offered his thanks in English and Spanish.
''Thanks,'' he said. ''Thanks a million.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan, praising his predecessor, said he hoped to gain the same
New York acceptance that the Philadelphia-born O'Connor had
achieved during his 16 years. O'Connor, 80, died last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you there is no place in the world that is quicker
to accept someone who wants to be a New Yorker,'' said Egan, who
worked in the New York Archdiocese earlier in his career. ''I want
to be a New Yorker, and I guess I am officially one.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan, born in Oak Park, Ill., studied theology at Rome's
prestigious Gregorian Pontifical University. He served from 1971 to
1985 on the Vatican tribunal that decides important juridical
matters, including whether to grant annulments.
</P>
<P>
   He took over the Bridgeport diocese in 1988, winning acclaim for
reorganizing diocesan schools and recruiting local men into the
priesthood. He was able to raise millions of dollars in his annual
bishop's appeal in the diocese, which embraces Fairfield County,
one of the richest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Egan came under fire for defending the Bridgeport diocese
against more than two dozen lawsuits over alleged sexual
molestation by local priests. Although all but one of the cases
preceded Egan's arrival, they raised embarrassing questions over
whether abuse was covered up.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, even when he stumbled slightly,
Egan remained at ease. Unsure of the etiquette during his question
and answer period, he paused briefly before cracking a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel like the boss,'' he said. ''But give me a little
time and I will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0108 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
