<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Take Homecourt Advantage  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- About to begin their sixth playoff game, the New
York Knicks feel they haven't been totally sharp yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had spurts, but we haven't been sharp for 48 minutes,''
Latrell Sprewell said as the Knicks prepared for Game 3 of their
best-of-seven series with Miami tied 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   New York swept the Toronto Raptors in the first round, but all
the games were decided in the final minute as the Knicks never put
together what they would consider their ''A'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Heat, they have struggled in the fourth quarters of
both games -- failing to score a field goal in the final five
minutes of Game 1 and watching a double-digit lead dissolve toward
the end of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had periods in both games where we've played well and
terrible. A lot of that is their defense and them knowing us, and
it's the same with us,'' Sprewell said. ''It's going to be that way
in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams' familiarity with each other comes from spending four
straight seasons meeting in the playoffs. For the past three years,
Miami has come to New York in need of a road win and got one each
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat are 3-4 at Madison Square Garden in the playoffs since
1997, which hardly qualifies as statistical evidence of a
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're a good team,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said
Thursday, ''and good teams can win anywhere they play. That's
really what it says.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Heat faced elimination in Game 4 at the Garden,
but outscored the Knicks 29-10 in the fourth quarter to force a
deciding Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The previous year, the series was tied 1-1 when Miami came to
New York and won Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1997, the Heat took Game 6 on New York's home court as
Patrick Ewing, Allan Houston and Charlie Ward sat out with
suspensions stemming from a fight in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being at home only does so much. It won't win the game for
you,'' Houston said. ''They know that, and they just have to put
themselves in position to win. We have to take advantage of it by
protecting it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will again try to contain Alonzo Mourning by trying
to keep him from setting up deep in the low post. They did so in
Game 2 by hindering him as he ran upcourt, putting bodies in his
way to give Ewing a chance to sprint upcourt and get in between
Mourning and the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks also expect to continue to see double-teams whenever
their two primary scorers, Houston and Sprewell, have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Houston shot 3-for-14 and Sprewell was 2-for-13 in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have to pick up the scoring a little bit, but every time
they're touching the ball they're getting double-teamed,'' Knicks
forward Marcus Camby said. ''Usually when a guy is the first
option, he's not going to get the shot against Miami. They force
other players to make shots, and the rest of us have to knock down
shots for us to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat will look for better games out of their point guards,
the hobbled Tim Hardaway and rookie Anthony Carter. Miami also must
do better at the free-throw line after going 19-for-33 in Game 2,
including eight straight misses early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, free-throw accuracy is no barometer of success for
the Heat -- especially in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3 of their first-round series against the Knicks in
1998, Miami led by four points with 1:23 left and proceeded to miss
seven of eight free throws the rest of the way. The Heat won
anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0109 </TRAILER>
