<HEADLINE> 'Cats' Extended Until Sept. 10  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The longest-running show on Broadway will be
around a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cats'' originally was scheduled to end its record-breaking
engagement at the Winter Garden Theater on June 25. But it will now
close Sept. 10, the musical's spokesman, Bill Evans, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The final performance, No. 7,485, will be by invitation only.
</P>
<P>
   Since the original closing was announced in February, weekly
ticket sales for the Andrew Lloyd Webber musical have more than
doubled, with the show often playing to full houses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cats'' opened Oct. 7, 1982, and became Broadway's
longest-running show in June 1997, surpassing ''A Chorus Line,''
which ran for 6,137 performances, from 1975 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The show, based on T.S. Eliot's ''Old Possum's Book of Practical
Cats,'' is still playing in London, where it opened in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cats'' was the first of the big British musicals with lavish
settings and pop scores to invade Broadway in the 1980s. It earned
a fortune for Lloyd Webber and producer Cameron Mackintosh, who
went on to bring ''Les Miserables,'' ''The Phantom of the Opera''
and ''Miss Saigon'' to Broadway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0033 </DOCNO>
