<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Disparities Persist in Health  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Though more women are seeking early prenatal
care, a new study shows that black and Hispanic women are less
likely to see a doctor in the early stages of pregnancy, leading to
more health problems for minority mothers and their infants.
</P>
<P>
   White women are twice as likely as blacks and Hispanics to see a
doctor in the first few months of pregnancy, according to a study
released Thursday by the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   A CDC review of 13 states showed that in 1997, the percentage of
babies born to mothers whose first medical exam was more than three
months into their pregnancy was 27.7 percent for black women, 26.3
for Hispanic women and 12.1 percent for white women.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, a CDC analysis of U.S. births showed the number of
women who delayed prenatal care or did not seek care declined from
25 percent in 1989 to 18 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Women who don't see a doctor until after the first three months
of pregnancy risk complications such as premature delivery and low
birth-weight babies, CDC epidemiologist Suzanne Zane said.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes, high blood pressure, infections, clotting and bleeding
need to be caught early to avoid health problems that can kill, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement may be partly due to an expansion of Medicaid in
the mid-1980s that made it possible for more women to pay a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Of the women who did not see a doctor early on, the most
frequent explanation was that they did not know they were pregnant.
Inability to pay and lack of health insurance were also significant
factors.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Surgeon General David Satcher called for research
into why the gap persists. He pointed out that black women are
nearly four times as likely to die of pregnancy-related causes as
white women.
</P>
<P>
   ''Studies estimate that at least half of these deaths are
preventable based on current medical knowledge,'' Satcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention:
http://www.cdc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0113 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Hope To Join Elite Group  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The Colorado Avalanche understand what the Dallas
Stars are trying to do. Four years ago, they were the defending
Stanley Cup champions hoping to join the elite group of repeat
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Saturday, the Avalanche will be the next-to-last
obstacle in the Stars' quest for a second straight title when the
teams meet in the opener of the best-of-seven Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a one-time champion and a multiple winner
is immense. Being on top of a sport for two years or more brands a
club as truly special and not just a group that got hot at the
right time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not many teams can say they won back-to-back Cups,'' said
center Joe Nieuwendyk, who won a Cup with Calgary in 1989 then
again with Dallas a decade later. ''That's the biggest challenge
for us. We've put together a good team and we'd like to ride this
as far as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock is using the phrase ''two-time
champion'' as a dangling carrot to motivate his team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure Colorado feels the same way, because when you win
once, you see the stuff that goes with the Edmontons and the
Detroits and the New York Islanders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you win a couple times, there's a certain status that
goes with that. I mean, they still call Detroit a championship
team, but they haven't been there for two years. So, that's what
we're looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, though, has said his team is the underdog because
Colorado is playing so well. Avalanche coach Bob Hartley sees some
gamesmanship in that comment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tough to say you're playing the underdog when you're
playing the Stanley Cup champions,'' he said. ''This year, they had
another season over 100 points. I think he's just trying to play a
little mind game.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Dallas doesn't win it all, the Stars can't be written
off as a one-year wonder. This is their third straight year in the
conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   They beat the Avalanche last year in a thrilling seven-game
series, then beat Buffalo for the first title in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas and Colorado have advanced this far by going 6-0 at home
and splitting their road games. The Stars went through the bottom
two seeded teams (Edmonton and San Jose), while the Avalanche faced
tougher foes in Phoenix and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The series all get tougher as you go along in the playoffs, so
it's going to be that much tougher for us than it was against
Detroit,'' Colorado center Peter Forsberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive titles used to be the norm in the NHL. From 1974-88,
the Cup was shared by only four clubs and all but one of their
titles was followed by another.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia did it in '74-75, then Montreal and the New York
Islanders each won four straight. Wayne Gretzky led Edmonton to
four championships the next five years, with the Canadiens
interrupting the streak. Since then, Mario Lemieux's Pittsburgh
clubs won in '91-92 and Detroit did it in '97-98.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano was in his second season when the then-Minnesota
North Stars lost to the Penguins in the 1991 finals. It took nearly
nine seasons to get back to the finals, so he fully appreciates
what it would mean to be two-time champs.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'd like to ride the wave as long as possible because you
don't know when the tide is going to turn in your organization and
changes are going to be made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't know when you're going to have a group of guys like
we've had here the last three, four years. You don't know how long
that can last, so you have to make the most of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0114 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Leading Devils in Playoffs  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- If one thing is making the New Jersey
Devils laugh in the playoffs, it's all the whining about their
defense, that so-called neutral zone trap.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the Devils insist they aren't playing the trap in
center ice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just think we are playing a system,'' forward Jay Pandolfo
said Thursday after the Devils held meetings at their South
Mountain training facility to prepare for the opening game of the
best-of-seven Eastern Conference final in Philadelphia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if it's called a trap or what,'' Pandolfo added.
''I don't even think we are sitting back and waiting for teams to
come. We've been putting a lot of pressure on them in their zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Florida nor Toronto mounted much offense in the first
two rounds of the playoffs against New Jersey, but the Flyers will
present a different challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Philadelphia playing well, it also has the size and
strength to match up against the Devils, even with Eric Lindros and
Keith Primeau probably sidelined with concussions.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers also are playing a different style without Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people believe in opening it up, but that's not the way
this team plays now,'' defenseman Chris Therien said after practice
on Thursday. ''It's defense first. The Devils play the same way we
do. It's almost like a chess match. It's who wants to be the most
patient. Some goals are going to be scored by which team makes a
mistake. That's the way the playoffs are.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Devils have been a little better statistically
than the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey goaltender Martin Broduer has faced 221 shots in 10
playoff games, giving up 15 goals. Flyers rookie goalie Brian
Boucher has faced 299 shots in 11 games, surrendering 22 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our styles are a lot alike now,'' said Flyers center Simon
Gagne, who will move to second-line in the expected absence of
Primeau for Game 1. ''The games will be tight, the shots might be
15-15. We have to dump the puck, pinch our defensemen and work
really hard against that team.''
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's defense has given the Flyers problems in recent
years. The Devils won the season series 4-1, and it is 11-2-2
against Philadelphia over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just think we are playing good positional hockey,'' Devils
center Bobby Holik said. ''I don't see the trap being created that
much. We play well in our end and we play well in their end. We're
responsible with the puck. People can watch it and name it whatever
they want, whether they like it or not. We like it, we're
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In eliminating Toronto on Monday night, New Jersey allowed a
modern-day, NHL-record low six shots in a 3-0 win.
</P>
<P>
   After the series, the Maple Leafs complained the Devils' system
of clogging up center ice and making it difficult to generate
offense made for a boring game.
</P>
<P>
   ''When people use the word trap, I get a kick out of it because
I still haven't heard it from (coach) Larry (Robinson) once,''
defenseman Ken Daneyko said.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that has changed since Robinson took over is the
Devils are doing the little things to help their defense. When the
puck is in their end, they get it out quickly. They don't allow
much traffic in front of Brodeur and they have been very good in
limiting odd-man rushes.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time that leaves opponents in the neutral zone
trying to get into the Devils' end, which makes them feel like they
are playing a neutral zone trap.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the complaining, and hence the laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
