<HEADLINE> Zapatistas Accuse Mexico Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- Zapatista rebels have
accused the Mexican government of reactivating paramilitary groups
in indigenous villages of the poor southern state of Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitaries were responsible for the deaths of three
family members in the village of Polho last Sunday, said a
statement signed by seven commanders of the Zapatista National
Liberation Army. The government has accused the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ''In an irresponsible and criminal act, the government of
Chiapas blames our Zapatista bases and maintains positioned at
little distance from Polho hundreds of police and military ready to
attack,'' said the statement released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas waged a brief uprising in 1994 in the name of
Indian rights. Since then, scores of people have been killed in
clashes between rebels or their supporters and armed,
pro-government squads. Peace talks between the rebels and the
government are at a stalemate.
</P>
</TEXT>
