<HEADLINE> Gore Fighting For Women Voters  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore eats a green-pepper omelet in Margo
Strong's modest Michigan kitchen, praises her cooking and gives her
a lift to school, where he plays teacher for eight hours -- all to
underscore his commitment to public schools, child care and
universal health insurance for children.
</P>
<P>
   While the vice president has bent over backward to personify the
issues dear to women whose votes will be critical in November,
polls give him little credit for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   So do some of the women who encounter him along the presidential
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   By the final bell at Holt High last Friday, one Michigan woman
meant to be drawn in by homey images of Gore immersed in the
school's life still felt the Democrat is too disconnected to get
excited about in the way women voters rallied around Bill Clinton
in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm probably a Gore supporter but I'm still figuring it out,''
said Sue Brown, a 50-year-old homemaker who went to Holt to see
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like Gore is more above where the rest of us are, and
Clinton is more down-to-earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Among women nationally, Gore is tied with Republican George W.
Bush and antsy women activists puzzle over why Gore is not wowing
women despite a woman-friendly agenda, including proposals to
improve Social Security for homemakers and widows.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somehow, his message isn't working. It isn't getting out
there,'' said Nancy Zirkin of the American Association of
University Women.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, such as domestic violence, family medical leave
and other issues that Zirkin and fellow activists have pressed with
Gore, the message isn't out there because, while supportive, he
isn't saying much about them -- at least, not in ways that make
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-blocked reauthorization of the landmark Violence
Against Women Act has consumed feminist lobbyists for more than a
year lest battered women's shelters be crippled on Oct. 1 when
funds expire. Gore has been silent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope he will talk more about the issues that affect women's
lives,'' said Kim Gandy, executive vice president of the National
Organization for Women.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, far from yielding the megaphone, recently laid out
proposals on education, health and long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not that Al Gore is in trouble with women,'' said Frank
Luntz, an analyst for the young Republicans' YROCK.com. ''It's that
Governor Bush has an appeal among women that Republicans haven't
had in a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton beat Republican Bob Dole by 16 points among
women in 1996, while splitting the men's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''That may be the toughest thing Al Gore has to face; it looks
like George W. Bush is not going to be Bob Dole, he's just not
going to concede that terrain to Al Gore,'' said Susan Carroll,
senior research associate at the Rutgers University Center for the
American Woman and Politics.
</P>
<P>
   To wit, Bush, with a photo of him and his wife prominently
displayed, gave an interview Thursday to Lifetime, the cable
channel for women, and dispatched women members of Congress outside
the Capitol to sing his praises.
</P>
<P>
   A new Voter.com-Battleground poll shows that since March, when
Bush clinched the GOP nomination and began an appeal to moderate
swing voters, he turned a 5-point deficit among women into a
4-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   While both margins represent a statistical tie, the swing
worries Gore allies -- as do recent polls showing Bush has muted
issues where Gore counted on establishing a lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has held close on the issue of education and, in a
development unthinkable to the staunchly pro-gun control Gore camp,
is leading slightly on the issue of guns.
</P>
<P>
   Zirkin and Gandy were among a loose coalition of some 100
women's groups who met with Gore and top campaign officials at the
White House this week to talk issues and ''voice concerns,'' Gandy
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said they requested the meeting back in November ''when we
saw that the message was not getting out about what an unmitigated
disaster George W. Bush would be for women.''
</P>
<P>
   In the six months it took to land a spot on Gore's calendar,
''there has not been much progress,'' Gandy said. But she left the
meeting with ''many assurances'' from Gore and his aides that he is
determined to keep trying.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Health and Human Services Secretary Donna
Shalala this week joined the effort to amplify, in press
interviews, Gore's central argument that a Bush administration,
given his record as governor of Texas, would be disastrous to the
environment, public schools, health care and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the issues that will be discussed over the course of
the next five months and 27 days,'' said Gore campaign spokesman
Chris Lehane. ''By this fall, people will know these differences
and that knowledge will translate into support for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Gore turns to words like ''smug'' and ''arrogant'' to
describe Bush's policy stances, he walks a delicate line with
women, warned Ari Fleischer, campaign spokesman for Bush, whose own
tone has mellowed markedly since his vitriolic primary fight with
GOP Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women are going to be increasingly turned off by Al Gore's
relentless barrage of negative attacks,'' said Fleischer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0147 </TRAILER>
