<HEADLINE> GOP Weighs Primary Schedule Changes  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SMITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Debate over a GOP plan to revamp the
presidential primary schedule could spill into the party's national
convention in Philadelphia this summer, pitting small states
against the likes of California, Texas and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we decide could decide the 2004 headlines in the
newspapers,'' Tom Sansonetti, chairman of the Republican National
Committee's rules panel, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was to vote today on a proposal to let small states
launch the nominating process by voting first in early March, with
clusters of larger states voting later through June.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who believe their states were practically shut out
of the presidential nominating process this year are backing the
proposal. Larger states oppose the plan.
</P>
<P>
   If endorsed today, final approval would be required during the
July 31-Aug. 3 convention, where delegations from larger states
would have an advantage in numbers. Those states are outnumbered,
however, on the rules panel, which debated the proposal Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rath of New Hampshire said the committee vote could be very
close, and if so, ''I don't know what kind of signal that sends to
the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   An advisory committee recommended the staggered primary schedule
as a way to give voters more time to consider candidates and a
greater say in the nomination process.
</P>
<P>
   The subject gained urgency this year after a front-loaded
calendar resulted in both parties' nominees being decided by early
March -- before half of the states had held primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the smallest states would vote no earlier than
the first Tuesday in March, with three more groups voting in
subsequent months, ending in June.
</P>
<P>
   Large states such as California, Texas and New York would hold
primaries in June, but that final group still would decide 47
percent of the delegates. The plan is to be voted on first before
deciding if Iowa and New Hampshire should keep their tradition of
going first.
</P>
<P>
   Another option the panel may consider today calls for a system
of rotating regional primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sense I get from talking to people is that the system is
so broken it demands reform,'' said Mike Hellon of Arizona, who
supports the plan although it would require moving the state's
Republican primary from February to May.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from more populous states argued against the
proposed new schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 12 largest states should not allow their voters to have
their voices stifled,'' said Barbara Alby of California, which over
the years has moved its GOP primary from June to the first Tuesday
in March. Officials there do not want to move it back, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have chosen to stay with their current system for now,
allowing Iowa and New Hampshire to go first and restricting other
states to a window from the first Tuesday in March to the second
Tuesday in June.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP panel also endorsed a rule that would allow the national
party to penalize states for not complying with the primary
schedule by stripping them of anywhere from half to 90 percent of
their convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   It backed a change that would give the national party greater
flexibility to change primary schedules between national
conventions, and rejected a recommendation that delegates be
awarded on a proportional basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0148 </TRAILER>
