<DOCNO> APW20000512.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Eyes Democrat Convention  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE DeARMOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democrats intent on ensuring a smooth
presidential nominating process this summer are working feverishly
to get their longtime labor allies to agree not to strike the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   A deal is expected within weeks to guarantee that workers who
serve food and drinks and engineers who keep the downtown Staples
Center's mechanical systems humming will stay on the job. Not
covered by the agreement are union members who don't work at the
convention site.
</P>
<P>
   It's those workers and their hunger for attracting the attention
of the 15,000 journalists expected to attend the convention who
could prove embarrassing for the political party that bills itself
as the champion of working people.
</P>
<P>
   Although they don't plan to protest Democratic policies, labor
leaders are plotting high-profile demonstrations outside the
convention site and a massive march nearby by one Service Employees
International Union local that covers 45,000 Los Angeles County
government employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''The convention does loom as a tasty target for labor
disputes,'' said Geoffrey Garfield, spokesman for the Los Angeles
Police Protective League, which represents 9,500 officers and is
negotiating with the city of Los Angeles for a contract to replace
one expiring June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Aug. 14-17 convention comes on the heels of a successful
strike by janitors in Los Angeles County that has unions flying
high. Members feel empowered, invigorated and, for a rare few,
ready to challenge Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we all need to up the bar on what Democrats need to be
doing for working families,'' said Roxana Rivera-Solis, political
coordinator for the SEIU Local 1877, which staged the three-week
janitors' strike in April.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders such as Rivera-Solis see the convention as a
chance to remind Democrats to use their position to exert influence
during union disputes and to craft laws favorable to workers.
</P>
<P>
   Rod O'Connor, chief of staff for the convention, insisted the
party's relationship with labor remains strong and predicted it
will be strengthened still as the convention nears.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Democratic Party has a long history of supporting
the rights of working families,'' O'Connor said. ''If there are
events around the convention that are sponsored by labor, I believe
... they will be done in coordination with the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement under negotiation is likely to establish a
grievance procedure for union workers at the convention and
guarantee no work stoppages by them.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a similar agreement with labor unions in
Philadelphia for the GOP convention there July 31-Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee, said
he was not worried about the possibility of labor protests outside
the meeting site.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very supportive of the rights and the causes of the men
and women of labor,'' he said. ''We are by no means overtly
troubled by this because these are our friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0150 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Giuliani Shows Softer Side  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Few national political figures have sought to
keep as tight a lid on their private lives as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely discusses his childhood. He doesn't talk about family
or friends. And what he does when he's not at City Hall is largely
a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, all that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of his disclosure two weeks ago that he is battling
prostate cancer, the mayor now is talking about the support he's
getting from a woman who isn't his wife, and confirming
long-standing rumors that his marriage is rocky.
</P>
<P>
   The recent disclosures have revealed a softer side to the
usually pugnacious mayor. They also have opened the prospective
U.S. Senate candidate up to nettlesome questions about morals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is ex-prosecutor who has set himself up as the
tough guy moralist who won't allow breaches of the law or moral
values: A man who drinks a beer from a paper bag on his front steps
should be arrested; all strip joints and peeps shows should be
shut; the Ten Commandments should be displayed in all city schools.
</P>
<P>
   As conservative columnist Eric Fettman of the New York Post
described the mayor's vaunted high standards: ''Rudy Giuliani has
been one of the few public officials to stand head-on against those
who defiantly insist that the unchecked lowering of society's moral
standards constitutes progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Fettman added, ''His ability to keep doing so has now,
sadly, been undermined -- by his own behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's other side began showing two weeks ago, after he was
spotted at a hospital by a reporter acting on a tip.
</P>
<P>
   After hours of intense media speculation, the 55-year-old mayor
hastily called a City Hall news conference to say he had treatable
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the next stunner -- the Republican mayor has been
having a relationship with Judith Nathan, a divorced health
executive, whom he called a ''very good friend.'' His remarks came
only after reporters spotted Giuliani and Nathan around town.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Giuliani announced he and television personality Donna
Hanover, his wife of 16 years, were discussing separation. She made
a public statement, too, accusing the mayor of an earlier affair.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Giuliani said he was ''very sad'' about the marriage
gone awry, and he wanted to protect his children, ages 14 and 10.
He described his wife as a ''wonderful woman, wonderful mother.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest disclosures -- including that Giuliani took Nathan to
places as public as political meetings and the St. Patrick's Day
parade -- amount to very strange behavior in the midst of his heated
Senate race against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jordan, a spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, went so far as to say he thought the mayor was ''losing
his marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have speculated that Giuliani secretly does not really
want to run and is sabotaging himself so he can drop out.
</P>
<P>
   And so Thursday, 26 television cameras and dozens of reporters
packed a news conference to hear whether Giuliani would indeed call
it quits.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor -- who was oddly buoyant in announcing April 27
that he had treatable prostate cancer and stunningly sober in his
declaration this week that he would seek a legal separation -- said
that he has not yet decided either way.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood the Republican Party's need to know his
decision soon but added, ''I do not have a personal timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's new contemplative side was in evidence, as he
broached a number of topics that would have been unthinkable just
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concerns are my life, my personal life, my health, my
family and the other people that are involved in it, all of whom
are very decent people,'' he said. ''I'm a very fortunate human
being to have very good friends and that is how I'm getting through
all of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   His familiar combativeness was there, too.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked about his suspected philandering, Giuliani
bellowed, ''Oh get out of here! Get lost, get lost, that's a sneaky
way of trying to invade somebody's personal life. Don't you guys
have the slightest bit of decency?''
</P>
<P>
   And to those who have watched Giuliani's tough-as-nails exterior
through the years, it was almost stunning to hear his admission
that he, too, is subject to the commonest of human frailties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you cry sometimes?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, of course,'' he said. ''Of course I cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0151 </TRAILER>
