<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani, who plays things close to vest, is forced to air his dirty linen </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Few national political figures have sought to
keep as tight a lid on their private lives as Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. He rarely discusses his childhood. He doesn't talk about
family or friends. And what he does when he's not at City Hall is
largely a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly all that has changed. Giuliani -- who set himself up
as the tough guy moralist who won't allow breaches of the law or
moral values -- is talking about the support he's getting from a
woman not his wife and confirming long-standing rumors his marriage
is rocky.
</P>
<P>
   It started two weeks ago when a reporter acting on a tip spotted
Giuliani, 55, at a hospital. After several hours of intense media
speculation, Giuliani hastily called a City Hall news conference
and, with television cameras rolling, told the city that he had
treatable prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the next stunner -- the Republican mayor has been
having a relationship with Judith Nathan, a divorced health
executive, whom he called a ''very good friend.'' His remarks came
only after reporters spotted Giuliani and Nathan around town.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Giuliani announced he and television personality Donna
Hanover, his wife of 16 years, were talking about separation. She
made a public statement, too, accusing the mayor of an earlier
affair.
</P>
<P>
   In his public statements, Giuliani said he was ''very sad''
about the marriage gone awry. It was ''very painful.'' He wanted to
protect his children, ages 14 and 10. His wife was a ''wonderful
woman, wonderful mother.''
</P>
<P>
   While the recent disclosures have revealed a softer side to the
usually pugnacious mayor, they have also opened the prospective
U.S. Senate candidate up to nettlesome questions about morals.
</P>
<P>
   After all, this is an ex-prosecutor who doesn't stand for moral
funny business. A man who drinks a beer from a paper bag on his
front steps should be arrested. All strip joints and peeps shows
should be shut. The Ten Commandments should be displayed in all
city schools.
</P>
<P>
   As conservative columnist Eric Fettman of the New York Post
described the mayor's vaunted high standards: ''Rudy Giuliani has
been one of the few public officials to stand head-on against those
who defiantly insist that the unchecked lowering of society's moral
standards constitutes progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Fettman added, ''His ability to keep doing so has now,
sadly, been undermined -- by his own behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, the latest disclosures -- including that Giuliani took
Nathan to places as public as political meetings and even the St.
Patrick's Day parade -- amount to very strange behavior in the midst
of the mayor's heated U.S. Senate race against first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jordan, a spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, went so far as to say he thought the mayor was ''losing
his marbles.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have speculated that Giuliani secretly does not really
want to run and is purposely sabotaging himself so he'll have an
excuse to drop out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   And so Thursday, 26 television cameras and dozens of reporters
packed a press conference to hear whether Giuliani would indeed
call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor -- who was oddly buoyant in announcing on April 27
that he had treatable prostate cancer and stunningly sober in his
declaration this week that he would seek a legal separation -- said
that he has not yet decided either way.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood the Republican Party's need to know his
decision soon but added ''I do not have a personal timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's new contemplative side was in evidence, as he
broached a number of topics that would have been unthinkable just
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concerns are my life, my personal life, my health, my
family and the other people that are involved in it, all of whom
are very decent people,'' he said. ''I'm a very fortunate human
being to have very good friends and that is how I'm getting through
all of these things.''
</P>
<P>
   But his familiar combativeness was there as well.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked about his suspected philandering, Giuliani
bellowed, ''Oh get out of here! Get lost, get lost, that's a sneaky
way of trying to invade somebody's personal life. Don't you guys
have the slightest bit of decency?''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most stunning piece of news to those who have
watched the mayor's tough-as-nails exterior through the years was
his admission that he, too, is subject to the commonest of human
frailties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you cry sometimes?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yeah, of course,'' he said. ''Of course I cry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0203 </TRAILER>
