<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conn. Bishop To Succeed O'Connor  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mixing a dry Irish wit with conservative church
doctrine, Bishop Edward Egan arrived here to assume the mantle of
the late Cardinal John O'Connor and the spiritual leadership of 2.4
million Roman Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, who for 12 years led 367,000 Catholics in the diocese of
Bridgeport, Conn., was selected Thursday by the pope to head the
New York Archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel like the boss,'' he joked with reporters at a
news conference. ''But give me a little time and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old bishop is an uncompromising defender of
traditional Vatican teachings. When asked about abortion and birth
control, Egan backed the pope's opposition to both, as he has done
staunchly during his career. Asked by a Vatican radio reporter
whether he would be pro-life, Egan answered in both English and
Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all the enthusiasms and insistence and light that I can
possibly add, the answer is yes,'' he said. ''Without any question,
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan will become the 12th archbishop of New York when he is
formally installed June 19. He is also widely expected to be
elevated to cardinal by Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Egan said he hoped to gain the same acceptance in New York that
the Philadelphia-born O'Connor achieved during his 16 years in the
church's most prominent American pulpit. O'Connor died last week of
a brain tumor at age 80.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you there is no place in the world that is quicker
to accept someone who wants to be a New Yorker,'' said Egan, who
worked in the New York Archdiocese earlier in his career. ''I want
to be a New Yorker, and I guess I am officially one.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgeport, Egan won acclaim for reorganizing diocesan
schools and recruiting local men for the priesthood. He also raised
millions of dollars in his annual bishop's appeal in the diocese,
which embraces Fairfield County, one of the nation's richest
counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an imposing figure and a great preacher,'' said Monsignor
Timothy Dolan, an American who heads the North American Pontifical
College in Rome. Egan studied there after his 1957 ordination.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the similarity to O'Connor, Dolan added, ''When Ed Egan
walks into a room, he doesn't go unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pieczynski, spokeswoman for the Chicago-based church
reform group Call to Action, described Egan as ''very
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My understanding is that he is very personable, but also very
rigid in his approach to issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oak Park, Ill., Egan studied theology at Rome's
Gregorian Pontifical University. He served from 1971 to 1985 on the
Vatican tribunal that decides such matters as whether to grant
annulments.
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgeport, Egan came under fire for defending the diocese
against more than two dozen lawsuits over alleged sexual
molestation by priests. Although all but one of the cases preceded
Egan's arrival, they raised tough questions over whether abuse was
covered up.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Vatican: http://www.vatican.va
</P>
<P>
   North American Pontifical College:
http://www.catholic-forum.com/pnac
</P>
</TEXT>
