<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Shakes S. Turkey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- A moderate earthquake hit southern Turkey
on Friday, sending residents of the town of Osmaniye into the
streets or jumping from balconies in panic.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials said a woman was treated for broken legs and
arms after she jumped out of her third-floor apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The epicenter of the quake was near Osmaniye, 350 miles
southeast of Ankara, according to Istanbul's Kandilli Observatory.
Most people were asleep when the magnitude 4.8 quake hit at 6:01
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The quake caused cracks in the walls of some houses while
damaging the minarets of at least two mosques, the Anatolia news
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office was trying to determine the damage.
</P>
<P>
   The quake struck four days after a magnitude 4.5 quake damaged
200 houses in the town of Puturge, further east. Puturge lies on
the East Anatolian fault, which also extends to the east of
Osmaniye.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Turkey lies on another fault, the North Anatolian, the
source of two strong earthquakes that leveled parts of northwestern
Turkey in August and November, killing more than 18,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
