<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FBI: Foreign Agents Have Access  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright says she
will look into an FBI disclosure that foreign spies working under
cover as news correspondents are able to move about the State
Department unescorted.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony Thursday by Timothy Bereznay, an FBI section
chief, before the House International Relations Committee caught
Albright and President Clinton by surprise. It also came amid
concern over security at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously we don't want spies posing as journalists,''
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright has given top priority to tightening security at the
department following a series of security lapses over the past two
years. The most serious occurred this past winter with the
disappearance of a laptop computer containing highly sensitive
information about weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   Bereznay implied that some of the foreign agents with press
credentials represented hostile powers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the FBI, in order to protect sources and sensitive
cases, does not customarily provide other agencies with lists of
intelligence officer identities.
</P>
<P>
   ''If asked, the FBI would be willing to identify to the State
Department permanent media badge holders identified as hostile
intelligence officers so that their access could be restricted or
their visits monitored,'' Bereznay said.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI issued a statement Thursday night that directly
contradicted that section of Bereznay's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''The FBI coordinates closely with the Bureau of Diplomatic
Security, Department of State, on all security issues,'' it said.
''The FBI shares information with them whether or not we are
specifically asked. If the FBI is in possession of any information
of that nature, we would share it with the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern about foreign correspondents who cover the State
Department had receded following the end of the Cold War. More than
a decade ago, the Reagan administration decreed that East Bloc
reporters be required to have an escort.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran correspondents also recalled a case about 15 years ago
when the State Department expelled a Soviet reporter who
acknowledged to a neighbor, in an apparently unguarded moment, that
he also worked as a spy.
</P>
<P>
   Bereznay said that over the past 15 years, no foreign
intelligence service officer under media cover has been declared
persona non grata for engaging in espionage activities because such
agents do not have diplomatic immunity and normally avoid such
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's disclosure was a setback for Albright, who has been
hoping to put the furor over security lapses behind her.
</P>
<P>
   There has been sharp criticism from Capitol Hill about the
problem but it has been directed more at the perceived lax security
culture at the department than at Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State David Carpenter acknowledged that
all media have unescorted access to the first two floors of the
State Department but said there are no assurances that access above
the second floor cannot be gained.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it was within my power, I would not have any press in the
building,'' Carpenter said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said there are 467 Americans with
department press credentials and 56 foreign media.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department: www.state.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani fights speculation that he's about to drop Senate bid  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Top state Republican officials say Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani just needs some time to deal with his crumbling marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat surprisingly, the sentiment is echoed by some of the
mayor's most vocal critics, namely his U.S. Senate opponent,
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just don't think anyone should comment on what they're going
through,'' Clinton said on NBC's ''Today'' show. ''I'm going to,
out of respect for him and his family, have nothing to say about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the public show of support from fellow Republicans seems to
be just that. Behind the scenes, plans are already being made to
back another Senate candidate should the mayor end his campaign.
And some potential alternative candidates are coming out publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Giuliani fought back Thursday, claiming he isn't going
away just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made no decision yet to drop out of the Senate race,'' he
insisted when confronted at a news conference with reports he would
quit. ''I didn't discuss that with anyone. I didn't say that to
anyone. I didn't think about it yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's latest statements came a day after he announced that
he and his wife of 16 years, Donna Hanover, are discussing a legal
separation. Hanover responded by dropping her own bombshell,
alleging that their marital woes began over his relationship with a
former press aide, Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover also told reporters that just as she and the mayor began
to reconcile, he took up with a third woman. Giuliani has
acknowledged an ongoing relationship with a health care executive,
Judith Nathan, whom he called a ''very good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the mayor lashed out at reporters who shouted
questions about the alleged affairs. ''Don't you guys have the
slightest bit of decency?'' he scolded. ''Shhhh! Do you realize you
embarrass yourself doing this in the eyes of just about
everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   He also reiterated that his Senate run is contingent on his
treatment for prostate cancer, which was diagnosed two weeks ago.
''I haven't made up my mind if I have the energy and the capacity
to run,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, a senior Republican official close to
Giuliani, speaking on condition of anonymity, told The Associated
Press that the mayor was leaning toward quitting. ''His heart, his
soul, his body are not in this thing,'' said the official, who
added that Giuliani hadn't made a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans must choose a Senate candidate by May 30, when they
hold their state convention. State GOP chairman Bill Powers gave
Giuliani a vote of confidence Thursday, saying: ''Contrary to
everybody else's popular belief, I believe he is running.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Bruno, the Republican majority leader in the state
Senate, agreed, saying: ''There are no plans other than to support
Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one senior adviser to state GOP leaders, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said contingency planning already was
underway in case a replacement candidate was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The list of potential replacements for Giuliani also grew
rapidly amid the mayor's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, a Long Island congressman, renewed his interest
in running, first expressed months ago. And Rep. Peter King of Long
Island and Wall Street multimillionaire Ted Forstmann, a prominent
supporter of Catholic causes, both let it be known they would be
available.
</P>
<P>
   While many were saying Giuliani's personal life was not public
information, that didn't keep them from talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told reporters in Washington: ''Everybody in
New York and everybody in America ought to be rooting for the human
side of this to work out. We should wish him well in the struggle
of his illness, wish that family well and should want the best for
their children. And we should want some space for all of them -- out
of the glare.''
</P>
<P>
   Average New Yorkers, meanwhile, were enthralled by the daily
drama coming out of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's become a public soap opera,'' said Frank Fornario, a
Westchester teacher who said he would continue to support Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''Between the cancer and the situation with his marriage, I feel
he's not interested in the politics,'' said Kathy Andrade, a
Manhattan retiree who plans to vote for the first lady. ''Stress is
no good for him; he's better off staying home.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Edward Egan, a Catholic bishop from Connecticut who was
named head of the New York archdiocese Thursday, offered an
opinion, saying he hoped Catholics and others ''would have the
greatest sympathy for this good human being who is struggling
through two very serious situations.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush said Giuliani's family
troubles are ''a personal matter between he and his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who like other Republicans questioned President Clinton's
integrity after the impeachment scandal, was asked on Lifetime
cable if voters should be concerned about the mayor's character.
''I hope he stays in the race,'' he said. ''I'm more concerned
about the fact that he's sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 0231 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exchange Regulator Said Dead  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's top foreign exchange regulator has died,
a Chinese official confirmed today, amid Hong Kong media reports
that he committed suicide either out of worries about his health or
a corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Ming Pao newspaper reported that Li Fuxiang,
director of China's State Administration of Foreign Exchange, was
admitted to a Beijing hospital and died Wednesday after jumping
from the seventh floor.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the administration's information office said Li
had died. But the official, who would only give her surname, Deng,
refused to provide additional information, saying she was awaiting
instructions from superiors on reporting the death.
</P>
<P>
   Ming Pao and the Sing Tao Daily, another mainstream, independent
Hong Kong newspaper, said Li's death may have been related to
health, work pressure or financial problems. Sing Tao said he
suffered heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on a popular Web site said Li had checked into the No.
304 Hospital, a military facility.
</P>
<P>
   A worker in the hospital's morgue confirmed that a person
staying in the ward reserved for senior officials had fallen to his
death and the body was found outside the hospital Wednesday
morning. Police came and removed the body, said the worker, who
would not give his name.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation bureau of China's ruling Communist
Party recently questioned Li about corruption involving China
Everbright Bank, Sing Tao reported.
</P>
<P>
   Everbright Bank's former chairman, Zhu Xiaohua, was removed last
summer, reportedly under investigation for economic problems, an
allegation the company denied. Zhu had run the government's foreign
exchange administration for two years, leaving in 1995, three years
before Li took over.
</P>
<P>
   Li, whose age was variously reported as 47 or 48, took over the
State Administration of Foreign Exchange in October 1998. The
administration sets policies and oversees the flow of foreign
currency, an important mission in China. China's currency, the
yuan, is not fully convertible on international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Under Li's leadership, the administration tightened controls on
foreign exchange to stop illegal outflows that were pressuring
China to devalue the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Li's death and its possible connection to the rumored but never
confirmed investigation into China Everbright could add to scandals
already embarrassing Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
   China Everbright Bank is one of China's more innovative and
profitable banks. Its parent company, China Everbright Group, which
Zhu also ran, is controlled by the State Council, the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders have been trying to curb rampant corruption that
has eroded popular support for Communist Party rule. But they have
limited the wholly state-controlled media's reporting on
corruption. They fear that revelations about the involvement of
senior officials could further damage the party's image.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into billions of dollars of smuggling through
the southeastern port of Xiamen has implicated the wife of Beijing
party secretary Jia Qinglin, party officials have said. President
Jiang Zemin, a mentor of Jia, ordered public denials that either
Jia or his wife were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Li Fuxiang's death, the spokesman's office for the
State Council said they had no information.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Li's death first appeared Thursday on a popular Internet
chat room, reported the Hong Kong-based rights group Information
Center of Human Rights and Democracy. It reported that the
two-sentence anonymous posting said Li's suicide was under
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
