<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Travels To Push China Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With momentum for a landmark China trade bill
seesawing in Congress, President Clinton is exerting pressure
nearly every day on undecided lawmakers, even traveling to one
congressman's district where opposition is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton today was heading to Akron, Ohio, an industrial city
where union members have been trying to block efforts to extend
permanent normal trade relations with China. Akron is in the
district of Rep. Thomas Sawyer, D-Ohio, who has not yet declared
his position on the trade measure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to meet with 15 business, religious, academic and
labor leaders to discuss their concerns about the bill. Union
members in Sawyer's district, meanwhile, were prepared to
demonstrate against the president's China policy and urge defeat of
the trade bill when a vote is taken later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Clinton was traveling to friendlier turf -- the
Hauer family farm in Shakopee, Minn., which could profit from
expanded agricultural sales to China. The rural area outside
Minneapolis is represented by Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., who is
backing the trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   A tug-of-war over votes for and against the measure is
hard-fought in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters Thursday that he believed Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, would find the needed GOP votes to pass the
measure despite complaints from DeLay that Republican support was
thinner than he initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''I noticed that he's quite effective at getting votes when the
time comes, sometimes when I like it and sometimes when I don't,''
Clinton said of DeLay, one of the leaders of the House impeachment
effort in 1998. ''I think we'll get there. We've just got a lot of
hard work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Thursday, Commerce Secretary William Daley, the Clinton
administration's point man on China, warned Republicans that if
they want the bill to pass, they'll have to agree to the formation
of a commission to monitor China's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a watchdog commission, which would issue an annual
report to Congress, has been suggested by Reps. Sander Levin,
D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb. The commission could recommend
economic sanctions against China outside of the trade area, such as
withholding U.S. loans.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer was considering the commission idea.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
