<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 03:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Extends No Gun Ri Probe  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army is extending a probe of civilian
killings by U.S. soldiers during the Korean War as investigators
try to untangle varying accounts of what happened in late July 1950
near the village of No Gun Ri, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   One official said that after interviewing more than 100 people,
investigators believe ''something tragic happened'' in the South
Korean hamlet in the opening days of the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   But because of discrepancies in accounts provided by U.S.
veterans and Korean survivors, investigators almost certainly will
be unable to finish the probe before the original target of June
25, the 50th anniversary of the start of the Korean conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Thursday the investigation
is likely to last until fall. ''It would be better not to
salami-slice the findings and to wait for the Army to conclude its
work and come out with everything at once,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was begun after The Associated Press, in a
report last fall, quoted U.S. veterans as saying American soldiers
killed at least 100 civilians. Korean survivors said as many as 300
civilians were shot to death under a railroad bridge at No Gun Ri
following a strafing in which about 100 died.
</P>
<P>
   Two officials, who recently discussed the matter separately on
condition of anonymity, said investigators have not verified the
scope of the alleged mass killings at the village. They also said
they have not yet established that the killings, which began on
July 26, 1950, were ordered by superior officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're quite aware that something tragic happened there,'' an
official familiar with the investigation said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that after interviews that included some of
the veterans who were at No Gun Ri and reviewing several thousand
historical documents -- Army investigators are wrestling with
''evidentiary inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   One account the investigators were having trouble reconciling
was that of Edward Daily of Clarksville, Tenn., who has been
especially visible in recounting his role in the episode.
</P>
<P>
   Army spokesman Maj. Thomas Collins acknowledged that ''there are
a lot of inconsistencies that we're aware of'' in Daily's story.
Collins said Army officials contacted Daily on Wednesday to
reinterview him, but he told them he was done talking about the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   The AP reported on an order issued by the 1st Cavalry Division
headquarters in late July 1950 that said: ''No refugees to cross
the front line. Fire everyone trying to cross lines. Use discretion
in case of women and children.''
</P>
<P>
   An AP request to interview Charles Cragin, the Pentagon official
directing the review, was denied Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators are still grappling with such questions as how
many people were killed, who may have issued orders to open fire,
and whether the shootings were provoked by gunfire from among the
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to soldiers, the Army interviewed dozens of Korean
survivors, and sources familiar with the investigation said the
accounts were compelling.
</P>
<P>
   But the sources said investigators were having difficulty
reconstructing a consistent version from witnesses' memories of
events that occurred a half-century ago. They said there were
direct contradictions in the stories, even in conflicting accounts
given by the same person.
</P>
<P>
   The sources spoke on condition of anonymity, reflecting the
investigators' determination to avoid influencing the investigation
or triggering diplomatic problems between Washington and Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. investigators met with a visiting South Korean delegation
in early May and turned over transcripts of interviews with U.S.
veterans, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins declined to comment on a report Wednesday by
Stripes.com, a privately owned Internet site for veterans, which
contended two of the dozens of Korean and U.S. witnesses who
described the No Gun Ri incident to the AP were not there at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Stripes.com report, citing a regimental document, asserted
that Delos K. Flint, an ex-GI eyewitness quoted by the AP, was
wounded and evacuated July 25, the day before the shooting started.
But a company ''morning report,'' obtained by the AP in June 1998,
says he was wounded the next day, July 26.
</P>
<P>
   The Stripes.com report also said newly released Army personnel
records indicate that Daily served in an ordnance maintenance unit
and was not in the front line unit -- H Company, 2nd Battalion of
the 7th Cavalry -- at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But Army spokesman Collins said, ''This doesn't change anything.
Ed Daily is just one guy of many that we've been talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   Five other soldiers interviewed by the AP in investigating No
Gun Ri said Daily was in H Company at the time, and he produced
documents to verify his presence in H Company then.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said investigators had questions about some of
Daily's assertions, including his presence at No Gun Ri and his
claim to have received a battlefield commission as an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Stripes.com is owned by IServed.com of Pittsburgh and publishes
the Web site and the domestic bimonthly publication under the name
The Stars and Stripes. The overseas Stars and Stripes newspaper, a
separate publication that circulates in Europe and Asia, is a U.S.
military publication.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly U.S. News and World Report magazine will publish a
story Saturday that challenges the accounts of Daily, Flint and
another veteran, Gene Hesselman. Brian Duffy, the magazine's
executive editor, said the story raised questions about whether the
three ''were in fact present at the time the incident allegedly
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Hesselman has told the AP he was offered a medical evacuation
after being slightly wounded that day but decided to remain in the
front line instead.
</P>
<P>
   At AP headquarters in New York, spokeswoman Kelly Smith Tunney
said the AP account, which last month was awarded a Pulitzer Prize,
was based on extensive witness interviews in the United States and
South Korea and an examination of U.S. military records.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ed Daily was but one of many voices in this story and he has
repeated and vouched for the account he provided AP,'' she said.
''We're aware of discrepancies in Daily's military records and he
has shown an AP reporter documents that he says support his
contention that he served with H Company in 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the Army's inquiry would not be influenced by any
news accounts of the No Gun Ri incident.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are conducting a comprehensive review of the facts,''
Collins said. ''As part of that review, the IG (inspector general)
is reviewing the records of many Korean War veterans, to include
Edward Daily's. It is premature to discuss our findings until the
review is complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Before publication of the AP story, South Koreans who sought
acknowledgment of the killings and compensation were told by U.S.
officials that the allegations had been investigated and no
evidence of a massacre was found. After the AP story was published,
Caldera ordered ''as quick and thorough a review of these matters
as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 0307 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
