<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Head To Visit Latin America  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Managing Director Horst Koehler of the
International Monetary Fund will visit four countries in Latin
America next week on his first overseas fact-finding trip since
taking the top job at the institution.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF said Friday that Koehler will travel to Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil, on May 15; Buenos Aires, Argentina, on May 16; Tegucigalpa,
Honduras, on May 18; and Mexico City on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ''The purpose of Mr. Koehler's trip is to hear perspectives on
critical issues facing the global economy,'' the IMF statement
said. ''He is particularly interested in the views of emerging
market countries on the role of the IMF, which will be an important
input in the consideration of reform of the institutions''
</P>
<P>
   Koehler has plans to visit Africa and Asia in coming months, the
IMF said, but no dates for those trips were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, a German and the former head of the London-based
European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, assumed the top
IMF post May 2 after a bitter succession race in which the United
States publicly rejected Germany's first candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and its sister lending agency, the World Bank, held
their spring meetings last month in Washington under extraordinary
security protection as demonstrators vowed to shut the sessions
down. Police arrested more than 1,300 and used pepper spray to
control crowds.
</P>
</TEXT>
