<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses say they tried to warn guard in fatal abduction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WESTFIELD, N.J. (AP) -- Witnesses say a Seton Hall University
security guard did nothing to help when they told him they saw a
man trying to force a woman into a car. A half-hour later,
authorities say, Christopher Honrath shot Sohayla Hope Massachi in
the back of the head with a stolen .38-caliber revolver and then
killed himself in the bedroom of his duplex apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ''She tried to start running. She's screaming, 'Help me! Help
me!''' Asia Davis, 17, told The Star-Ledger of Newark for today's
editions. Davis said the ''big man'' used a necktie to lasso
Massachi, 23, and pull her by the neck into his black Plymouth
Laser.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle lasted several minutes Wednesday afternoon on a
street in front of the South Orange campus. A second teen-age
witness screamed at Honrath to stop while Davis pleaded with a
campus security guard for help.
</P>
<P>
   The guard did not call police, which allowed Honrath, 24, to
drive off with the woman in the car, the witnesses and
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said: 'There's a woman being kidnapped out there. I have the
license plate number. She needs help.' He told me he couldn't do
anything because he's not a police officer,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the guard picked up his phone, spoke with someone and
''then he hangs up and tells me that I have to walk down to the
South Orange police station. All the way down into town. I kept
saying, 'He's out there right now! We need help!'''
</P>
<P>
   Westfield police on Thursday said the security guard's inaction
cost precious time that could have been used to prevent the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Allegedly, he told them it happened off-campus, so he would
not make the call,'' Brunelle told the Courier News of Bridgewater.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not know the identity of the guard, and university
officials said they could provide no further information.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, we can't confirm any of this,'' university
spokeswoman Laurie Pine told the Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he worked for me, he'd be looking for a job at McDonald's
right now,'' Westfield police Lt. Francis Brunelle told The
Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   Massachi, an education student at Seton Hall, remained on
life-support at University Hospital in Newark Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Honrath was found dead behind the bedroom door of his apartment,
near Massachi, after police went to his apartment responding to a
report of violence. Police said they heard two gunshots after
knocking on the door. The gun Honrath used had been reported stolen
in Ossining, N.Y., in 1990, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Chituru Iromuanya said they were walking home from
Columbia High School in neighboring Maplewood about 2:30 p.m. when
they passed a young woman on the sidewalk. Moments later, they saw
a man stop his car in the middle of the street, get out and go
after her, the teens said.
</P>
<P>
   The girls said after pleading with the guard they ran to
Iromuanya's house and called South Orange police, describing what
they saw and giving police the license number. An officer was sent
to the house and took their statement.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Honrath was back in Westfield and had dragged Massachi
upstairs to his bedroom, Brunelle said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had quarreled before and had obtained restraining
orders against each other, police said. Brunelle said the pair met
through the Internet a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
