<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Chief Not Worried by Weak Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) -- EU Commission President Romano Prodi
said Friday he was not worried about the weakness of Europe's
single currency, adding that he was confident that the euro ''very
soon'' would be stronger than the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has fallen steadily against the dollar since the
currency was launched by 11 EU countries on Jan. 4, 1999, for
corporate and investment transactions. It was trading at 90.74
cents in London on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have to say that I don't care very much about that because
these ups and downs are typical of any currency market,'' Prodi
said at a news conference. ''The European Central Bank is working
well, there is no complaint about that, the fundamentals are sound,
(so are the) inflation and the rate of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the European Union's executive arm indicated the
euro was still suffering growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   The euro ''very soon will be bigger than the dollar,'' Prodi
said. He characterized the currency as ''a baby but a strong
baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodi's statement was in line with a similar statement from
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who said Thursday he too
wasn't worried about the euro and that the young currency faced the
prospect of strong growth and low inflation within the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi was in Copenhagen to attend a conference about the
15-nation bloc's upcoming intergovernmental conference on
enlargement and the need for reform when candidate countries
eventually join.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark, Sweden and Britain declined to adopt the euro in its
initial phase. Greece, which was not allowed into the monetary
union because of its high inflation and budget deficit, is expected
to gain membership next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
