<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, May 12, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   April Sees Wholesale Prices Drop
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a jump in food prices, wholesale
prices fell 0.3 percent in April after surging for two straight
months as energy costs took their biggest plunge in nine years. The
decline in the Labor Department's Producer Price Index, which
measures inflation pressures before they reach the consumer, was
the best showing on inflation since a 0.4 percent drop posted in
February 1999. Outside the volatile energy and food categories, the
''core'' rate of inflation at the wholesale level for the second
month in a row rose by 0.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Deal Creates Largest Ad Company
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Britain's WPP Group is buying U.S. heavyweight
Young &AMP; Rubicam for $4.7 billion in stock, a deal that would form
the world's largest advertising company. It would be the ad
industry's biggest deal ever. WPP, which already owns the
U.S.-based ad companies Ogillvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J. Walter
Thompson, said today the acquisition would expand its client base
and generate annual savings of more than $30 million. The two
advertising powerhouses already share a number of major customers,
including Ford Motor Co., Kraft Foods and Sears, Roebuck and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Report Pushes Stocks Up
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher this morning on Wall Street
after a government report showed a decline in wholesale prices in
April, helping to quell recent worries about inflationary
pressures. Just before 11 a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 68.20 at 10,614.17. The benign reading on inflation
came after a series of indicators showed strength in the economy
and raised worries that the Federal Reserve would move aggressively
to raise borrowing costs. Broader stock indicators were also
higher. The Nasdaq composite index was up 109.29, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 17.05.
</P>
