<P>
   Another Drop in Crop Prices Seen
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A worldwide surplus of grain and soybeans is
likely to push prices for many commodities down again this year,
given the big crops that farmers are planting this spring, the
Agriculture Department said today. Soybean prices, which averaged
$4.65 per bushel in 1999, will decline for the fourth year in a row
this year with U.S. production expected to rise 12 percent, the
department said. Prices this year will range from $4 to $5 a
bushel, with a midpoint of $4.50, the department said. Rice and
corn prices are expected to decline as well.
</P>
<P>
   Allaire Back As Xerox CEO
</P>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Paul A. Allaire, who stepped down as
chief executive of Xerox 13 months ago, is moving back into the
job. The move was announced yesterday following the firing of CEO
Rick Thoman. Thoman was hired as the No. 2 executive at Xerox in
June 1997 before being promoted. A cost-cutter who helped reverse
IBM's declining fortunes, he was seen as a leader who could help
Xerox regain its dominant position in the small and large office
machine markets. But since his arrival, Xerox has struggled with
slumping sales and a sales force restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Wants More Time
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- If, as expected, the judge in Microsoft's federal
antitrust case wants to consider the Justice Department's proposals
to break up the software giant, the company wants at least six
months to prepare its defense. Microsoft probably won't get the
full six months, but may have marshaled a sufficient legal argument
to gain at least some of that time, experts said. On Wednesday,
Microsoft asked U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson to
summarily dismiss the Justice Department's plan to break the
company in two.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Wants AOL-Time Warner Conditions
</P>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. is asking federal
regulators to require America Online and Time Warner to agree to
provide other Internet service providers access to their high-speed
cable lines as a condition of approval of their merger. Disney's
request was part of a filing on the proposed merger yesterday with
the Federal Communications Commission. ''Disney is not opposing the
proposed merger. We do think the Federal Communications Commission
should impose meaningful and enforceable conditions,'' Disney said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Plans To Slash 1,900 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. plans to slash 1,900 jobs at its
largest vehicle assembly plant in Britain, as part of an effort to
restore profitability to its money-losing European division. Ford
said it aims to eliminate the jobs at its assembly plant at
Dagenham in East London by 2002. Over time, however, it plans to
add more than 500 jobs at a separate plant at Dagenham that makes
diesel engines. Ford said the cuts would be voluntary.
</P>
