<HEADLINE> Kansas City Radio Stations Sold  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALA CYNWYD, Pa. (AP) -- Entercom Communications Corp. is selling
three radio stations in the Kansas City, Mo., market to Susquehanna
Radio Corp. of York for $113 million.
</P>
<P>
   The three stations named in the agreement were KCMO-AM, KCMO-FM
and KCFX-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Entercom announced that it agreed to purchase
stations WOLX-FM, WMMM-FM and WYZM-FM in Madison, Wis., from
Woodward Communications Inc. for $14.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both transactions are subject to regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the stations is in connection with Entercom's
planned purchase of four other Kansas City stations from Sinclair
Broadcast Group. Federal regulations require the company to divest
itself of three stations so that it will own a total of eight
stations in the Kansas City market, said Steve Fisher, a senior
vice president of Entercom.
</P>
<P>
   Once the acquisitions are completed, Entercom will own or
operate 95 stations in 18 markets, including Wilkes-Barre and
Scranton.
</P>
