<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche's Poland Takeover Closer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- The Securities Commission has stopped its
investigation of Deutsche Bank's bid to gain control of Poland's
fifth largest bank, bringing the German giant closer to its goal, a
newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rzeczpospolita daily said the decision was made Thursday by
Poland's securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   It described the decision as a success for Deutsche Bank, which
is taking steps to control BIG Bank Gdanski SA and strengthen its
position in Poland, a leading trading partner for Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Liliana Jarczuk, spokeswoman for the commission, confirmed it
gathered all necessary documents on the takeover but decided to
halt all proceedings for ''formal and legal reasons.'' She refused
further explanation saying the case is ''difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank refused to comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank unleashed a storm of controversy in January when
it unexpectedly pushed for the replacement of BIG's nine-member
supervisory board with a 19-member board that supported the German
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The old management and other investors protested, prompting the
Securities Commission to investigate Deutsche Bank's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Deutsche Bank increased its stake in BIG Bank to 16
percent with the purchase of 3 percent of BIG shares from an ally
in its takeover plans.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank has since asked Polish regulators for permission
to increase its control of BIG to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BIG lacks a majority owner, and its shares are divided among
several Western and Polish financial institutions. It has been
struggling to remain independent in a sector that now is about 60
percent controlled by foreign capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1133 </TRAILER>
