<DOCNO> APW20000512.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- Serial killer Michael Ross received six
death sentences today, six years after his original death penalty
was overturned by the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas P. Miano ordered the execution be held Sept. 15,
although all death sentences are automatically stayed pending
Supreme Court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will have closure when you are gone and you know longer have
the breath of life that you took from my daughter,'' said Ellen
Roode, whose 14-year-old daughter, April Brunais, was one of four
teen-age girls Ross was convicted of kidnapping and killing in
eastern Connecticut the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Ross sometimes cried as he apologized to the families of his
victims. He said any apology is inadequate but ''an absence of an
apology would be even more unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentence was handed down according to the verdict of a
Superior Court jury, which last month found that Ross should not be
spared the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Miano rejected a last-minute appeal by the defense that claimed
last week's Supreme Court decision in another death row appeal had
bearing on the case. The high court overturned Terry Johnson's
death sentence, ruling that the jury erred in finding that the
Griswold man killed state Trooper Russell Bagshaw in a cruel and
heinous manner.
</P>
<P>
   Ross admitted preying on his victims as they walked or
hitchhiked down quiet country roads in New London County. He raped
some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were Robin Stavinsky, 19, of Norwich; Wendy
Baribeault, 17, of Jewett City; and two 14-year-old friends,
Brunais and Leslie Shelley, both of Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, Ross claimed a disorder called sexual sadism
drove him to rape and kill -- a defense the jury last month
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, 40, was convicted of the slayings and sentenced to death
in 1987, but the state Supreme Court in 1994 overturned the
penalty. The high court ruled that information was withheld from
the defense that might have helped Ross get life in prison and
ordered a new penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview from death row at Northern Correctional
Institution in Somers last month, Ross said he does not want his
lawyers to file any non-mandatory appeals. But he appeared to
change his mind while addressing the court today.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said that he is sickened at the thought that a higher court
could overturn the sentence and prolong the case, but has
authorized his lawyers to do what they must to complete the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers raised numerous issues at Ross' monthlong
penalty trial that may be used in an appeal. Miano and the lawyers
were forging new law for death penalty cases, since Ross was the
first person in Connecticut to have one penalty hearing for four
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders who are representing Ross also want to use his
case to highlight alleged racial inequalities in the death penalty
system. Ross is white and his victims were white, but lawyers think
Ross' case is part of a pattern where all death penalty victims are
white.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' case already has taken several roller-coaster rides
through the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Ross and prosecutors reached a written agreement to
waive appeals and put Ross to death. The Supreme Court refused to
answer questions about the legality of the deal and Miano later
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a new penalty hearing last summer, the case ended
up before the high court again over ground rules for the
prosecution and the defense in the hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 1139 </TRAILER>
