<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton in Ohio To Push China Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- A dozen protesters against a landmark China
trade bill greeted President Clinton with signs reading ''no blank
checks for China'' as he arrived here today to push Congress to
extend permanent normal trade relations to the Asian nation.
Business leaders, on the other hand, embrace the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Akron is a stronghold of union opposition, yet manufacturing
companies, such as Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co., the area's largest
employer, are enthusiastic about prospects for expanded trade with
the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   On a two-state swing through the Midwest to drum up grass-roots
support for the legislation, Clinton said passage of the bill would
ease China's entrance into the World Trade Organization, tear down
barriers to trade and investment with America and lead to more
stable relations.
</P>
<P>
   ''What they get is membership in the club. What they give us is
membership dues. That's the way you have to look at this,'' Clinton
told business and labor leaders at a round-table discussion that
was closed to reporters. ''The access, on purely economic terms,
is, I think, quite impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to Ohio, a leader in machinery exports, at the
invitation of Rep. Thomas Sawyer, D-Ohio, who has not yet publicly
declared his position on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   One of the protesters outside the National Guard Armory was Don
Bingman. ''I've been a letter carrier for 32 years and I've seen
what free trade has done to the tire industry in Akron,'' said
Bingman, a member of Local 148 of the National Association of
Letter Carriers. ''I decided it was time for me as an individual to
take a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the original four tire companies in Akron now make tires
there. Goodyear has factories in China.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Clinton was traveling to friendlier turf -- the
Hauer family farm in Shakopee, Minn., which could profit from
expanded agricultural sales to China. The farm, 18 miles southwest
of Minneapolis, is in a growing area where farms are becoming
subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's farm community is backing passage of the trade deal,
says Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., who represents the congressional
district where the farm is located.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the near future, 75 percent of agricultural market growth
will be in Asia. China accounts for half of that growth,'' Minge
said in a letter urging his constituents to back the measure.
''Europe, Australia and New Zealand will gladly fill that market if
our farmers are not allowed.''
</P>
<P>
   A tug of war over votes on the measure is being hard-fought in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Commerce Secretary William Daley, the Clinton
administration's point man on China, told Republicans that if they
want the bill to pass, they'll have to agree to the formation of a
commission to monitor China's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a watchdog commission, which would issue an annual
report to Congress, has been suggested by Reps. Sander Levin,
D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb. The commission could recommend
economic sanctions against China outside of the trade area, such as
withholding U.S. loans.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer was considering the commission idea.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
