<HEADLINE> Justice OKs Waste Deal Changes  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department approved an $80 million
exchange of waste-collection and -disposal assets between Allied
Waste Industries and Superior Services Inc. after the companies
agreed to sell some assets to preserve competition.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with the government, Superior must sell
commercial waste-collection operations and transfer stations in
Milwaukee and Mansfield, Ohio, and must abandon it purchase of
Allied's landfill in Leeper, Pa., the department announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court here to block the
original deal, the government alleged that proposal would have
resulted in higher prices for waste hauling and disposal in these
areas. Along with the lawsuit, the government filed the agreement
that would settle the lawsuit, if the court approves it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without restructuring this deal, consumers in parts of Ohio,
Wisconsin and Pennsylvania would have paid higher prices for waste
collection and disposal,'' said Assistant Attorney General Joel I.
Klein, head of the department's antitrust division. ''This
resolution ensures that the benefits of competition -- lower prices
and better service -- will be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Allied and Superior are two of only three major competitors
hauling waste in Milwaukee and they are the only two significant
waste haulers in Mansfield, the government said. In addition, they
are the only two landfill operators in the Leeper area.
</P>
<P>
   These companies contract to haul trash and garbage from
residential and commercial customers to disposal sites, like
landfills, incinerators and transfer stations, which legally
dispose of the waste for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Allied, based in Scottsdale, Ariz., is the second largest waste
hauling and disposal company in the nation and had 1999 sales of $6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Superior, based in Milwaukee, had U.S. revenues of more than
$300 million in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
