<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Fights Gay Sailor Over Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- A man who resigned from the U.S. Naval
Academy amid accusations of homosexuality has been ordered to repay
the government for his education, even though a Navy review panel
found he was treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   The academy began investigating Tommie Lee Watkins Jr. in 1997
following alleged homosexual behavior, which is banned in the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins, president of his class and an aspiring Navy pilot, said
he was pressured to resign and did so because he feared homophobia
would prevent him from receiving a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn H. Becraft, assistant secretary of the Navy for
manpower, ordered Watkins in March to repay the government nearly
$67,000.
</P>
<P>
   But a report issued in November by the Navy's highest personnel
review panel, made public today by The Washington Post, said making
Watkins reimburse the government violates Pentagon policy.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 policy says those discharged for being gay should only be
required to repay the government under certain circumstances that
require a specific written finding of homosexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no finding of any aggravated homosexual behavior,''
the Board for Correction of Naval Records said in its report, which
was made available to The Associated Press today by William Ferris,
Watkins' lawyer. ''Accordingly, the board believes that directing
recoupment was inappropriate in Watkins's case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferris said he will file suit next month in U.S. District Court
in Baltimore, asking that the Navy be required to follow the
board's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Becraft contended that Watkins, who resigned rather than face
charges, voluntarily left the academy. Because of that, she argued,
the Pentagon policy does not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Ferris said it is absurd for the Navy to tell Watkins he will be
kicked out if he doesn't resign and then insist he pay for his
education because he agreed to leave voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ''I assert it is because I am an African-American homosexual,''
Watkins, now 25, told the Post.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists say the practice of requiring reimbursement
-- either in cash or through enlisted service -- from officer
trainees who leave the academy in their junior or senior years is
especially burdensome for homosexuals, who cannot enlist under the
ban on gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a particularly insidious twist to a policy which itself
places so many burdens on people,'' said Joseph C. Steffan, who was
himself expelled from the academy shortly before his 1987
graduation for acknowledging he was gay.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 15 upperclassmen who left the Naval Academy in the
1998-99 school year, 87 percent had to reimburse the government or
enlist.
</P>
<P>
   Among midshipmen who resigned in recent years but did not have
to reimburse the government were 24 who were expelled from the
academy in 1994 for cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ''Such misconduct strikes at the heart of the honor system at
the Academy since these midshipmen were involved in lying, cheating
and stealing, all honor offenses,'' the board said.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with them, Watkins ''was treated unfairly'' the board
said.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Watkins erupted in April 1997, when a
midshipman claimed Watkins had made advances to him and other
midshipmen. A legal officer who reviewed the case said there was
not enough evidence to support several of the allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1245 </TRAILER>
