<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls in European Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was lower against most other key
currencies in European trading today. Gold prices fell.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 90.80 cents, up from 90.10 cents on
Thursday. Later, in midday trading in New York, the euro traded at
90.95 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included 108.70 Japanese yen, up from 108.60; 1.7082 Swiss francs,
down from 1.7252; 1.4868 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4891.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5174, up from $1.4968.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 108.81 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5148.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.1535 German marks,
down from 2.1700; 7.2194 French francs, down from 7.2763; 2.4254
Dutch guilders, down from 2.4445; 2131.05 Italian lire, down from
2,147.83.
</P>
<P>
   Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $276.60 bid
per troy ounce, down from $276.80 late Thursday. In Zurich the bid
price was $276.00, down from $276.90. In Hong Kong, gold closed at
$276.15 an ounce, down $1.80 from Wednesday's final price of
$277.95. The market was closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.01 bid per troy ounce, up from
$4.97.
</P>
