<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-abortion leader says he won't run for Senate  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Anti-abortion activist and Operation Rescue
founder Randall Terry said Friday he will not launch a U.S. Senate
candidacy even if Republican Rudolph Giuliani drops out of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Terry's announcement came after months of saying he was
considering a Senate run because the New York City mayor as well as
rival Hillary Rodham Clinton are abortion rights supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''A protracted bankruptcy and serious personal financial and
family difficulties'' led to the decision to withdraw, Terry said.
He filed for bankruptcy after facing civil litigation from
abortion-rights groups and is separated from his wife of 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''For those reasons I've decided not to run, and I can tell you
it's the most difficult decision I've had to make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in June, Terry said he will take a year-long
sabbatical from public life.
</P>
<P>
   He said he is convinced that Giuliani -- plagued by prostate
cancer and marital woes -- will pull out of the race. By announcing
he's not going to jump into the fray, Terry said he's offering the
state's Republican leadership an ''olive branch'' in the hope it
will look for an anti-abortion candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pro-life movement cannot stand the possibility of Clinton
being senator. But it is the conviction of a lot of pro-lifers that
Rudy Giuliani is even a greater danger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry had hinted at a possible Senate run, even as a spoiler,
for several months. He said he would have raised at least $2
million to $3 million from anti-abortion constituents alone and
gotten 5 percent to 7 percent of the votes. In a neck-and-neck
race, Terry said that percentage may be the ''margin of defeat for
Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry said he will ''leave to the power-brokers'' to decide
alternative candidates, adding that a candidate who is ''pro-life,
pro-family and somewhat conservative'' would have no trouble
raising campaign funds nationwide ''from people who want to see an
end to the Clinton era.''
</P>
<P>
   While not endorsing any specific person, Terry said U.S. Rep.
Rick Lazio of Long Island, an abortion rights supporter, would be
''unacceptable.'' He added that Rep. Peter King, also of Long
Island, is a ''viable candidate.'' Both Lazio and King have been
mentioned as possible alternative GOP candidates if Giuliani scraps
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Terry returned to New York after lobbying unsuccessfully against
legislation in Vermont that legalized same-sex civil unions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Terry lost a bid for a Republican congressional
nomination in New York but stayed in the race as the Right to Life
Party's candidate. Democratic incumbent Maurice Hinchey was
re-elected in that race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 1302 </TRAILER>
