<DOCNO> APW20000512.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two men ignore health, age to save fishermen from deadly dam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A stroke, pneumonia and a heart condition
weren't enough to keep Ronald Tougas, 75, and Gordon Trotter, 81,
from saving two fishermen in a raging, frigid river with a
reputation for death.
</P>
<P>
   Tougas of Marlboro, Mass., and Trotter were at Trotter's
northern New York home along the Schroon River Wednesday 75 miles
north of Albany, when they spotted something in the powerful
current, coming their way. At first it looked like a turtle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then all of a sudden I saw the body pop up and I knew it was a
person,'' Tougas told the Glens Falls Post-Star.
</P>
<P>
   ''They shouted, 'Please come in and get us! Please!''' recalled
Leona Trotter on Friday of Wednesday's rescue. But she knew they
couldn't jump in. She's in her 80s and legally blind, her husband
was hospitalized over the winter after what was apparently a small
stroke and pneumonia, and Tougas has a heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Tougas saw another head and body emerge from the
turbulent current. Then a small rowboat surfaced. Tougas and
Trotter quickly cut a rope from the dock at Trotter's home, and
watched as the river rush the two anglers toward them in the water.
They were able to get the rope to one of the men and quickly drag
him to shore at Trotter's home.
</P>
<P>
   But the other fisherman was still clinging to the overturned row
boat and moving downstream.
</P>
<P>
   ''At one point, they heard him say, 'I can't hold on much
longer,''' said Warren County sheriff's Patrol Officer John Maday.
</P>
<P>
   But the rescuers persisted, following the man south as the river
carried him away, trying to fling the rope to him. Three homes
downstream, they managed to get it to him and pull him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Police later Wednesday praised Trotter and Tougas, saying they
likely saved the life of at least the second man, Clark Talham, 36,
who wasn't a strong swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ''These guys were lucky,'' Maday said. ''I don't think they
would have made it if it wasn't for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Talham and Stephen Koblensky, 39, both of the Schroon Lake area,
didn't require medical treatment after they were fished from the
river.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature of the water was in the upper 40s, but that
wasn't the biggest danger. The powerful current at the dam claimed
more than a half-dozen lives in 20 years, three in the summer of
1992 alone. It has taken searchers days to recover bodies in the
still popular fishing spots for trout and salmon. Among the dead
since the Trotters moved retired to their riverside log cabin in
1981 are a boy, his dog he was trying to save, a father and his
son.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good thing we were down there,'' Tougas said. ''That
river is ice cold. They could hardly breathe when they got out.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotter, a retired state Thruway Authority worker, and Tougas,
who is visiting for a week at the Trotters' log cabin, happened to
be out moving lumber at the river's edge when they spotted the
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   ''The river is beautiful, but it's treacherous this time of
year,'' said Leona Trotter, who retired years ago from the
Cooperative Extension agricultural service in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Tougas tried to buy a floatation device and 100 feet of rope to
tie to a tree for anyone to use to use in rescues. But he couldn't.
The Palmer Brothers Marine Outfitters shop in Brandt Lake that he
went insisted on providing the $80 in wares to the heroes for free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
