<HEADLINE> European Stocks Rise in Thin Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Technology and telecom stocks once again set the
pace for firmer European equity markets Friday, taking their cue
from across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall performance of European markets was subdued amid
relatively thin trade as investors held back ahead of next
Tuesday's U.S. Federal Reserve meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index closed 4.62 points or 1.4 percent, up
at 389.18. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx index, which tracks companies
in countries that joined the single currency, ended up 5.38 points,
or 1.3 percent, at 436.96.
</P>
<P>
   Among telecoms, London's Kingston Communications jumped 56 pence
to 688 pence, or 9 percent, while Vodafone AirTouch advanced 7.5
pence to 278 pence on an optimistic outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Among high-tech stocks, ARM Holdings gained 20 pence to 646
pence.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong performing sector was cyclical goods and
services, up 2.3 percent, as analysts reported switching into the
sector amid expectations that interest rates might peak at a lower
rate than had been feared.
</P>
<P>
   Old economy stocks were again in the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, BMW fell on talk that Rover left a
bigger-than-expected dent in the company's balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index closed up 9.80
points, or 0.1 percent, at 7,269.28. The Paris CAC 40 index ended
69.14 points ahead at 6,449.27, or 1.1 percent, and in London the
FTSE-100 finished 37.6 points higher at 6,283.5, or 0.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
