<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea To Resume Talks on War Dead  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of stalemate, North Korea has
agreed to resume talks on excavating an area in North Korea where
U.S. officials believe they could unearth the remains of several
hundred Americans killed in the Korean War, a U.S. official said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before the end of June we should be back to the table'' to
negotiate details of the arrangement, Robert Jones, head of the
Pentagon office in charge of POW and missing-in-action issues, said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the North Koreans want to hold the talks in Thailand
and the Pentagon is not opposed to that.
</P>
<P>
   If the talks lead to a U.S. excavation project, it would mark a
resumption of recovery operations that were halted last year when
the Defense Department balked at a North Korean demand for a new
program of American humanitarian donations, including the
construction of factories to produce children's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The area targeted for U.S. recovery operations is near Unsan, a
site of major battles between elements of the U.S. Army's 8th
Cavalry Regiment and Chinese troops that had swept south across the
Yalu River in early November of 1950 in a surprise offensive. The
Pentagon believes more than 500 sets of remains could be recovered
in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, U.S. recovery operations in North Korea have yielded
42 sets of remains. More than 8,000 servicemen are still missing
from the war -- many from the battles with Chinese troops in late
1950.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-North Korean negotiations on an arrangement for recovery
operations in 2000 broke off last December. Several weeks later,
the North Koreans notified the Pentagon that a land reclamation
project in the Unsan area had turned up human remains and personal
belongings that indicated they were American.
</P>
<P>
   Among the personal items the North Koreans said they found was
the dog tag of Charles E. Sizemore, who according to Pentagon
records was a soldier from Rush County, Ind., who went missing on
Nov. 2, 1950. At first the North Koreans claimed they had about 400
sets of remains from this site, but later they said they had only a
few but believed that a scientific excavation could locate hundreds
more.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he hopes an agreement to conduct a recovery operation
in the Unsan area could lead to similar operations later this year
in the vicinity of the Chosin Reservoir, where many Marines were
lost in late 1950 when they encountered an onslaught of Chinese
forces from across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Pentagon also will seek North Korean agreement to
excavate in areas on the North Korean side of the Yalu River where
many prisoner-of-war camps were established and hundreds of GIs are
known to have died.
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, Jones expressed optimism about persuading
China to cooperate more fully in U.S. research into the fate of
American servicemen held in Korean War POW camps that were run by
the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he expects to travel to Beijing this month to kick
off an oral history project in which American officials are to
interview Chinese veterans who were involved in running Korean War
POW camps. During and after the war, U.S. intelligence reports
indicated that some American prisoners of war were taken into China
from POW camps in North Korea. China has never acknowledged that
this happened.
</P>
<P>
   On a more pessimistic note, Jones said he saw no indication that
China was ready to open up its military archives to Pentagon
researchers. Nor has it provided any information on 44 American
servicemen who are missing from the war and whom the Pentagon
believes China should have information about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
