<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Joins National Geographic  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two of Washington's most respected
organizations -- the Smithsonian Institution and the National
Geographic Society -- have launched their first large-scale joint
endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   The project, ''Forces of Change,'' takes a new and detailed look
at the geological, environmental and cultural forces that shape the
Earth, combining the efforts of the Smithsonian's National Museum
of Natural History and National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   Components include a book, on sale now; a temporary exhibit of
28 large-format photographs opening at the museum June 8 and a
permanent exhibit hall at the museum currently under development.
</P>
<P>
   The two institutions stand just blocks apart in downtown
Washington and their scientists have worked together in the past,
but this was the first major project they have undertaken together
that officials could recall.
</P>
<P>
   ''In this case it was simply that we had a great book idea and
wanted to find the publisher who would do best by it,'' said museum
director Robert Fri. ''National Geographic looked like the best one
for this book and it's turned out really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Smithsonian scientists contributed to the volume, along
with a cross section of academics and other experts.
</P>
<P>
   ''For thousands of years, people believed in the balance of
nature, that nature was constant,'' commented Daniel Botkin of
George Mason University in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scientific research of the late 20th century showed, to the
contrary, that nature is always changing and has no single, perfect
condition,'' said Botkin, head of the university's Program on
Global Change, who wrote the preface to the book.
</P>
<P>
   ''Forces of Change represents the Smithsonian's commitment to
better understanding our world, the changes that have brought us to
this point and what we face at the start of the 21st century,''
added Fri.
</P>
<P>
   The upcoming photo exhibit at the museum focuses on three of the
book's 14 chapters, with the permanent exhibit to include more
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Those three are photographs of landscape and geologic vistas
contrasting the effects of nature and human occupation, accompanied
by text by writer John McPhee; a section on coral reefs under the
study of museum biologist William Kiene and ''Ritual Earth,'' a
section in which Smithsonian anthropologist Michael Mason tells how
cultures around the world use ritual and art to relate to nature.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ''Forces of Change: A New View of Nature,'' also
includes essays by Smithsonian geologist Alan Cutler, Stanford
biologist Gretchen C. Daily, University of Virginia meteorologist
Michael Garstang, Harvard professor Stephen Jay Gould, Smithsonian
Indian expert George P. Horse Capture and essayist David Quammen,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian Institution was established in 1846 and has
grown to include sixteen museums and galleries and the National Zoo
and numerous research facilities in the United States and abroad.
When Englishman James Smithson left funds for its creation he
directed that it work for the ''increase and diffusion of
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two years later, on the evening of Jan. 13, 1888,
thirty-three men gathered at Washington's Cosmos Club to found
National Geographic, ''a society for the increase and diffusion of
geographical knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Museum of Natural History: http://www.mnh.si.edu
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic: http://www.nationalgeographic.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1420 </TRAILER>
