<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: More time to first major challenge of death penalty  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's highest court Friday gave
defense lawyers nearly four months more to file legal papers in the
case which represents the first major constitutional challenge to
New York's revived death penalty law.
</P>
<P>
   The revised timetable means the Court of Appeals is unlikely to
hear the appeal of Darrel Harris until at least the summer of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Brooklyn district attorney's office and the
state Capital Defender Office both asked the Court of Appeals for
more time to formulate arguments in the complex case.
</P>
<P>
   Without comment, the court said Friday it was extending from
June 19 to Oct. 17 the deadline the Capital Defender Office has to
file its defense brief in the case.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, will push back other filing deadlines in the
case. Prosecutors have until April 20, 2001, to file their brief
and the defense has until June 15, 2001, for its reply brief to the
prosecution's brief.
</P>
<P>
   It is only after digesting all of that paper that the Court of
Appeals will hear oral arguments in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The expanding time frame is emblematic of complexity of
challenges to death penalty statutes not only in New York but
elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   When the revived death penalty statute went into effect in New
York on Sept. 1, 1995, experts predicted that because of
constitutional challenges to the law and individual offenders'
appeals, no one would be executed for at least a decade in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Doyle, head of the Capital Defenders Office, said the
expanding time frame is necessary to cope with the ''unique''
nature of the Harris case, ''its legal complexity and the stakes
and its implications for New York's jurisprudence.'' Complicating
that is the fact there was little development of capital punishment
court rulings in New York between the mid-1960s, when the state
abandoned the death penalty, and its revival in the mid-1990s,
Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Salomon, Doyle's first deputy, told the Court of Appeals
judges on Wednesday that her office's incomplete brief in the
Harris case is 800 pages long. Doyle said the office would try to
''bring the brief in'' at fewer than 800 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The Capital Defender Office earlier filed a statement with the
Court of Appeals listing 39 issues it was likely to raise in the
Harris appeal. They included both general constitutional challenges
to the death penalty law and specific complaints about the way
Harris was indicted, tried and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon said some of the 39 points have been dropped, but others
have been added.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was the first person sentenced to death under the capital
punishment statute George Pataki promised to enact during his
successful 1994 gubernatorial campaign against Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, a Brooklyn jury recommended execution for Harris
after finding the former state prison guard guilty of killing three
people at a Brooklyn social club.
</P>
<P>
   Since Harris became the first person on death row in New York
since 1984, four other inmates have joined him. Death row is
located at the Clinton Correctional Facility near the U.S.-Canadian
border.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the seven-member court has only interpreted parts of the
statute and not considered broader constitutional questions about
the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 1421 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Defective Product Penalties?  </HEADLINE>
By REBECCA SINDERBRAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton unveiled the
president's plan Friday to toughen civil and criminal penalties for
companies that fail to notify the government or consumers about
potentially dangerous products.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would upgrade willful criminal violations of
product safety laws from misdemeanors to felonies, and eliminate
the $1.65 million cap on civil penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this legislation, the punishment will finally start to
fit the crime,'' said Mrs. Clinton, who called million-dollar fines
''just a drop in the bucket'' with little impact on the profit
margins of large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Although the changes would apply to most consumer products,
Friday's announcement focused on children's products.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today reported last month that at least 17 firms had been
accused of keeping quiet about dangerous children's products since
1997. CPSC Chairman Ann Brown said she had witnessed ''a continuing
trend of nonreporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the CPSC assessed $922,500 in fines, 10 times as much
as it did 10 years ago. So far this year, fines have totaled more
than $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   In April, toy giant Hasbro Inc. agreed to pay a $400,000 civil
penalty for failing to give consumers and the government timely
notification about a defect in an infant carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro waited until it had received 12 reports of infant carrier
handles spontaneously unlatching, causing seven skull fractures,
before informing the government of the problem and recalling the
carriers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the recall, Hasbro continued to deny that the product
had any defects or that the company violated any law.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said Friday that about half the products that
eventually face federal recalls are not reported to the CPSC by the
companies themselves but come to light through consumer complaints,
federal investigations, emergency room records and even coroners'
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added that too often, the CPSC had been forced to rely on
its own ''detective work.''
</P>
<P>
   In one instance last year, there were more than 3,000 complaints
against and 42 children injured in a combination child safety seat
and infant carrier manufactured by Kolcraft Enterprises before the
company agreed to a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based Kolcraft never officially reported the defect
before the government stepped in and launched an investigation,
federal regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's plan also includes an enhanced reporting
network, administered by the CPSC, to more effectively bring
children's product injury information to the agency's attention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1424 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 97; Nasdaq Gains 91  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today after the government's
report of a decline in wholesale prices in April helped quell
recent worries about inflationary pressures and higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 97.32 at 10,643.29 in
afternoon trading. The Nasdaq composite index was up 91.40 at
3,590.98.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also were higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 17.89 at 1,425.70.
</P>
<P>
   The market had nervously awaited the Labor Department's
wholesale price report, issued before trading began today. And
investors were rewarded with a 0.3 percent decline in April that
reversed two months of increases. It was the best showing on
inflation at the wholesale level since February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The benign reading on inflation came after a series of
indicators had showed strength in the economy and raised worries
that the Federal Reserve would move aggressively to raise borrowing
costs at the next meeting of its policymaking committee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices have seesawed in recent weeks as investors
alternately fretted and relaxed about interest rates. Today's
report removed a measure of nervousness from the market, but didn't
change most analysts' expectations that the Fed will raise rates by
a half-percentage point at Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results represent a fine performance on inflation,'' said
Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America. Still,
he said, ''we'll stick with the call for 50 basis points at next
week's meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, technology stocks have stumbled amid the
continuing belief that prices were bid too high last year and early
this year. Today, they were among the biggest gainers. Dell
Computer, which released an upbeat earnings report late Thursday,
rose 5\ to 49 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cisco Systems, hurt earlier this week by a negative
article in Barron's, was up 1[ at 61]. Intel was up 2} at 118 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks were mixed after J.P. Morgan analyst Susan
Walker White lowered her price target for nearly a dozen companies
in the sector. Among the stocks she singled out: Switchboard, which
fell ] to 10}.
</P>
<P>
   But larger companies that White downgraded remained unscathed.
Yahoo! rose 4| to 129 15/16, and eBay gained 6\ to 124.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a 5-to-4 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 593.11 million
shares, compared with 637.73 million at the same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 6.58 points to 495.97.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
