<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Prices Fall in April  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wholesale prices fell in April for the first
time in 14 months as energy costs took their biggest dive in nine
years, more than outweighing a sharp jump in food prices.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the good news on inflation, economists expect the
Federal Reserve will push interest rates higher next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures
before they reach consumers, dipped an expected 0.3 percent last
month after having shot up in February and March, the Labor
Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core''
rate of inflation in April rose for the second straight month by
just 0.1 percent, also matching many analysts' forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good report. When I look at it, I kind of say where's
the inflation?'' said Donald Ratajczak, director of Georgia State
University's economic forecasting project. ''Sure, you got problems
in a few spot areas but you are always going to have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors liked the report. The Dow Jones industrial average
gained 112 points and Nasdaq added 102 points in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
   But economists weren't as sanguine. Even though Friday's report
suggested that inflation at the wholesale level was quiet last
month, it came after a series of other economic indicators showing
great strength in the economy and rising wage and inflation
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   And that has led a growing number of economists to predict that
Fed policy-makers will boost interest rates at their meeting
Tuesday by a more aggressive half-point in order to slow the
speeding economy and keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The key to whether the Fed chooses a half-point or a
quarter-point increase may well be determined by the results of
April's Consumer Price Index, economists said. That report will be
released Tuesday, the same day the Fed meets.
</P>
<P>
   ''The CPI is really where all the action,'' said John Hancock
economist William Cheney, who is expecting a half-point interest
rate boost.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has already raised interest rates five times by
a quarter-point each since June in an effort to slow things down a
bit and prevent inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The dip in April's wholesale prices was the first decline since
February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In February and March of this year wholesale prices shot up by 1
percent. In both months, the jolts came from soaring energy prices,
which posted their biggest increases in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But in April, energy prices plunged 4.1 percent, the steepest
decrease since February 1991. Increased crude-oil production
accounted for the decline, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices -- which skyrocketed in February and March -- went
down by 11.7 percent in April, the steepest drop in nearly 11
years. Home-heating oil fell 14 percent, the largest decline since
December 1998. Prices for liquefied petroleum gas, such as propane,
fell 7.8 percent, the biggest decrease since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, wholesale prices have been rising at an annual
rate of 5.4 percent, compared with a 3 percent gain for all of
1999. The increase in this year's wholesale prices largely came
from a pickup in energy costs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, food prices, which rose just 0.1 percent in March
went up a sizable 1 percent in April -- the biggest jump since
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   A record 41.6 percent increase in egg prices led the way. That
surpassed the previous record 24.6 percent increase set in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for eggs for Easter was stronger than supply and pushed
prices up, Ratajczak said. Some economists also blamed the
lingering effects of higher transportation costs stemming from the
prior surge in fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription drug prices also went up 0.5 percent, something
economists partly blamed on increased demand by aging Baby Boomers
and the introduction of more expensive new drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Car prices rose 0.4 percent, while light truck prices fell 0.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, businesses boosted their stockpiles of goods
on shelves and backlots by 0.3 percent in March, down from a 0.5
percent rise the month before.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:The PPI report: http://stats.bls.gov/ppihome.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
