<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, May 12, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deal Creates Largest Ad Company
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- In a deal that would form the world's largest
advertising company, Britain's WPP Group is buying U.S. heavyweight
Young &AMP; Rubicam for $4.7 billion in stock. It would be the ad
industry's biggest deal ever. WPP, which already owns the
U.S.-based ad companies Ogillvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J. Walter
Thompson, said today the acquisition would expand its client base
and generate annual savings of more than $30 million. The two
advertising powerhouses already share a number of major clients,
including Ford Motor Co., Kraft Foods and Sears, Roebuck and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Euro Airlines Seek Online Bookings
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Travel agents want to pull the plug on
a new e-commerce venture that is being set up by Europe's top
airlines in a bid to recapture customers from discount competitors
online. Even before the announcement of the venture led by
Lufthansa, British Airways and Air France, travel agents who once
had a tight grip on booking Europeans' vacations were getting
squeezed by online travel agencies. The three airlines plan to cut
out the middleman and lead eight other carriers in building a
one-stop-shopping Web site for cheap tickets, hotel packages and
car rentals.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale Prices Fall in April
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wholesale prices fell in April for the first
time in 14 months as energy costs took their biggest dive in nine
years, more than outweighing a sharp jump in food prices. But even
with the good news on inflation, economists expect the Federal
Reserve will push interest rates higher next week. The Producer
Price Index, which measures inflation pressures before they reach
consumers, dipped 0.3 percent last month, the Labor Department
reported today. Outside the volatile energy and food categories,
the ''core'' rate of inflation in April rose for the second
straight month by 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Maine Enacts Drug Price Curbs
</P>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- Gov. Angus King has signed legislation
enabling the state to negotiate for prescription drugs at lower
prices. Under the measure the state, as a big buyer, would seek
substantial discounts from suppliers similar to those provided to
other large purchasers, then pass on those savings to consumers. If
negotiations with manufacturers fail to reduce prices
significantly, price controls could still be imposed three years
from now. A spokeswoman for the pharmaceutical industry called the
state law ''the worst piece of legislation I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Report Pushes Dell Shares Higher
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Shares in Dell Computer Corp. rose 11
percent today after the company posted strong first-quarter
earnings that beat Wall Street expectations. A focus on
Internet-related services and equipment coupled with the direct
sale of personal computers helped Dell in the quarter. For the
three months ended April 28, the computer maker posted a 21 percent
increase in profits over the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Feds Take Defective Product Stand
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton unveiled the
president's plan today to toughen civil and criminal penalties for
companies that fail to notify the government or consumers about
potentially dangerous products. The legislation would upgrade
willful criminal violations of product safety laws from
misdemeanors to felonies, and eliminate the $1.65 million cap on
civil penalties. Although the changes would apply to most consumer
products, today's announcement focused on children's products.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Up 51; Nasdaq Gains 55
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today after the government's
report of a decline in wholesale prices in April helped quell
recent worries about inflationary pressures and higher interest
rates. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was
up 51.06 at 10,597.03. The Nasdaq composite index was up 54.86 at
3,554.44. Broader stock indicators also were higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index was up 11.30 at 1,419.11.
</P>
