<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reality Bites Cannes Film Festival  </HEADLINE>
By CLAR NI CHONGHAILE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France (AP) -- Real-life janitors in a film about the
true story of workers struggling to better their lot -- it must be a
movie by Ken Loach, a.k.a. the conscience of Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   The British director and master of social criticism is no
stranger to the star-spangled frenzy of the film festival, even if
he does think dressing up in a dinner jacket makes one look like a
''bourgeois idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't worry about his credibility, though. His films always
inject a dose of gritty reality at Cannes and his latest work,
''Bread and Roses,'' is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   For his first feature film, shot in the United States, the
veteran director turned his critical eye on movie mecca Los
Angeles, but in true Loach tradition, his gaze caught the
underside.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the ''Justice for Janitors'' union campaign that began
in the United States in the late 1980s, the $5.5 million film is
about mainly Latin American immigrant cleaners battling for better
wages and working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Not only true but topical. The ''Justice for Janitors'' movement
continues. Last month, janitors in Los Angeles sealed a new
three-year contract after an aggressive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Mexican actress Pilar Padilla, who did not speak
English when she was chosen for the lead role, plays Maya, a feisty
young woman who sneaks across the U.S. border to join her sister,
Rosa, in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Maya gets a job cleaning offices with Rosa. A chance encounter
with union activist Sam, played by Adrien Brody, draws Maya into
the union struggle and exposes the difficult choices faced by
vulnerable immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the janitors in the movie are played by real janitors --
one of whom was fired before the film ended for taking too much
time off work to act.
</P>
<P>
   In the movie, cleaners clad in red T-shirts invade the swish
chrome-and-glass building they usually tidy by night.
</P>
<P>
   For Scottish scriptwriter Paul Laverty, ''Bread and Roses'' is a
promise kept.
</P>
<P>
   Laverty, who worked with Loach on ''Carla's Song'' and ''My Name
is Joe,'' hooked up with people involved with the ''Justice for
Janitors'' campaign in 1994 in Los Angeles, and promised to take
their story to the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   For Loach, the film exposes a parallel world of semi-invisible
immigrants and the two-faced reception they receive.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is this particular hypocrisy in the way immigrants are
treated -- they are abused for taking jobs and tax money, but on the
other hand, they are cheap labor,'' he said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Brody marched with activists and even took a weekend course in
union organizing to fit the role of a maverick union man.
</P>
<P>
   Padilla and co-star Elpidia Carrillo, who plays Rosa, worked a
night shift with regular janitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We worked hard, with no air conditioning. People come to their
offices and it is so clean and nobody knows how it gets done,''
said Carrillo, who also starred in Oliver Stone's ''Salvador.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrillo, originally from Mexico, gives the strongest
performance, portraying the vulnerable pride, defensiveness and
sheer weariness of a woman who has been battered by life too long.
</P>
<P>
   Loach's film is not an easy ride -- not least because it shifts
between Spanish and English. Some viewers may also think the
idealism is too simplistic and didactic, although Loach takes the
edge off with his trademark humor.
</P>
<P>
   But the acting is strong. Apart from Carrillo's powerful
performance, Padilla is a vibrant Maya and Brody is engaging and
passionate as Sam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1512 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
