<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Faces Challenge in Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAKRA, Lebanon (AP) -- Irish peacekeeper John Mahoney, in blue
U.N. helmet and reinforced flak jacket, kept his tattooed forearm
firmly on the machine gun mounted atop his battered white armored
personnel carrier as it bounced along a winding valley road on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to get worse around here before it gets any
better,'' said Mahoney, a veteran of U.N. peacekeeping duty, as he
surveyed the steep hills and deep wadis where Israeli troops and
their allied Lebanese militia do daily battle with a disciplined
and determined band of Islamic guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, U.N. troops patrolling a
330-square-mile swath of south Lebanon have tried to keep peace in
a place where there is precious little of it to be found -- and do
what they can to keep out of the cross fire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that task is about to become even more difficult and
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, Israel is to withdraw its troops from the buffer
zone it set up 15 years ago to try to protect its northern
communities from cross-border guerrilla attacks. But rather than
calming tensions, the expected pullout may set the stage for a new
explosion of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, the Shiite Muslim guerrilla group spearheading the
fight against Israel and its allied militia, the South Lebanon
Army, has sharply stepped up its attacks in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Upward of a dozen times a day, its fighters -- wielding mortars
or heavy machine guns or rocket-propelled grenades -- stage
hit-and-run attacks against the squat Israeli and SLA bunkers
dotting the rugged, rocky landscape. That is about double the rate
of guerrilla activity in the previous several months, said senior
U.N. adviser Timur Goksel.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah has promised it will gun for Israeli troops until the
last possible moment -- and has hinted, through its spiritual
leader, that it may not lay down its weapons even after the
pullout.
</P>
<P>
   The SLA, meanwhile, increasingly fearful and angry over what
many in its ranks see as impending abandonment by Israel, has been
returning guerrilla fire with indiscriminate shelling and gunfire
that menaces the mainly Shiite Muslim villagers and peacekeepers
alike, the U.N. forces say.
</P>
<P>
   SLA fighters ''have become very nervous -- they open up for no
reason at all, whenever they hear the slightest noise,'' said Maj.
Joe McDonagh, spokesman for the Irish battalion. As he was briefing
a group of visiting reporters, the dull thud of mortars was heard
on the hillside just opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Only 400 yards from the nearest U.N. outpost, almost over the
heads of villagers, the SLA and guerrillas were trading fire again.
Hours earlier, just outside the Irish-patrolled area, an SLA
militiaman had been killed by a guerrilla hit on his outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Such skirmishes can rapidly spiral into wider conflict. Last
week, after SLA shellfire killed two Lebanese civilians, Hezbollah
retaliated with a rocket attack on northern Israel, to which Israel
replied by blasting power installations and a highway deep inside
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the clock ticking down to the Israeli withdrawal --
which is to take place by July 7, but which Israel says could come
even sooner -- many crucial questions about the U.N. role in the
wake of the pullout remain unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. troops -- which now patrol only a small sliver of the
Israeli-occupied zone -- are expected to expand their deployment all
the way down to the Lebanon-Israel border once Israel pulls out.
Diplomatic sources say the addition of up to 2,000 troops to the
current 4,500-member U.N. force is being discussed as part of that
redeployment plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the necessary approval for an expanded force and a larger
U.N. zone has not yet been obtained from the Lebanese government,
which in turn must answer to its domineering neighbor, Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Another crucial task will be to avoid creating a power vacuum in
south Lebanon that rogue elements -- from holdout SLA men to
Palestinian guerrillas -- could rush to fill.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. force still must recruit additional troops and work out
which member nations will contribute them. But that will take time,
and in the days and hours following what could be a precipitous
Israeli pullout, delays could make the U.N. deployment far more
difficult and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   And it is the United Nations that must certify the completion of
the Israeli pullout -- not as straightforward a matter as it
appears, as Israel must meet several conditions in addition to
pulling out its troops. Those include the disbanding of the SLA and
the release of detainees from the notorious SLA-run Khiam prison
inside the Israeli-controlled zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
