<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dept. Refutes Spying Allegation  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department on Friday dismissed an
FBI assertion that foreign governments were planting spies in the
building posing as reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the department tightened a nine-month old rule
and informed reporters they would be stripped of their access to
the building if found by guards above the second floor without a
government escort.
</P>
<P>
   ''During working hours, you are allowed to go to the cafeteria.
But any appointments, any visits, any discussions, any time you
need to go above the second floor, you're supposed to be
escorted,'' department spokesman Richard Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   The press office, the briefing room and a room for reporters to
work are on the second floor and can be reached only by building
pass. Guards are posted at the entrances on the first floor and
patrol all areas of the building.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying Thursday before the House International Relations
Committee on security lapses, Timothy Bereznay, an FBI section
chief, said the FBI knew of spies who used press credentials to get
into and around the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''If asked, the FBI would be willing to identify to the State
Department permanent media badge holders identified as hostile
intelligence officers so that their access could be restricted or
their visits monitored,'' Bereznay said.
</P>
<P>
   And Assistant Secretary of State David Carpenter, who is in
charge of diplomatic security, said Thursday that ''if it was
within my power, I would not have any press in the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright appeared taken by surprise
by Bereznay's testimony. She said she was trying to tighten
security and that ''obviously, we don't want spies posing as
journalists.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Albright also remarked at a news conference: ''I think we
have to be careful here not to go crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the FBI issued a statement saying ''if the FBI is in
possession of any information of that nature, we would share it
with the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Boucher flatly disputed Bereznay's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this time, we are not aware of any information that any
members of the foreign press are utilizing the media as cover for
intelligence activities at the State Department,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And ''I think I can safely say that we're not aware of any
American press that are using this as cover for intelligence
activities,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher also dismissed as without foundation a report last week
that Israel was secretly tapping telephone at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Bereznay implied that some of the foreign agents with press
credentials represented hostile powers.
</P>
<P>
   He said the FBI, in order to protect sources and sensitive
cases, does not customarily provide other agencies with lists of
intelligence officer identities.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said there are 467 Americans with
department press credentials and 56 foreign media. These include
reporters, photographers, camera operators and technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher, warning them they should not venture unescorted beyond
a limited area, said there were guards posted everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're found above the second floor with a press badge and
not an escort, the badge will be taken away from you and you will
not get it back. So there's zero tolerance for this and we do have
ways of checking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded reporters traditionally have been able to move freely
about most of the building -- excluding those parts marked
off-limits -- Boucher said: ''The issue is that we can't have people
who don't have security clearances wandering this building
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
