<HEADLINE> Dow Up 87; Nasdaq Gains 71  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today after the government's
report of a decline in wholesale prices in April helped quell
recent worries about inflationary pressures and higher interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 87.73 at 10,633.70. The Nasdaq
composite index was up 71.34 at 3,570.92.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also were higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 18.14 at 1,425.95.
</P>
<P>
   The market had nervously awaited the Labor Department's
wholesale price report, issued before trading began today.
Investors were rewarded with a 0.3 percent decline in April that
reversed two months of increases. It was the best showing on
inflation at the wholesale level since February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The benign reading on inflation came after a series of
indicators had showed strength in the economy and raised worries
that the Federal Reserve would move aggressively to raise borrowing
costs at the next meeting of its policy-making committee on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices have seesawed in recent weeks as investors
alternately fretted and relaxed about interest rates. Today's
report removed a measure of nervousness from the market, but didn't
change most analysts' expectations that the Fed will raise rates by
a half-percentage point at Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results represent a fine performance on inflation,'' said
Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America. Still,
he said, ''we'll stick with the call for 50 basis points at next
week's meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, technology stocks have stumbled amid the
continuing belief that prices were bid too high last year and early
this year. Today, they were among the biggest gainers. Dell
Computer, which released an upbeat earnings report late Thursday,
rose 5 5/16 to 50.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Cisco Systems, hurt earlier this week by a negative
article in Barron's, was up 7/16 at 60 11/16. Intel was up 1 3/16
at 116}.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, a spinoff of Hewlett-Packard, soared 15 7/16 to 92
after a Goldman Sachs analyst said the company is a likely addition
to the S&AMP;P 500. Agilent's full split from its parent company takes
effect June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks were mixed after J.P. Morgan analyst Susan
Walker White lowered her price target for nearly a dozen companies
in the sector. Among the stocks she singled out: Switchboard, which
fell ] to 10}.
</P>
<P>
   But larger companies that White downgraded remained unscathed.
Yahoo! rose 3 1/16 to 128], and eBay gained 4 23/32 to 122 15/32.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a 5-to-4 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 693.28 million
shares, compared with 756.87 million at the same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 4.90 points to 494.29.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
