<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Presidential Image in Mexico  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- For decades, Mexican presidential campaigns
followed a time-honored ritual: A hired band struck up a tune and
trucked-in supporters cheered as the candidate roared into town in
a convoy of luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   A quick, lachrymose speech praising the poor and promising a
better future -- and then the candidate's convoy rumbled off to
another impoverished town.
</P>
<P>
   Over seven decades, the result was always the same: the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, won the election.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was amazing how dull Mexican campaigns were,'' says
political analyst Delal Baer. ''There was no lively rhetoric. They
were convoluted, stilted.
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Political marketing -- polling firms, political advisers, the
news media -- have become key to Mexico's July 2 presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates have been accused of publishing false poll results,
using foreign advisers, receiving preferential treatment from the
news media, pitching their message to the United States and using
spin rather than substance.
</P>
<P>
   PRI candidate Francisco Labastida, a courtly, gray-haired former
governor, joined in a hip-shaking dance with other guests on a
morning talk show this week.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign rallies, Labastida often remains the distant
platform speaker. By contrast, conservative opposition candidate
Vicente Fox has mixed with the crowds, even speaking in the spicy
slang most Mexicans use in daily life but studiously avoid in
public.
</P>
<P>
   Image-building has become even more important as polls show Fox
nearly even in the polls with Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. political consultant James Carville seems to have helped
define Labastida's campaign slogan -- ''change with a course'' --
meant to overcome the corrupt image the PRI has acquired during 71
years in power.
</P>
<P>
   Carville -- who summed up President Clinton's 1992 campaign with
the phrase ''It's the economy, stupid'' -- defined Labastida's theme
as ''It's the right kind of change, stupid'' in October.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida frequently accuses Fox, of the National Action Party,
of catering to Americans. When Fox went to meet with
Mexican-Americans in the United States, Labastida accused him of
negotiating with ''his American partners'' to sell out Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida -- who employs Washington-based political consultant
Stan Greenberg for polling and focus groups -- says his own polls
are more reliable than National Action polls showing Fox ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, meanwhile, produced some questionable polls saying that
Labastida won a recent debate -- most here saw it as a Fox victory --
and at least one state governor prodded newspapers to publish them.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has cleaned up his language, reportedly after market
research showed that Mexicans want something closer to the
formality they are accustomed to in a president.
</P>
<P>
   All the candidates rely more on television ads and sound clips
than ever before, though the independent observer group Civic
Alliance says coverage is still often slanted.
</P>
<P>
   On television, opposition candidates are often seen fielding
hostile questions while Labastida is shown in front of cheering
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no doubt the mold is breaking.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate's wife once stood in the background at campaign
rallies, along with local politicians who hoped to ride his
coattails to victory. Now, both local politicians and some would-be
first ladies are waging their own battles.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's wife took a spin -- on her own -- through one of
Mexico City's rougher neighborhoods to talk about crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's the first wife of a candidate with her own
personality,'' said Miguel Acosta of the Mexican Human Rights
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   The four candidates from smaller parties, some of whom show no
evidence of marketing advice, seem upset by the new style.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't let yourselves be steamrolled by empty marketing,''
candidate Porfirio Munoz Ledo of the Authentic Revolution Party
told voters during a televised debate. ''This isn't a choice being
made in a supermarket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
