<HEADLINE> Study Raises Cell Phone Concerns  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Worms that were exposed to microwave radiation of the
sort
emitted by cellular phones underwent biological changes that can
disrupt the functioning of their cells, a study found.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The experiment's results do not directly address the effects of
prolonged use of cell phones on human health.
</P>
<P>
   But the study raises concerns, said the researchers, David de
Pomerai of the University of Nottingham in England and Peter
Candido of the University of British Columbia in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ''Current exposure limits to microwave equipment might need to
be reconsidered,'' they said in the study, which was released by
the journal Nature in advance of its scheduled publication in the
May 25 issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the researchers continuously exposed nematodes, or
microscopic soil worms, to levels of microwave radiation overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The cells of the worms later showed they produced heat-shock
proteins, which can disrupt cells' functions. Organisms produce the
proteins in response to threatening conditions, such as heat. But
the researchers said the changes in the worms were not caused by
heat but by the radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Current exposure limits for cell phones assume that the
microwave radiation they emit has no harmful effects if it does not
cause heating.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a British government panel concluded there is no
evidence that cell phones are harmful. However, it recommended that
parents limit their children's use of cell phones and that the
equipment carry labels disclosing how much radiation they generate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1533 </TRAILER>
