<HEADLINE> French Bank Machines Run Dry  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Cash machines around France ran out of bank notes
on Friday as armored truck guards entered the fourth day of a
strike, which they have vowed to maintain until demands for better
on-the-job protection are met.
</P>
<P>
   Empty automatic teller machines caught Parisians off-guard ahead
of the weekend, when most banks are closed. By midday Friday,
officials at France's biggest banks said that cash machines were
quickly running out of francs.
</P>
<P>
   At Credit Lyonnais and Societe Generale, 25 percent of the
machines were empty by Friday afternoon, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Banque Nationale de Paris said that 10 percent of its
automatic teller machines weren't working, mostly those in busy
commercial areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some banks opted to refill cash machines on their own, a job
usually reserved for the unionized security guards, using older
notes instead of the crisp bills supplied by the guards.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Brink's armored truck service had warned on Thursday
that France could face a shortage of bank notes at automatic teller
machines over the weekend if negotiations with employers broke
down. Discussions were expected to resume Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Armored truck guards across France went on strike Tuesday after
a series of attacks on security guards. They are demanding a pay
increase and asking that limits be placed on how far guards should
have to walk from their vehicles to collect money
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
