<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Star: TV Westerns Hit the Trail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Robert Fuller, star of TV westerns
''Laramie'' and ''Wagon Train,'' said he doubts those thrilling
shows of yesteryear will be coming back to prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody in power in this business knows how to make a decent
western,'' he said Thursday during the opening of the 15th annual
Knoxville Western Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, he pointed to the short-lived ''Magnificent Seven'' TV
series a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of the actors could ride a horse,'' Fuller said. ''You're
not going to get a western on the air that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuller, who later starred in the 1970s medical drama
''Emergency,'' recently made a guest appearance on ''Walker, Texas
Ranger,'' one of the closest things to a western now on the small
screen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1543 </TRAILER>
