<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grain Futures Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybeans prices fell slightly Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade after an Agriculture Department report
forecasted robust harvests for U.S. farmers this year, provided
that ample moisture reaches growing areas.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, corn and wheat prices rallied after falling in
early trading as investors speculated on the impact of the USDA's
report. According to the report, soybean production will outpace
last year's output by 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures rebounded earlier in the day, but finished lower
amid concern about hot weather this weekend in the Midwest. Wheat
prices closed higher, triggered by the USDA's estimate that U.S.
winter wheat production would exceed investors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 2\ cents to $2.84 a bushel; July
corn rose 1 cent to $2.45} a bushel; July oats fell 1 cent to
$1.22\ a bushel; July soybeans fell 2} cents to $5.65} a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .33 cent to 68.25 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle fell .42 cent to 83.60 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .10 cent to 72.85 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .75
cents to 89.10 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
