<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bus struck by object latest in series of expressway incidents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Vandals have launched objects from
overpasses to the Kensington Expressway below at least a dozen
times in the last four months, most recently Tuesday when a chunk
of concrete was dropped onto a school bus windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Stacy Moss felt slivers of glass go into her left eye,
but managed to steer the bus, which was not carrying any
passengers, off to the side of the inbound expressway also known as
Route 33.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Lord was watching over me. I was very grateful I didn't
have children in the bus,'' said Moss, 25, who was on her way to
Waterfront Elementary School to pick up children.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been several such incidents on that expressway,
a main thoroughfare into Buffalo, the potentially deadly practice
is not limited to it or to the city, officials said. Three
motorists died in New York state in 1998 from thrown of falling
objects, according to the most recent statistics available from
federal highway officials. Adolescents are usually blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a motorist who drove to the station house with a baby
buggy imbedded in her windshield several years ago,'' James
Giammaresi, chief of staff for the Buffalo Police Department, told
The Buffalo News. ''We've had situations where bowling balls have
been hurled at cars on the Kensington Expressway.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, two young adults narrowly escaped injury when
someone threw a couch into the path of their car on the expressway.
</P>
<P>
   ''These young kids don't recognize the danger in what they are
doing; it's a game to them,'' said State Trooper Daniel Krawczyk,
who arrested three teen-agers last summer for throwing rocks from
railroad tracks onto the Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   State Police Major Michael McManus said the youths see it as
entertainment. ''They're bored and they do it for kicks but they
don't realize the possible tragic consequences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   J. Patrick Murphy was driving when a brick or rock was dropped
on the roof of his car. He said he drove back to where the vandals
were and called police, but left after about 45 minutes. He
contacted U.S. District Judge William Skretny after learning the
judge was recently a victim of the same mischief that he
experienced several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe cameras can be installed on overpasses where this
happens, or maybe we can give these kids something to do -- get them
involved in Habitat for Humanity or sports activities,'' Murphy, an
Amherst resident, said.
</P>
<P>
   On April 18, an object was thrown at Skretny's car on the
Kensington as he drove home from work. His windshield shattered,
spraying him with glass.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really amazing the number of individuals, about two
dozen, who have expressed to me in either letters or phone calls
that they or someone they know has had similar experiences,''
Skretny said.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the overpasses have tall fences at the edge of the
sidewalks bordering the bridges, vandals climb on them and throw
objects over. Giammaresi believes the fencing should be expanded to
cover the entire overpass.
</P>
<P>
   Krawczyk said the vandals, however, need to think their action
through.
</P>
<P>
   ''If these kids who do this could put themselves in the place of
the people in the vehicle, I think that it would make a
difference,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
