<HEADLINE> Fishermen, boaters applaud decision to replace Manasquan rescue boat </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   POINT PLEASANT BEACH, N.J. (AP) -- Bowing to pressure, the U.S.
Coast Guard has agreed to replace a heavy-weather rescue boat at
its Manasquan Inlet station, alleviating fears that stranded
boaters or shipwreck survivors could die while waiting for another
station to send one.
</P>
<P>
   A new, 47-foot motorized lifeboat described by one seaman as
''unstoppable'' will be delivered by summer's end to replace an
older 44-foot vessel that was taken away from the station last
year, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is big,'' said commercial fisherman Jim Lovgren, captain
of the 67-foot trawler Sea Dragon, which is based here. ''This is
going to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody sitting in 44-degree water, well, you're dead before
a boat from Sandy Hook or Barnegat gets here. It's that simple,''
Lovgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the Manasquan Inlet station's lone heavy-weather
rescue boat was taken away by the Coast Guard, which is in the
process of replacing its 1960s-era 44-foot boats with the
47-footers.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard later notified station officials that the boat
wouldn't be replaced; instead, the responsibility for rescues in
seas of 8 feet or more would fall to stations in Barnegat Light and
Sandy Hook -- each more than 25 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The move triggered criticism from commercial fishermen, sport
fishermen and others who said the longer response time for SOS
calls could spell disaster for victims.
</P>
<P>
   Manasquan Inlet is one of the busiest ports on the East Coast
and needs a Coast Guard station with the equipment to act quickly
in emergencies, they said.
</P>
<P>
   They enlisted U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg and New Jersey
congressmen in a bid to reverse the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''A two-hour response time could be a death sentence for a
seriously injured boater,'' U.S. Reps. Chris Smith, James Saxton,
Frank LoBiondo, Bob Franks and Frank Pallone said in a letter to
Adm. James Loy, commandant of the Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard later agreed to provide the boat, as it already
has or will soon, for stations in Cape May, Atlantic City, Barnegat
Light and Sandy Hook.
</P>
<P>
   The boats, which cost $1.2 million each, are capable of
operating in 30-foot seas and 50-knot winds. If overturned in the
water, they right themselves within 8 seconds, according to Coast
Guard officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's virtually unstoppable,'' said Senior Chief Boatswain's
Mate Rob Wyco, standing near Barnegat Light's 47-footer, which was
brought here for a news conference at which the announcement was
made. ''The only limitation on it is the crew,'' he said referring
to injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, a member of the Senate Transportation Appropriations
Subcommittee, said that persuading the Coast Guard to provide the
boat wasn't hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''They listened to reason. And I threatened to cut the
commandant's pay,'' he joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
