<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 16:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Even Cheap Drugs May Not Aid Africa  </HEADLINE>
By RAVI NESSMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- On an AIDS-ravaged continent
where many countries spend only $5 a year per capita on health
care, a plan by pharmaceutical companies to reduce sharply the
price of AIDS drugs was greeted Friday as a sign of progress -- but
one that will have little impact on most of those infected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even if the therapy drops from $15,000 a year to $1,000,
that's still way unaffordable for most of the continent,'' said Dr.
Gary Maartens, head of the department of infectious diseases at the
University of Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   Five major drug companies announced in Geneva on Thursday they
would work with governments in Africa and other poor regions to cut
the overall costs of HIV/AIDS drugs by a reported 70 to 85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, few countries in sub-Saharan Africa, where 70 percent
of the world's 33.6 million HIV-infected people live, have the
resources to provide any large-scale programs to their infected
populations.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the cut in treatment cost is a big step forward, there
is still a huge gap in terms of it making a huge difference in the
lives of infected persons,'' said Chinelo Bob-Osamor, spokeswoman
for the Nigerian Health Ministry. ''Ultimately, it is still about
who can afford to pay for treatment. I'm afraid not many people
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even South Africa, the continent's wealthiest country, will not
be able to make the ''triple treatment'' used in treating AIDS
affordable to its more than 4 million HIV-infected people, Health
Minister Manto Tshabalala-Msimang said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The entire public drug budget of $300 million would buy
treatment for only a fraction of those infected, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Maartens foresees the cheaper drugs spurring more realistic
plans, such as a program using the drug AZT to prevent transmission
of HIV from pregnant women to their children. With an estimated 25
percent of South Africa's pregnant women infected with the virus,
the government has previously said it could not afford the program.
</P>
<P>
   Only relatively wealthy countries such as Nigeria, Botswana or
South Africa could even consider long-term treatment programs for
people with full-blown AIDS, Maartens said.
</P>
<P>
   For the nearly one-fifth of South Africans who have private
insurance, and others with steady incomes, the reduced prices make
those treatments plausible for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement brought a flicker of hope to one woman sorely in
need of some good news.
</P>
<P>
   Lucia, a 31-year-old resident of Soweto, was diagnosed with HIV
in 1995 after she was raped. She declined to give her last name
because the stigma attached to AIDS is so great here that she
feared her neighbors might kill her if they found out she was
infected.
</P>
<P>
   Lucia, who owns part of a janitorial company that employs
HIV-infected workers, likely would be able to afford the
reduced-cost medicines -- but at a stiff price.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be tough for me. I won't be able to buy enough food,''
she said. And that's her dilemma. ''If you are on these drugs, you
have to eat a balanced diet. You can't just take drugs without
food, they go together.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why the government must implement an anti-poverty
program that delivers food aid as well as medicine to fight off the
illnesses that attack weakened immune systems, said Nkululeko
Nxesi, director of the National Association of People Living with
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many people who are HIV positive, they don't die because of
AIDS or HIV, they die because of alternative diseases that are
curable,'' he said. ''If someone has got pneumonia, and he can't
get help to treat that pneumonia, then AZT would be useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Sturchio, spokesman for Merck and Co., one of the
participating drug companies, admitted there were enormous
roadblocks to be confronted before major AIDS treatments can be
dispersed to most afflicted Africans. However, he was encouraged by
planned talks among the companies, international organizations and
the African countries to work to solve the problems.	   ''This isn't going to
make a dramatic difference overnight,'' he
said. ''I think things are now moving in a constructive direction
... and we should be able to make progress on those issues. But it
is going to take time because they are complex issues.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue involves the complex regime of as many as a dozen
pills that must be taken at set times daily as part of some AIDS
treatments. Health researchers fear that if the program is not
strictly followed, the disease could become resistant to the
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   For many AIDS sufferers in rural Africa, where roads could be
cut off by floods and deliveries might be weeks late, following
such a regimen might not be plausible, Sturchio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the kinds of things that we need to address through
this initiative,'' he said. ''We don't have all the answers yet,
but we are encouraged that at least we have a framework to discuss
these questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
