<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Father acquitted in shooting of daughter's boyfriend  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BATAVIA, N.Y. (AP) -- A jury on Friday acquitted a father who
said he shot in the direction of his daughter's fleeing boyfriend
to seek justice.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Murray, 55, was accused of first-degree assault in the
shooting of his daughter's boyfriend in September. The jury also
didn't convict Murray of a lesser assault charge, court officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray of Pavilion, 44 miles east of Buffalo, was accused of
shooting Duane Charache, now 17, once in the stomach with a
.12-gauge shotgun on Sept. 30. He said he found Charache in his
daughter's car and held him at gunpoint while he called police.
Murray was on the phone with emergency dispatchers when Charache
ran and Murray fired three shots, state police said. One slug went
through Charache's abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had said he didn't know Charache and assumed he was
trying to steal the car. Charache was planning on taking the car
and running away with Murray's daughter and another girl to Canada,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray would have faced five-to-25 years in state prison if he
was found guilty of the first-degree assault count, said District
Attorney Lawrence Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   The jury deliberated more than eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who retired because of health problems last year after
27 years as a truck driver, testified that on that night he saw a
young man in his daughter's car. He went inside and grabbed his
shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ''I walked up to him and told him 'Don't run. Just stand
there,''' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   He told Charache, who Murray said he never met before, to stand
on the sidewalk while he called police.
</P>
<P>
   Charache ran, Murray dropped the phone as he was talking to
police and fired three shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hollered for him to stop and then I reached the porch
railing and fired the first shot,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said Charache disappeared into brush. Murray fired again,
aiming into the air. He briefly saw Charache again, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fired my third shot,'' Murray said. ''He was out of sight. I
was leaning over the porch and it was wet and slippery and I had
sandals on and I slipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he wasn't angry that Charache was trying to take the
car.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted to see justice done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Benjamin Bonarigo, who spoke with jurors after
the case ended, said the jury acquitted Murray because they didn't
believe his client intended to injure Charache and that Murray
didn't show the necessary ''wanton or reckless'' disregard for the
youth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Justice has been served,'' Bonarigo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
