<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New US Embassy in Moscow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The United States unveiled a new, debugged embassy
building in Moscow on Friday, 15 years after its construction was
halted because Soviet builders had left it riddled with listening
devices.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Marine squadron hoisted the American flag in front of the
red-brick building, and Ambassador James Collins called it ''one of
the most challenging construction projects ever undertaken by the
Department of State.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been a task ... beset by the unexpected,'' Collins said
in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Work on what would have become the new U.S. Embassy was halted
in 1985 after listening devices installed by Soviet construction
workers were discovered throughout the building. American officials
concluded that the bugging was so extensive that the building could
not be used for diplomatic purposes. The structure remained empty
for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, a decision was made to tear down the top two floors
and add four new ones. The six lower stories were gutted to only
columns and floors, to be used only for non-classified operations,
embassy officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Only American workers were used in the new construction.
Thousands of people worked on the building over the years, and one
was killed in an on-the-job accident, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   One glass wall of the rebuilt chancery faces the main Russian
government building, called the White House, across a big
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ''The move ... parallels the figurative move of U.S.-Russia
relations into a new era,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the start of a new century and the transfer of leadership
in Russia to a young, forward-looking new generation of Russian
leaders, we are witnessing the opening of new possibilities to
develop and strengthen U.S.-Russian relations,'' he said, referring
to the recent election of President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
