<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Women Enrolling for MBAs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Greater numbers of women are enrolling in top
law and medical schools than in graduate business programs,
apparently because many women don't see business careers as
compatible with their personal and professional goals, according to
a study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of more than 1,600 male and female MBA graduates was
done by the New York-based women's group Catalyst along with the
University of Michigan Business School and the university's Center
for the Education of Women.
</P>
<P>
   It found that 95 percent of all graduates from 12 of the
nation's top business schools expressed satisfaction with their
school experience and post-MBA careers. Yet while women make up 44
percent of law and medical school classes, they constitute just 30
percent of those enrolled in MBA programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an opportunity gap -- high satisfaction among women who
attend MBA programs but few women investing themselves in those
programs in the first place,'' said B. Joseph White, dean of the
University of Michigan's business school.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that one-third of women MBA graduates surveyed
felt business school culture to be too aggressive and competitive.
More than half said they could not relate to people in case studies
used in the classroom, and nearly 40 percent said there are not
enough opportunities to work with women professors.
</P>
<P>
   While equally satisfied with their jobs, men and women were on
somewhat different career tracks after graduation, the study found.
Forty-six percent of the men MBA graduates were found to be
employed in ''line jobs,'' while just 37 percent of women graduates
had such positions.
</P>
<P>
   So-called line jobs -- related to running the factories, sales
staffs and accounting -- tend to lead to positions in senior
management. Women often are routed to other jobs, such as human
resources and information systems.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that among the factors holding women back from
getting MBAs were a lack of female role models, the perceived
incompatibility of business careers with their life goals, a lack
of confidence in mathematical skills and lack of encouragement from
employers.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which has a margin of error of plus or minus 2.4
percentage points, covered MBA graduates from Michigan, Columbia
University, Dartmouth College, Duke University, University of
California at Los Angeles, Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
New York University, Stanford University, University of California
at Berkeley, University of Chicago, University of Pennsylvania and
University of Virginia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1638 </TRAILER>
