<HEADLINE> Census Counting Door-To-Door  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly one-third of the households that failed
to return their census forms have now been counted by workers going
door-to-door, the Census Bureau reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Census Deputy Director William G. Barron, Jr., said that 30
percent of the roughly 42 million households which did not return a
form have been counted by census takers.
</P>
<P>
   The army of 460,000 workers has been in the field just under two
weeks and is expected to continue seeking out people who did not
respond for another eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Census forms were sent to most households across the country in
March with residents asked to return them around April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The mail-back response rate of 65 percent matched that of 1990,
surprising officials who had expected it to fall slightly
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the Committee on National Statistics meeting in
Washington, Barron said the Bureau is ''very pleased with the
progress to date of the enumeration phase of the census.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-percent completion reflected results through Thursday, or
the first week and one half of the 10-week process.
</P>
<P>
   ''There remain significant challenges ahead in the next eight
weeks, but the census continues to be running very well and all
operations are meeting or exceeding our expectations,'' Barron
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney, D-N.Y., ranking member of the House
Government Reform census subcommittee, called the report ''an
amazing accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution requires a national census every 10 years for
purposes of reapportioning seats in the House of Representatives.
The data collected are also widely used for many other purposes,
including distribution of billions of dollars in state and federal
aid to communities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   Committee on National Statistics:
http://www4.nas.edu/cbsse/cnstat.nsf
</P>
</TEXT>
