<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Observers Make Harrowing Escape  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Day after day, night after night,
the U.N. peacekeepers hunkered down in their compound endured the
harassing gunfire and the taunts of rebels who came to their camp
gate wearing U.N. uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''I skinned the guy who was wearing this,'' one called to the
men holed up inside. ''You are next.''
</P>
<P>
   The three British military observers and one New Zealander
wondered what they should do. Unlike the armed Kenyan U.N.
peacekeepers holding off the rebels, they had no guns.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, the rebels were holding hostage hundreds of U.N.
peacekeepers from Zambia -- their weapons, uniforms and vehicles
seized -- and clashes were breaking out. The fragile cease-fire in
this west African country was nearing collapse.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to make a break for it.
</P>
<P>
   With only a new moon to light their way, the four jumped,
unarmed, over the compound wall after midnight on May 5 and escaped
through the back alleys of Makeni, the town in central Sierra Leone
where they had lived for four months.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going over the wall, it was like the feeling when you are
standing on top of the high diving board. The difference being, you
are not sure if there is any water underneath,'' said Maj. Phil
Ashby, 30, a lean, good-natured British Royal Marine who was among
the four.
</P>
<P>
   It was three days and 50 miles later before he felt safe again.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, the four -- dressed in camouflage fatigues --
nearly bumped into patrols of the rebel Revolutionary United Front,
who control Makeni.
</P>
<P>
   Did the rebels see them? They still don't know. Ashby wonders if
the rebels saw them and, assuming they were armed, let them pass
by.
</P>
<P>
   They slipped out of Makeni, 80 miles northeast of Freetown, and
moved into the bush, crossing dense jungle, rice paddies and scrub.
</P>
<P>
   They froze at the slightest sign of life; a glowing cigarette
tip, the dying embers of a fire.
</P>
<P>
   When dawn broke, the men hid motionless underneath the brush. As
the sun rose, and temperatures soared, sleep was impossible. The
heat was enveloping, the humidity choking.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spent most of the day trying to decide where the sun was
going next and where I could get a bit of shade,'' said Maj. Andrew
Samsonoff, 26, of the British Light Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby had a portable radio and listened to his favorite team
lose a soccer game back in Britain. The others whispered jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to remind myself this was real,'' said Samsonoff.
''There is a big temptation to slip into 'this is just an exercise.
The people out there aren't really going to kill us.'''
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall, they resumed their painstaking trek.
</P>
<P>
   But already, they were dangerously dehydrated and weak. They
hadn't slept for four days before their escape because of rebel
gunfire. Ashby had been ill with malaria until two days before they
left, Samsonoff was still recovering from typhoid.
</P>
<P>
   And they'd been able to take few supplies -- just a little bit of
food and two pints of water each.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, worn out by lack of sleep and water, began hallucinating.
At first it was funny, but as his hallucinations worsened, the men
rested. Ashby improved.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby said he was ''pretty scared'' during the ordeal, but
added: ''You worry about being tired more than about being
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby and Samsonoff had survival training, but the others, Lt.
Comdr. Paul Rowland, 31, of the British Royal Navy and Maj. David
Lingard, 37, of the New Zealand Army, did not.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst moment was when two of the guys collapsed from heat
exhaustion and couldn't move without leaning on the two of us,''
said Ashby, still pale from the exhaustion of his journey and
covered in scratches.
</P>
<P>
   Making slow progress traveling at night, they finally approached
a farmer who found them a guide.
</P>
<P>
   With the guide scouting ahead for rebels, they began traveling
by day, finally reaching a village controlled by a pro-government
militia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reception we got was as if the Queen of England herself
had walked in,'' Samsonoff said. ''They sat us down, took our boots
off, gave us flip-flops, cooked us a meal.''
</P>
<P>
   The four slept that night in the village's best hut. In the
morning, a man was sent on the village's only bicycle to get help,
and a chicken was slaughtered for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Five hours later, a U.N. chopper landed in the village, lifting
the four to safety in Freetown, the capital, now heavily fortified
against a feared rebel assault.
</P>
<P>
   While the men won't say where they were picked up -- they don't
want to give the rebels clues about who helped them -- they crossed
more than 50 miles on foot by the time the helicopter touched down,
three days after they left Makeni.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're cleaned up, fed and back at base. They've got new
camouflage uniforms, replacing their shredded fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   They're grateful to the Sierra Leoneans who helped them out,
especially their guide.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had been caught, we may have become hostages again,''
said Ashby. The guide would have been shot on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   All four refused a U.N. offer to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ashby: ''If anybody has valuable information about what's
going on upcountry, it's us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
