<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Justice: SBC Addressed Concerns  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- SBC Communications has made progress in
addressing certain competitive concerns as it seeks to offer
long-distance service in Texas, the Justice Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although not lending a full endorsement, the Justice Department
said that SBC had improved its performance in one of four areas
identified by the department as problematic several months ago. It
also said it would review the other three issues and defer its
judgment on those matters until more data became available later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The department makes its recommendations to the Federal
Communications Commission, which ultimately decides whether to
allow Bell companies to provide their local customers with
long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 law mandated that before a Bell company can do so, it
first must show in detail that it has opened its local monopoly to
give rivals a chance to compete. So far, Bell Atlantic has been the
only company to meet the test in New York.
</P>
<P>
   SBC filed its initial application in the beginning of this year
seeking to offer long-distance in Texas. But the bid received harsh
reviews from the Justice Department, which said that the company
had not taken sufficient steps to give competing companies access
to its network -- as required by law -- and recommended that the FCC
deny the petition.
</P>
<P>
   The company ultimately asked for a new review, so it could
bolster its application with more information.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Justice Department said the company had
adequately addressed one important hurdle -- making sure its rivals
can get needed equipment to connect their local calls to SBC's
networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the department said it would push off its evaluation of
other matters until it could get more data. Those issues include
the company's handling of requests from rival businesses seeking to
lease lines so they could offer high-speed Internet service and its
processing of orders to switch local phone customers over to
competing providers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are encouraged that the Department of Justice will continue
to review the entire record and we look forward to working with
them to address any remaining issues,'' said Priscilla Hill-Ardoin,
SBC's vice president for federal regulatory affairs.
</P>
<P>
   SBC filed its new application on April 5. The FCC has 90 days to
render a decision and must also take into account the evaluation of
state regulators. In this case, the Texas Public Utility Commission
has given its endorsement twice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
