<HEADLINE> Jackson To Visit Sierra Leone  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After weeks of telephone negotiations with
leaders of warring factions in bloodstained Sierra Leone, civil
rights activist Jesse Jackson will visit the West African region
Tuesday in an attempt to free captured U.N. peacekeepers there.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, in Pittsburgh to address a group of communications
lawyers, said he hopes that face-to-face meetings and a moral
appeal could help to end the bloodshed between government forces
under President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and rebel forces of the
Revolutionary United Front (RUF).
</P>
<P>
   Through telephone calls with regional leaders, Jackson said,
''We have done a lot of the work needed to bring together crucial
forces to end the fighting. We want to help facilitate the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Details on the mission are sketchy. Calling the situation ''very
fluid,'' Jackson said he expects to land in neighboring Liberia,
which has been working to help broker a peace settlement. Where
Jackson will go from there isn't certain but could include a visit
to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But while his itinerary is uncertain, Jackson's goal is solid --
get freedom for the 500 U.N. peacekeepers now in rebel hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''The peacekeepers must not be used as bargaining chips. Their
role is too significant to be captured and used that way,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Civil war has raged in the diamond-rich nation for eight years.
Last year, a peace agreement was signed granting RUF forces, under
the leadership of Foday Sankoh, a stake in the national government
in exchange for laying down their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the RUF continued to stockpile arms and then escalated the
fighting, moving toward the capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh hasn't been seen in several days and Jackson appealed to
the rebel leader to resurface and help bring stability to the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would tell Sankoh to make himself become visible and make an
appeal to release the U.N. peacekeepers. It would be of immense
value to Sierra Leone, the Congo and the rest of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Sankoh missing, it has added to the tension,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some like Amnesty International USA Director William F. Schulz
have called on President Clinton to state unequivocally that those
who commit atrocities in Sierra Leone will be prosecuted for war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he wasn't willing to commit to a war crimes panel
at this stage, saying he wanted to avoid statements that could sow
''fear or divisiveness''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he wasn't sure exactly why the peace negotiations
broke down but guessed ''greed and the politics of diamonds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1733 </TRAILER>
