<DOCNO> APW20000512.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversy in Calif. Gender Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- A bill banning job and housing
discrimination based on a person's perceived gender was approved by
state lawmakers over the opposition of those who argued it could
force businesses to allow cross-dressers at work.
</P>
<P>
   California law already prohibits discrimination based on sex and
sexual orientation. The bill would add a person's appearance or
behavior, whether or not those traits differ from what is
''traditionally associated'' with his or her gender.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Assemblyman Fred Keeley, said there were court cases
in other states where heterosexuals were fired or lost promotions
because they were not feminine or masculine enough. He said the
bill would prevent similar situations in California.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said businesses feared the bill would result in
lawsuits filed if bosses did not allow cross-dressing men to wear
dresses at work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we're going to be telling businesses they can't set some
dress-code standards of how they want their employees to look,''
said Assemblyman Steve Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Keeley said the bill would not change current law, which allows
employers to impose dress codes if there is a legitimate business
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly approved the measure 41-30 Thursday, and it
now goes to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Read the bill, AB2142, at
</P>
<P>
   http://www.assembly.ca.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
