<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the euro Friday as
European leaders seemed willing to intervene in an effort to revive
their ailing currency. The dollar rose slightly against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 91.89 cents, up
from 90.06 cents late Wednesday. The dollar was quoted at 108.89
Japanese yen, up from 108.53 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The euro surged in value against the dollar during a late rally
after several European leaders indicated a desire to develop a
strategy for curbing the euro's recent decline.
</P>
<P>
   No specifics were provided, however, leaving analysts to
question whether Friday's gains were a turning point or merely a
temporary lift.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market here is somewhat confused,'' said Hillel Waxman,
chief foreign exchange trader for Bank Leumi USA, referring to
sentiment among U.S. foreign exchange traders. ''There's thinness
and uncertainty in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the euro has dropped to new lows as investors
predicted that European authorities would not take aggressive
action to stimulate the economy. The euro is the single currency of
11 European nations and has been trading since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman said dollar trading was light against most other
currencies, specifically the yen, ahead of Tuesday's meeting of the
Federal Reserve Board, when Fed policy-makers are widely expected
to raise U.S. interest rates by half a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound rose to $1.5144, up from a four-year low of
$1.5022 in late trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.6917 Swiss francs, down from
1.7292, and 1.4879 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4901.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1289 German
marks, down from 2.1724; 7.1401 French francs, down from 7.2860;
and 2,107.61 Italian lire, down from 2,150.69.
</P>
</TEXT>
