<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Top Chinese Official Dies  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A top Chinese monetary official said by Hong Kong
media to have committed suicide out of worries over his health or a
corruption scandal has died, a Chinese official confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's Ming Pao newspaper said Li Fuxiang died Wednesday
after jumping from the seventh floor of a Beijing hospital. As
director of the State Administration of Foreign Exchange, Li was
China's top foreign exchange regulator.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the administration's information office confirmed
that Li had died. However, the official, who only gave her surname,
Deng, refused to provide additional information, saying she was
awaiting instructions from superiors.
</P>
<P>
   Ming Pao and the Sing Tao Daily, another mainstream, independent
Hong Kong newspaper, said Li's death may have been related to
health, work pressure or financial problems. Sing Tao said he
suffered heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Reports on a popular web site said Li had checked into the No.
304 Hospital, a military facility.
</P>
<P>
   A worker in the hospital's morgue confirmed that a person
staying in the ward reserved for senior officials had fallen to his
death and the body was found outside the hospital Wednesday
morning. Police came and removed the body, said the worker who
would not give his name.
</P>
<P>
   The internal investigation bureau of China's ruling Communist
Party recently questioned Li about corruption involving China
Everbright Bank, Sing Tao reported.
</P>
<P>
   Everbright Bank's former chairman, Zhu Xiaohua, was removed last
summer reportedly while under investigation for economic problems,
an allegation the company denied. Zhu had run the government's
foreign exchange administration for two years. Around the time Zhu
left the agency in 1995, Li became a deputy director.
</P>
<P>
   Li, 47, was promoted to head of the foreign exchange
administration in October 1998. The administration sets policies
and oversees the flow of foreign currency, an important mission in
China. China's currency, the yuan, is not fully convertible on
international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Under Li, the administration tightened controls on foreign
exchange to stop illegal outflows that were pressuring China to
devalue the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Li's death and its possible connection to the rumored but never
confirmed investigation into China Everbright could add to scandals
already embarrassing Chinese leaders. China Everbright Bank is one
of China's more innovative and profitable banks. Its parent
company, China Everbright Group, which Zhu also ran, is controlled
by the State Council, the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese leaders have been trying to curb rampant corruption that
has eroded popular support for Communist Party rule. But they have
limited the wholly state-controlled media's reporting on
corruption. They fear that revelations about the involvement of
senior officials could further damage the party's image.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation into billions of dollars of smuggling through
the southeastern port of Xiamen has implicated the wife of Beijing
party secretary Jia Qinglin, party sources have said. President
Jiang Zemin, a mentor of Jia, ordered public denials that either
Jia or his wife were involved.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Li Fuxiang's death, the spokesman's office for the
State Council said it had no information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
