<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Touts Trade Bill in Midwest  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHAKOPEE, Minn. (AP) -- Beside a vast field of soybeans,
President Clinton argued Friday that open trade with China will
help the communist nation move closer to democracy and suggested
that U.S. opponents are aligning themselves with China's most rigid
communist traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The president toured a 1,500-acre farm run by Terry Hauer and
his father, Gene. Like many farmers here, the Hauers figure the
trade bill will make them more competitive with state-subsidized
producers in China.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter how hard I work, or how much I cut my costs, I
simply can't compete with subsidized corn,'' said farmer Dallas
Bohnsack.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill, he said, would eliminate the subsidies and
enable him to garner a greater share of corn sales to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said China has already begun cutting back on certain
crops, such as wheat, in preparation for the entry of American
crops.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way the Chinese farmers can keep pace with the
growth of their own consumers, but American farmers can,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several local farmers, in baseball caps and striped shirts,
gathered before a stage surrounded by bundles of hay to hear
Clinton's free-trade pitch. Also in the crowd was Walter Mondale,
former vice president and former ambassador to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked the crowd to look past China's sad record on human
rights to consider the changes that an American economic presence
can foster there.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get frustrated, but China is an old country, and it's
changing fast,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can tell you that we'll have a lot more influence on Chinese
foreign policy ... if we have an open hand of working with them,
than if we say no, if we turn our backs on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakopee, a rural town outside Minneapolis, is represented by
Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., who is backing the trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota ranks seventh in the United States for exports,
sending $2.4 billion in agricultural products abroad in 1998.
Minnesota products include soybeans, meal, seed corn, beef and
pork.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton toured the Hauer farm with Minge and Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said there are still a handful of House members from
agricultural districts who remain undecided about the trade
legislation. ''I think it's tight, but I think generally, it's
going in our direction,'' Glickman told reporters on Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll win this vote, but I think it's going to be a
very close vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president left Washington to build for support for extending
permanent normal trade relations. He visited places where opinion
on the matter ran to either extreme.
</P>
<P>
   In Ohio, where union opposition runs high, Clinton was greeted
by protesters whose signs made their sentiments clear: ''No blank
checks for China.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton discussed the trade legislation with labor and business
leaders at a National Guard armory in North Canton, Ohio, far from
union protesters gathered in small clusters on nearby roads
</P>
<P>
   The president said the trade deal will create, not steal away,
American jobs. He cast the need for open trade with China in terms
of national security, saying the United States needs access to
China's markets to ''reduce the likelihood of conflict, even war''
in Asia for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't pass it, it will increase the chances that
something bad will happen,'' Clinton said. ''That's not a threat,
and goodness knows if I didn't prevail, I would pray that I was
wrong. I believe I know what I'm talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said one of the ''great ironies'' of this trade
debate is the fact that American liberals are aligned in opposition
to the legislation with ''militant elements'' of the Chinese
military and operators of China's state-run industries. These
people in China want the subsidies to continue and ''want to keep
their thumb on the little folks in China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an unusual thing to see that some of the most progressive
people in our country are taking a position that is supported by
only the most regressive people in their country,'' Clinton said.
''They know if they open up China, their control will be
undermined.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
