<DOCNO> APW20000512.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope To Visit Portugal  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   FATIMA, Portugal (AP) -- Pope John Paul II joined more than
100,000 pilgrims in silent prayer in this small town Friday as he
prepared to beatify a shepherd boy and girl where they said they
spoke to the Virgin Mary 83 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Waving aside health concerns raised by Vatican hierarchy, the
pope knelt carefully before folding his trembling hands for five
minutes of prayer during a 45-minute appearance. This northern
Portuguese settlement of 8,000 is expected to swell to a million by
the end of his 24-hour visit.
</P>
<P>
   The pope flew in a camouflaged military helicopter emblazoned
with a cross from the capital of Lisbon to a soccer field outside
Fatima, where he embraced small children and briefly caressed the
heads of many in the teary crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Joyous local priests kissed his hand before he rode the
popemobile through ecstatic crowds to pray at Fatima's Chapel of
Apparitions, built where the Virgin Mary allegedly appeared to
three shepherd children on May 13, 1917.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise gesture, John Paul donated to the Virgin of Fatima
a gold ring his late mentor Warsaw Cardinal Stefan Wyszynski, the
Polish primate, gave him in 1978 when he became pope.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the pope is to beatify Jacinta Marto and her
brother Francisco who said the Virgin Mary appeared to them and
their cousin Lucia de Jesus dos Santos six times above an olive
tree and told them three secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The brother and sister died of pneumonia two years after the
visions, at the ages of 9 and 11. Dos Santos, now 93, has been at a
Carmelite convent in central Portugal since 1929. She will meet the
Pope on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Beatification is the final step before sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherbeaten farmers, fashionably dressed youths and tourists
pitched tents on available space throughout the town, some enjoying
sunny picnics of wine and salads or touring hectic stalls for
statuettes of the Virgin Mary and porcelain plates featuring the
shepherd children.
</P>
<P>
   ''The beatification of children brings much more faith. It
proves children are good, innocent,'' said the 64-year-old
Portuguese pilgrim Rosarita de Armeida, motioning to crowds of
teen-agers in jeans and T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's was John Paul's third visit to the shrine, considered
one of his favorites. The pope, who turns 80 next week, credits the
Virgin of Fatima with saving his life when he was wounded in a 1981
assassination attempt in St. Peter's Square. The shooting happened
on May 13, the day the first apparition of the Virgin is said to
have taken place in Fatima, 72 miles north of Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   When the pontiff came to Fatima on May 12 the following year to
thank the Virgin, he survived another assassination attempt as a
fundamentalist Spanish priest lunged at him with a bayonet,
accusing him of betraying the church.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the pontiff's arrival, thousands crawled along a marble
walkway through Fatima's central square in penance or to honor a
promise to the Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Many pilgrims hoped the pope, whose frailty is associated with
Parkinson's disease, would reveal the last of three secrets the
shepherd children said the Virgin told them.
</P>
<P>
   The first two foretold the end of World War I and the rise and
fall of communism.
</P>
<P>
   Dos Santos has told the third secret to several popes but the
Vatican has refused to disclose it.
</P>
<P>
   The Fatima visit is expected to be the pope's last foreign trip
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.vatican.va
</P>
<P>
   http://www.santuario-fatima.pt (in Portuguese)
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fatimavirtual.com (in Portuguese)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1800 </TRAILER>
