<HEADLINE> German Leader: Welcome Foreigners  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Stepping into a national debate on immigration,
Germany's president urged his compatriots Friday to show more
tolerance for foreigners and condemned politicians who play on
racist themes.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech marking his first year in office, President Johannes
Rau also said Germany must not be afraid to think about controlling
immigration if that would help ease the integration of 7 million
foreigners already living here.
</P>
<P>
   ''That people of different origins and cultures all live in our
country will not change,'' Rau said. ''We need a new effort so all
people in Germany can live together -- an effort without fears, and
without getting dreamy.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech to a Berlin audience of politicians, business leaders
and academics was the 69-year-old head of state's first major
address since his inauguration last May. The German president has
little power but is often viewed as the nation's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder sparked the immigration debate with
recent plans to fill a high-tech labor shortage by offering special
visas to 20,000 foreign computer specialists.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative opposition called instead for a new law modeled
on U.S. immigration law to steer the flow of immigrants, giving
priority to highly qualified workers.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging the debate, Rau said Germany ''should seriously
consider'' passing measures to regulate immigration because its
demand for workers was increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Immigration can't be left to chance,'' he said. ''We need
well-reasoned viable concepts that don't overburden anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Rau caused controversy at his inauguration last year when he
said he wanted to be president of all Germans -- including
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he condemned hate crimes against foreigners, urged
Germans to confront neo-Nazis and called for tough punishment for
perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   He also lashed out at politicians who play on anti-foreigner
themes. It was a veiled attack on Juergen Ruettgers, the
conservative gubernatorial candidate running in Sunday's elections
in North Rhine-Westphalia. Ruettgers has been running an
anti-immigration campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 million Turks living among Germans, he also backed
Islamic religious instruction in public schools -- but only in
German.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
