<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Icahn Raises Bid for Nabisco Group  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financier Carl Icahn has raised his bid for
Nabisco Group Holdings Corp. to $22 a share from $16 as part of the
continuing auction process that is under way for the company that
controls the maker of Ritz crackers and Oreo cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn, who already owns 9.5 percent of Nabisco Group stock, said
in documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission that
he planned to offer $19 in cash and $3 in two-year notes for each
remaining share of Nabisco Group., or about $6.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Icahn is probably not the only bidder, although no
others have been publicly identified.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group hired investment bankers last month to explore its
options after Icahn indicated he wanted to expand his stake in the
company and unseat the board so the new directors could take steps
to boost the value of its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn eventually agreed to participate in the bidding process
and dropped his effort to elect his own slate to the board.
</P>
<P>
   But the Parsippany, N.J.-based company and the investment
bankers have declined comment on the state of the auction process.
Nabisco Group spokesman Henry Sandbach would only say there has
been significant interest in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Martin Feldman, who follows Nabisco Group for the
investment firm Salomon Smith Barney, said Friday he expects
Nabisco Group will fetch at least $25 a share at auction.
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been about 13 confidentiality agreements
signed that allow prospective bidders for Nabisco Group or the food
company it controls, Nabisco Holdings Inc., to examine the
company's financial records.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman said he did not know how many of these agreements have
resulted in bids.
</P>
<P>
   But among those who may be interested, Feldman said, are Philip
Morris Cos., which owns Kraft Foods, and R.J. Reynolds Tobacco
Holdings Co., the tobacco company spun off last year by Nabisco
Group's predecessor, RJR Nabisco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Nabisco Group shares
rose $2.12{, or 12 percent, to $19.68}. Nabisco Holdings shares
gained 37{ cents to $43.93}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
