<HEADLINE> Bush: Social Security Needs Changes  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HOLMES
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate George W.
Bush said Friday he will propose changes in the Social Security
system because it's time to ''think differently'' about providing
for Americans' retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Without going into details, Bush said allowing younger Americans
to have retirement savings accounts is an idea that deserves
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am optimistic that if the American people give my
administration a chance to come in office, that we can save and
secure Social Security,'' Bush said. ''I welcome the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Social Security has become a contentious issue in the campaign,
with Democrat Al Gore criticizing Bush's support for diverting some
Social Security taxes into private investment accounts for workers.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning Friday in Portland, Ore., Gore didn't mention Bush
by name, but said the stock market is no place for Security
Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Think about what happens when that first generation of
Americans retires in a bear market,'' Gore said. ''They would be
left trying to live on worthless paper and we as a nation could be
stuck with sky-high bailout costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is to elaborate on his proposals Monday in a speech in
Ontario, Calif. Gore also is to address the subject Monday, in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor touched on the issue in a brief speech
broadcast from Austin to the Republican National Committee
Chairmen's Conference in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody said, 'Why are you bringing up such a touchy issue?'
I said because I'm running to lead is why,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a time for America to send a leader to Washington, D.C.,
who will work with both reform-minded Republicans and reform-minded
Democrats to not only save Social Security for the elderly today
... but to think differently -- like personal savings accounts -- so
younger workers will be able to have a retirement system in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promised the GOP leaders that a tax cut would be a
cornerstone of his campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we've got enough money to not only meet governmental
needs, enough money to pay down debt, enough money to strengthen
Social Security, and we've got money left over. And I understand
that money is not the government's money, it is the people's
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush poked fun at some news coverage of his meeting this week
with defeated Republican rival Sen. John McCain, especially those
who said the two men didn't seem very close.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know a lot of people were trying to analyze the body
language of the press conference,'' Bush said. ''Sometimes when
you're standing in front of 250 members of the press corps, or 200
members of the press corps, the body language can be a bit altered
somewhat with all those faces staring at you.
</P>
<P>
   ''But John and I had a fabulous meeting,'' he said. ''There's
much more that unites us than divides us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
