<HEADLINE> FAA Could Delay Flights at O'Hare  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE ZIEGLER DIZON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A summer of long lines and flight delays could be
in store at O'Hare International Airport if federal aviation
officials and pilots can't work out a plan governing takeoffs and
landings at intersecting runways, experts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has set a May 27 deadline
for its new rules to take effect. But pilots unions say they
haven't had enough time to study the changes and make sure they are
safe.
</P>
<P>
   If the deadline passes without an agreement, the pilots will
have to stop ''land and hold short'' operations that have allowed
for faster takeoffs and landings at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a huge headache,'' said Craig Burzych, an
O'Hare representative for the National Air Traffic Controllers
Association. ''It's going to cause delays -- a lot of upset
passengers, a lot of late passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   The worries come as a separate dispute between United Airlines
and its pilots wreaks havoc on passengers' travel plans, with 197
flights canceled Friday, according to United spokesman Joe Hopkins.
Many pilots are refusing to work overtime because of a lack of
progress in contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   The land and hold short operation at issue in the Chicago
squabble is a procedure used when two airplanes are on intersecting
runways, with one cleared to land and another ready to depart.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, pilots who are landing can agree to ''hold short,''
or stop at a designated point before the intersection of the
runways. As a result, air traffic controllers can more quickly
clear planes to depart from the other runway.
</P>
<P>
   Such procedures have been in effect at O'Hare for more than 30
years. But pilots' safety concerns prompted the FAA last year to
impose greater restrictions on the operations. These included
allowing them only in dry weather and barring foreign aircraft from
participating.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those restrictions are to be eased May 27, but pilots,
controllers and other airlines players are arguing that the changes
haven't been thought through and should be discussed at a national
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokeswoman Elizabeth Isham Cory said that if no agreement
is reached by May 27, all land and hold short operations will have
to cease at O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   The effect will be ''like it is now on a rainy day,'' Cory said,
although she could not say how much of a delay the average
passenger might expect.
</P>
<P>
   Burzych said the land and hold short operations now allow
controllers to clear two to three airplanes a minute for departure
on the approved intersecting runways at O'Hare. If those operations
were banned, there would be about one departure every two to three
minutes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Air Traffic Controllers Association, along with the
Air Line Pilots Association, the Allied Pilots Association and
representatives from United and American airlines, sent a letter to
the FAA on May 4 outlining their concerns with the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Overman, a spokesman for the Allied Pilots Association,
said airline pilots are worried about a provision allowing general
aviation pilots -- from businessmen to student pilots -- to
participate in the land and hold short operations.
</P>
<P>
   Another major sticking point is an FAA requirement that O'Hare
pilots, controllers and airlines begin computer modeling by May 27
to prevent an accident in the rare case that a pilot cleared to
land must pull back up, creating a potential danger if another
plane is departing from the intersecting runway. The O'Hare groups
say they haven't been given enough time to come up with a modeling
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our attitude is where safety is concerned, it's always better
to be conservative,'' Overman said.
</P>
<P>
   Cory said she is optimistic the issue will be resolved before
the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   FAA Air Traffic Control System Command Center:
http://www.fly.faa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Air Line Pilots Association: http://www.alpa.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
