<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates Five Judges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton announced Friday that he has
nominated five people to U.S. District Court benches in Illinois,
Texas and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   John Darrah of Naperville, Ill., has been nominated to the
Northern District of Illinois. He has been a judge on the 18th
Judicial Circuit Court of Illinois since 1986 and has worked as an
adjunct professor at Northern Illinois University's College of Law
since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Lefkow of Chicago also has been nominated to the Northern
District of Illinois. She has been a federal bankruptcy judge in
the district since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Morado of San Benito, Texas, was Clinton's pick for the
Southern District of Texas. Since 1987, Morado has been a partner
at a law practice and also has been mayor of San Benito since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Reagan of Belleville, Ill., has been nominated to the
Southern District of Illinois. He has practiced law in Belleville
since 1995 and has been a part-time assistant public defender for
St. Clair County, Illinois, since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The president nominated George Singal of Bangor, Maine, for the
District of Maine. He has been with a law firm there since 1970. He
also was part-time assistant county attorney from 1971 to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The nominations must be confirmed by the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
