<HEADLINE> Illinois Boy Wins Top Math Prize  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An eighth-grader from Aurora, Ill., won the
national MathCounts competition Friday, solving an algebra problem
to beat out 227 other ''mathletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruozhou ''Joe'' Jia, 14, a pupil at Washington Middle School,
solved the equation in 15 seconds. Contestants in the finals have
45 seconds to solve each problem, hit the buzzer and answer
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The final question was: ''A lecture hall has 40 rows of seats.
There are 10 seats in the first row, 12 seats in the second row,
and so on, with two more seats in each row than in the previous
row. How many seats are in the lecture hall?
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois student's correct answer, ''1,960,'' won him a gold
medal, an $8,000 scholarship, a laptop computer and an
expenses-paid week at the original U.S. Space Camp in Huntsville,
Ala. At the NASA camps, children learn about space flight, using
flight simulators and weightlessness tanks just like astronauts in
training.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, held here since 1983, is sponsored by the CNA
Foundation as well as several education groups and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jia, who wants to become an engineer, has already completed a
year of algebra.
</P>
<P>
   He said he computed his answer on pencil and paper this way:
''a1'' plus ''an'' multiplied by ''n'' divided by 2 equals ''x,''
where ''x'' is the number of seats in the lecture hall.
</P>
<P>
   He came in second place in last year's contest.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Jia said, he solved about 4,000 math problems this
year to practice for the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was sort of easy,'' he said. ''After you do the problems,
you start to see all of the connections between algebra and
geometry.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-place prize in the contest for seventh and eighth
graders went to Tiankai Liu, 14, who won a $6,000 scholarship. He
is an eighth-grader at the Harker School, a private school in San
Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Student state teams also competed. The team representing
California on Friday won the state title, a space camp trip,
computers and a $2,000 scholarship for each of the four team
members.
</P>
<P>
   The third-place winner of a $2,000 scholarship was Ho Seung
''Paul'' Ryu, an eighth grader at Southwest Junior High School, in
Lawrence, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://mathcounts.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
