<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 63 Points; Nasdaq Up 29  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Friday after the government's report
of a decline in wholesale prices in April helped quell recent
worries about rising interest rates. But investors took profits in
late afternoon, proving that a single positive report wasn't enough
to eliminate all their fears.
</P>
<P>
   Selling in the last hour of trading left the Dow Jones
industrial average up 63.40 at 10,609.37. The Nasdaq composite
index rose 29.48 to 3,529.06. Earlier in the session, each index
was up as much as 120 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow ended the week with a gain of 31.51 points, while heavy
selling on Monday and Wednesday left the Nasdaq down 287.76 points
for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mostly higher Friday. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 rose 13.15 to 1,420.96 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 1.55 to 490.94.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks initially shot higher Friday after the Labor Department's
Producer Price Index showed a 0.3 percent decline in April that
reversed two months of increases. It was the best showing on
inflation at the wholesale level since February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The benign report came after a series of indicators had showed
strength in the economy and raised worries that the Federal Reserve
would move aggressively to raise borrowing costs at the next
meeting of its policy-making committee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices have seesawed in recent weeks as investors
alternately fretted and relaxed about interest rates. Friday's
report removed a measure of nervousness from the market, but didn't
change most analysts' expectations that the Fed will raise rates by
a half-percentage point at Tuesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results represent a fine performance on inflation,'' said
Michael Moran, chief economist at Daiwa Securities America. Still,
he said, ''we'll stick with the call for 50 basis points (half a
percentage point) at next week's meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Many investors shared Moran's view and opted to stay out of the
market until the Fed's meeting has passed. Those who were willing
to put money to work remained cautious, taking some profits from
sharp gains on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is some skepticism in the market going into the Fed's
meeting,'' said Richard A. Dickson, a technical analyst at Scott &AMP;
Stringfellow in Richmond, Va. ''That's taken some of the glow off
the attempts to rally.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, technology stocks have stumbled amid the
continuing belief that prices were bid too high last year and early
this year. Investors are beginning to nibble at stocks that have
been knocked down to more reasonable prices, Dickson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate to use the word 'bargain' in reference to technology
stocks, but there is some bargain-hunting going on there,'' he
said. Dell Computer, which released an upbeat earnings report late
Thursday, rose 5 3/16 to 49~. Sun Microsystems rose 4 11/16 to 81{.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, a spinoff of Hewlett-Packard, soared 13 7/16 to 90
after a Goldman Sachs analyst said the company is a likely addition
to the S&AMP;P 500. Agilent's full split from its parent company takes
effect June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks were mixed after J.P. Morgan analyst Susan
Walker White lowered her price target for nearly a dozen companies
in the sector. Among the stocks she singled out: Switchboard, which
fell 1 to 10[.
</P>
<P>
   But larger companies that White downgraded remained unscathed.
Online auctioneer eBay closed up 3 9/16 to 121 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 1.05 billion shares,
compared with 1.14 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 2.8 percent, coming
back from a steep selloff of 4.6 percent the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Germany's Xetra DAX index edged up 0.1 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 0.6 percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 1.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
