<HEADLINE> Officers Resign From Safety-Kleen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Three top officers have resigned from
troubled waste-disposal company Safety-Kleen Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive Kenneth W. Winger, chief operating officer
Michael J. Bragagnolo and Paul R. Humphreys, chief financial
officer had been on paid administrative leave since March 6. They
resigned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 6, chairman David E. Thomas Jr. and vice chairman
Grover C. Wrenn have been operating the company on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Safety-Kleen launched an investigation into accounting
irregularities in March after board members received information
that the problems may have affected financial results since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Laidlaw Inc., which owns 44 percent of Safety-Kleen, has been
trying to sell its stake in the company as Laidlaw focuses on its
transportation business.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Safety-Kleen rose 6\ cents to 81\ cents in trading on
the New York Stock Exchange, where shares of Laidlaw rose 6\ cents
to 75 cents.
</P>
