<HEADLINE> Strong Quake Shakes N. Chile  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- A strong earthquake rocked northern Chile
and Argentina Friday, setting off a landslide at a copper mine that
killed a miner.
</P>
<P>
   The temblor struck at 2:45 p.m. and had a preliminary magnitude
of 6.8, the Seismological Institute of the University of Chile
said.
</P>
<P>
   The quake, which temporarily cut telephone links to some areas
in northern Chile, had its epicenter in a sparsely populated area
near the northern Argentine city of Salta, about 100 miles from the
Chilean border. There were no reports of damage or injury in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The quake was strongly felt in the Chilean city of Antofagasta,
520 miles north of Santiago, according to Alberto Maturana, head of
the government's Emergency Office.
</P>
<P>
   The temblor was also felt hundreds of miles to the south and
north of Antofagasta and as far away as parts of Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   A 24-year-old miner was buried by a landslide in a mine in
Tierra Amarilla, 510 miles north of Santiago, Deputy Interior
Minister Jorge Burgos said.
</P>
<P>
   The regional governor, Armando Aranciba, called the death ''a
painful but isolated incident.'' There were no other immediate
reports of death or injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
