<HEADLINE> Army To Award 21 Asian Americans  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Twenty-one Asian-American veterans of World
War II will receive the Medal of Honor, the nation's highest honor
for valor in combat, for their heroism in France, Italy and the
Philippines, the Army announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said earlier this week it would present medals
at a ceremony June 21 but the identity of only one of the
recipients was made public then: Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, who
lost his right arm in combat in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen of the 21 men were members of either the 100th Infantry
Battalion or the 442nd Regimental Combat Team, both of which were
all-volunteer units and were among the most decorated units in U.S.
military history.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 21, a Medal of Honor recommendation for
another Japanese American, James Okubo, has been okayed but cannot
be formally approved until Congress waives a statutory time limit
for his case.
</P>
<P>
   Okubo was an Army medic and received a Silver Star for his
actions near Biffontaine, France, in October and November 1944. He
was cited for extraordinary heroism in several separate battles in
which he saved the lives of members of the 100th Infantry Battalion
and 442nd Regimental Combat Team while repeatedly exposing himself
to enemy fire, the Army said in disclosing the names of all 22
honorees.
</P>
<P>
   It was on a steep forest ridge in France's Vosges Mountains east
of Biffontaine that the 100th Infantry Battalion and 442nd
Regimental Combat Team fought perhaps their most famous battle, the
epic rescue in October 1944 of the ''Lost Battalion'' of the 141st
Infantry Regiment of 36th Division (a former Texas National Guard
unit) whose ranks had been cut off and decimated by German forces
for days.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 veterans whose Medals of Honor will be presented June 21
at the White House all had received the Distinguished Service
Cross, the second-highest military award, for their heroics. In
1996 the Congress authorized the Army to review the records of the
104 Asian American veterans of World War II who had been awarded
the Distinguished Service Cross and determine if some deserved to
be upgraded to Medals of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   ''These American heroes sacrificed much for our nation and we
are privileged to honor them properly,'' Army Secretary Louis
Caldera said.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans approved to receive the Medal of Honor are:
</P>
<P>
   --Staff Sgt. Rudolph B. Davila, of the 7th Infantry, for action
on May 28, 1944, at Artena, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Barney F. Hajiro, of the 442nd Regimental Combat Team, for
actions at Bruyeres and Biffontaine, France, in October 1944.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Mikio Hasemoto, of the 100th Infantry Battalion
(Separate), for actions on Nov. 29, 1943, at Cerasuolo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Joe Hayashi, of the 442nd, for actions in April 1945 at
Tendola, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Shizuya Hayashi, of the 100th Infantry Battalion
(Separate), for actions on Nov. 29, 1943, at Cerasulolo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --2nd Lt. Daniel K. Inouye, 442nd, for actions on April 21, 1945
at San Terenzo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Tech. Sgt. Yeiki Kobashigawa, of the 100th Infantry Battalion,
for actions on June 2, 1944, at Lanuvio, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Staff Sgt. Robert T. Kuroda, of the 442nd, for actions on Oct.
20, 1944, at Bruyeres, France.
</P>
<P>
   --Pfc. Kaoru Moto, of the 100th Infantry Battalion, for actions
on July 7, 1944 at Castellina, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pfc. Kiyoshi Muranaga, of the 442nd, for actions on June 26,
1944 at Suvereto, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Masato Nakae, of the 100th Infantry Battalion, for actions
on Aug. 19, 1944, at Pisa, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. Shinyei Nakamine, of the 100th Infantry Battalion
(Separate), for actions on June 2, 1944, at La Torreto, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pfc. William K. Nakamura, of the 442nd, for actions on July 4,
1944, at Castellina, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pfc. Joe M. Nishimoto, of the 442nd, for actions on Nov. 7,
1944, at La Houssiere, France.
</P>
<P>
   --Sgt. Allan M. Ohata, of the 100th Infantry Battalion
(Separate), for actions in November 1945 at Cerasuolo, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Tech. Sgt. Yukio Okutsu, of the 442nd for actions on April 7,
1945, at Mount Belvedere, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pfc. Frank Ono, of the 442nd, for actions on July 4, 1944, at
Castellina, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Staff Sgt. Kazuo Otani, of the 442nd, for actions on July 15,
1944, at Pieve di S. Luce, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Pvt. George T. Sakato, of the 442nd, for actions on Oct. 29,
1944, at Biffontaine, France.
</P>
<P>
   --Tech. Sgt. Ted. T. Tanouye, of the 442nd, for actions on July
7, 1944, at Molina a Ventoabbto, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Capt. Francis B. Wai for actions on Oct. 20, 1944, at Leyte,
Philippine Islands. The Army did not identify Wai's unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 1833 </TRAILER>
