<HEADLINE> Bonds Pull Back Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bonds prices fell Friday as a report showing a
drop in wholesale prices failed to change expectations the Federal
reserve will hike interest rates next week to fight inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 10-year Treasury note fell 23/32
point, or $7.18} per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves
in the opposite direction, rose to 6.50 percent compared with late
Thursday's level of 6.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond fell 13/16 point with the yield
jumping to 6.20 percent from 6.14 percent a day earlier, according
to Bridge Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-weekend selling came despite a report that wholesale
prices fell 0.3 percent in April, the first drop in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   While encouraging, the data won't be enough to distract the Fed
from all the other recent reports that suggest the economy is
growing at an inflationary pace, analysts said, maintaining that
central bank officials will proceed with an expected interest rate
hike at next Tuesday's meeting. Rising inflation and interest rates
make fixed-income investments like bonds less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Friday, short-term Treasury securities ranged
from 5/32 to 9/32 point higher, while intermediate maturities fell
{ to 19/32 point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 6.10 percent while
the discount rate of 5.94 percent, up 0.01 percentage point. Yields
are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Six-month yields finished at 6.50 percent with a discount of
6.22 percent, rising 0.09 percentage point. One-year yields settled
at 6.37 percent with a discount of 6.06 percent, rising 0.09
percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, held steady at 6.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 to 92 1/16. The average yield to
maturity rose to 6.22 percent compared with late Thursday's 6.20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices were little changed Thursday following the prior
day's big gains as investors turned cautious again before next
week's expected interest rate hike by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 10-year Treasury note rose 3/32
point, or 93} cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.40 percent compared with
late Wednesday's level of 6.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond also rose 3/32 point with the yield
slipping to 6.14 percent from 6.15 percent a day earlier, according
to Bridge Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, worried that heavy spending is aggravating
inflationary pressures, were heartened by a morning report that
revealed a surprise 0.2 percent drop in retail sales during April.
</P>
<P>
   While it was the first decline in nearly two years, economists
said the report wouldn't be enough to stop the Federal Reserve from
boosting interest rates again next week to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and inflation make the fixed payoff on
bonds less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Thursday, short-term Treasury securities ranged
from unchanged to 1/32 point lower, while intermediate maturities
were unchanged to 1/32 point higher.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills held steady at 6.09 percent
while the discount was unchanged at 5.93 percent. Six-month yields
were 6.41 percent with a discount of 6.14 percent, a gain of 0.01
percentage point. One-year yields were unchanged at 6.29 percent
while the discount held steady at 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.06 percent compared with late Wednesday's 5.94
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 to 92\. The average yield to
maturity rose to 6.20 percent from 6.19 percent a day earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
