<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jets Bomb Iraqi Air Defense  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. jets bombed military sites in
northern Iraq Friday for the third consecutive day after being
fired upon by Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery, the U.S. military
said.
</P>
<P>
   The artillery was based near Bashiqah, 250 miles north of
Baghdad, the Germany-based U.S. European Command said.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, the official Iraqi News Agency quoted an
unidentified military spokesman as confirming strikes by ''enemy
warplanes'' in northern Iraq. The spokesman said civilian
installations were hit, but gave no further details.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military denies targeting civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Operating out of Incirlik air force base in southern Turkey, the
United States and Britain have been enforcing northern no-fly zone
in Iraq since the end of the Gulf War in 1991. Allied forces also
impose a similar no-fly zone in the south of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   President Saddam Hussein, who says the zones violate Iraqi
sovereignty, has been challenging the patrols since December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
