<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Rebels OK Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANDA ACEH, Indonesia (AP) -- As thousands of people knelt and
prayed for peace in mosques across Aceh province Friday, Indonesian
government and separatist rebel negotiators meeting in Switzerland
signed the first cease-fire agreement in 25 years of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking examples of the positive reaction by
the war-weary people to the first ray of hope in the territory came
from a rebel stronghold south of the capital, Banda Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   There, dozens of young, heavily armed guerrilla fighters put
down their weapons and gave thanks as they heard news that their
leaders and Indonesia's reformist government had signed the
landmark accord and would begin the three-month cease-fire on June
2.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is great news,'' said rebel commander Tengku Tarzura in
the well-camouflaged camp of flimsy bamboo huts. ''We will abide by
the cease-fire, but we still want independence and will struggle
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there lies the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Even though President Abdurrahman Wahid, Indonesia's first
democratically elected leader in 40 years, appears to have won the
tentative trust of Aceh's rebels, few people believe they will ever
accept his demand to remain part of Indonesia with limited
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may be celebrating in our mosques, and praying and reading
the Koran at home, because the agreement is better than nothing.
But we don't necessarily believe the peace will last here,'' said
Abdul Gani Nurdin, a university lecturer and human rights activist
in Banda Aceh.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan welcomed the
announcement and commended both sides ''for the important first
step they have taken towards the resolution of the problem in
Aceh,'' U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general hopes that a mutually acceptable political
solution can be found in the near future through strict adherence
to the agreement, ''the involvement of the wider Acehnese community
and a strong commitment to peace,'' Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 people have been killed in the fighting in Aceh
in the last decade, including 345 this year. Many of Aceh's 4.3
million people know someone who has died or disappeared during the
insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Embittered by a perceived economic exploitation and an
Indonesian military crackdown, the rebels are fighting not only for
independence, but also for a greater share of the profits from
their oil-rich region, and the right to impose Islamic religious
laws on the Acehnese people.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Wirayuda, Indonesia's permanent U.N. representative in
Geneva, and Zaini Abdullah, a rebel representative based in Sweden,
signed the ''joint understanding on a humanitarian pause'' at an
undisclosed location in Switzerland. The cease-fire will be
regularly reviewed for renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ''This joint understanding is an early step of a hundred-step
journey in the efforts to find a final solution of the Aceh
problem,'' Wirayuda said, adding that the rebels' demands for
independence hadn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum of understanding followed three rounds of talks
organized by the Geneva-based Henry Dunant Center for Humanitarian
Dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   A panel for humanitarian action and another for security
aspects, both based in Banda Aceh, will implement the deal. They
will be supervised by a monitoring team composed of ''five persons
of high integrity.'' A ''joint forum'' based in Switzerland will be
the highest decision-making body.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, a Muslim cleric and reformist who took office in October,
has promised Aceh partial autonomy and a greater share of oil
profits and has reduced the number of soldiers fighting the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   He also has set up a human rights tribunal in Aceh, which is
trying Indonesian soldiers on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a lasting peace in Aceh is a major test for Indonesia, a
country made up of hundreds of different ethnic groups, languages
and several religions, as it continues its painful transition
toward democracy after three decades of authoritarian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Former dictator Suharto, whose 32-year reign came to an abrupt
and violent end in May 1998 during a student uprising, was renowned
for the harsh, repressive measures he ordered his military to use
in trying to stamp out Aceh's insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens after the cease-fire begins, it was clear
Friday that many people in Aceh couldn't wait for it to start,
given how tired they are of the fighting between the rebels and
Indonesian police and soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let peace come soon. Let the fighting end. Let God punish
those who violate the cease-fire,'' students chanted at No. 39, one
of the many crowded and poor public schools in Banda Aceh that
canceled classes Friday to pray that the peace talks would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Banda Aceh, about 10,000 people crammed into the city's
largest mosque and prayed that there would be no more bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Many other towns across the province virtually closed down for
the day as people stayed home or prayed for peace at places of
worship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
