<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Kennedy Views Airport Tape  </HEADLINE>
By LEON DROUIN KEITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rep. Patrick Kennedy and the airport guard
who said he assaulted her at a security checkpoint viewed a
videotape of the March incident Friday and gave their version of
events to a hearing officer.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on whether to file misdemeanor charges against the
Rhode Island Democrat will come in about a week, said Lawrence
Webster, assistant supervisory attorney for the city attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides met at a closed-door hearing at a Superior Court
office. Webster said most cases that go through such quasi-judicial
hearings are settled without charges filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears to have been a successful meeting,'' Webster said
during a news conference after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Della Patton, 58, claims Kennedy shoved and grabbed her March 26
after she told him his bag was too big to fit through an X-ray
scanner at Los Angeles International Airport. She filed a battery
complaint with police.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than filing a misdemeanor battery charge, which carries a
penalty of up to six months in jail and a $2,000 fine, the city
attorney's office ordered Friday's hearing in hopes of resolving
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 32, the son of Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., has
expressed his ''regret that I acted rudely,'' but denied hurting
the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Patton's attorney, George L. Mallory Jr., said his client
''desires to go forward with a criminal case.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the airport security tape shows Kennedy pushing Patton
with his right hand, shoving her into the X-ray machine. Patton
remains arthritic, primarily in the shoulder, and is seeking
workers compensation, he said. She has not been back to work since.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement after the hearing, Kennedy said he was glad for
the opportunity to ''set straight what really happened'' and to
apologize to Patton.
</P>
<P>
   ''After viewing the tape for the first time today, there is
absolutely no question that Ms. Patton's allegations and press
descriptions about the incident are inaccurate,'' Kennedy said.
''As I have said all along, I look forward to the tape being
released to show how this matter has been blown so far out of
proportion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
