<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman abducted, shot by ex-boyfriend dies; witnesses say guard refused help </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A Seton Hall University student dragged
kicking and screaming into a car by her ex-boyfriend who later shot
her and himself died Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The university fired a guard accused of refusing to call for
help, and accepted the resignation of the guard's supervisor. Two
teen-age girls who witnessed the abduction say they begged the
guard to summon help, but he allegedly refused, telling them to
call police themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sohayla Hope Massachi, 23, died at 4:20 p.m. at University
Hospital in Newark, spokesman Rogers Ramsey said. She had been in
grave condition ever since police in Union County broke down the
door to her ex-boyfriend's apartment Wednesday afternoon to find
him dead and her grievously injured with a gunshot wound to the
back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Christopher Honrath, 24, dragged Massachi into
his car outside the campus, then drove to his Westfield apartment,
where he dragged her upstairs. They said he shot her, then himself
as police tried to enter the room after being summoned because of
the commotion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our prayers are with our student, Sohayla Massachi, and her
family during this trying time,'' Seton Hall said in a prepared
statement. ''The university has reviewed the claim that a security
guard failed to respond to a request for assistance from a
bystander. The outcome of the review has resulted in the dismissal
of the security guard from his assignment at Seton Hall. The
university has also accepted the resignation of the supervisor of
the security guard.''
</P>
<P>
   University spokeswoman Laurie Pine would not identify the guard,
the supervisor or the private company that had employed them, but
she said the company will continue to provide on-campus security.
</P>
<P>
   Two 17-year-old students at Columbia High School in Maplewood
said they witnessed the abduction at about 2:30 p.m., and asked the
guard to call for help.
</P>
<P>
   ''She tried to start running. She's screaming, 'Help me! Help
me!' '' Asia Davis told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Friday's
editions. Davis and her friend, Chituru Iromuanya, told the
newspaper they saw a man use a necktie to pull the woman into his
car.
</P>
<P>
   Iromuanya yelled at the man to let the woman go as Davis ran up
Seton Hall's driveway to a guard post.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'There's a woman being kidnapped out there. I have the
license plate number. She needs help.' He told me he couldn't do
anything because he's not a police officer,'' Davis told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   She said the guard picked up his telephone and spoke to someone,
then hung up and told her to walk to South Orange police
headquarters to summon help.
</P>
<P>
   The university's Web site asserts that Seton Hall's security
office ''maintains frequent and current contact with the South
Orange Police Department ... A direct telephone tie-line between
the security office and the South Orange Police Department provides
instant contact with the police department, which is located less
than one-half mile from the campus. All security personnel are
equipped with two-way radios and maintain constant contact with the
dispatcher in the security office.''
</P>
<P>
   Pine did not respond to a request for further information on
security arrangements at the university.
</P>
<P>
   The girls said they ran to Iromuanya's house and called South
Orange police. An officer responded and took information, including
the car's license plate, from them.
</P>
<P>
   But by that time, authorities said, Honrath was already back at
his apartment with Massachi. Police officers knocked on the
apartment door at about 3 p.m. and yelled 'Police!'' They then
heard two shots fired inside the apartment, Assistant Union County
Prosecutor Robert O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a hostage situation was unfolding, the officers
retreated and called for backup, including an emergency response
team, and evacuated neighbors. When no other sounds were heard from
the apartment for a prolonged period, officers decided to storm the
room at about 4:30, O'Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, they found Honrath dead of a self-inflicted gunshot
wound, and Massachi lying on the floor, moaning.
</P>
<P>
   The gun Honrath used had been reported stolen in Ossining, N.Y.,
in 1990, police said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said the prosecutor's office reviewed the response of
Westfield police, and concluded officers had acted properly under
the circumstances. But neither he nor Essex County Assistant
Prosecutor Charlotte Smith would comment on the actions of the
Seton Hall guard. South Orange and Westfield police did not return
numerous telephone calls from The Associated Press on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no legal obligation to assist someone,'' O'Leary said.
''The girls were told it didn't happen on campus and to report it
to local police.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.shu.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
