<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authorities hunt for stolen shipment of potassium cyanide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LINDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Authorities hunted Friday for 20 drums of
potassium cyanide, a potent poison used in metal finishing, that
were stolen from a warehouse in Union County.
</P>
<P>
   The drums, each about as big as beer keg, were inside a shipping
container, along with machinery, car parts and tape measures, that
went missing May 4, Linden police Lt. Jeffrey Vitrano said.
</P>
<P>
   The gray trailer-sized container was hauled away by truck, and
those responsible were probably unaware of their deadly cargo,
Vitrano said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Viewing it from the outside, there was no way of knowing the
contents of the load,'' Vitrano told The Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization says potassium cyanide could be
used by terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the wrong place, this is a very, very nasty thing,'' Steven
Marcus, executive director of the New Jersey Poison Information and
Education System, told The Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   The manmade liquid kills by preventing oxygen from reaching
vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   Drinking it would would mean almost certain death, while
inhaling large amounts could be fatal, Marcus told the newspaper.
It is less likely to be absorbed through the skin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Linden police notified the FBI, State Police, and county
prosecutors, and ask those with information to contact authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The shipping container was to be sent to Puerto Rico through the
Port of Philadelphia, Vitrano said.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium cyanide is often used in electroplating, a process
employed to make silverware and jewelry, Marcus said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
