<HEADLINE> Father: Didn't Mean To Kill Kid  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE SCHNEIDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAVARES, Fla. (AP) -- A man convicted of murder for beating his
6-year-old daughter testified Friday that he didn't mean to hurt
her and had sought repeated help from child welfare workers to deal
with his anger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted help,'' Richard Adams tearfully told 12 jurors who
will recommend whether to send him to death row or give him a life
prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't mean to hurt my daughter. I didn't even mean to spank
her,'' he said. ''I tried to do the best job I could as a parent. I
lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, 26, was convicted of murder Monday for killing Kayla
McKean and burying her in the Ocala National Forest in November
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were sent home Friday and were expected to begin
deliberating on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Adams reported his daughter missing the day before Thanksgiving
1998. Her picture was posted and hundreds of people mobilized into
search parties, forgoing their football games and turkey dinners to
look for the girl.
</P>
<P>
   The community's concern turned to disgust when police arrested
Adams. An investigation revealed child welfare workers repeatedly
had missed signs that Kayla was being abused by Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Kayla's death spurred significant changes in Florida's child
protection system and caused the firings and resignations of
several Department of Children and Families workers in the
district.
</P>
<P>
   During the last months of Kayla's life, Adams was interviewed
three times by investigators with Children and Families, which
opened a case on Kayla after Adams took her to a hospital for
injuries he said she suffered in a bike accident.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he asked for help from the investigators but didn't
receive any. Former DCF investigator Kelly Mahoney had testified
that Adams only asked about counseling for Kayla.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was running out of ways to time-out or discipline her
without getting physical with her,'' Adams said. ''I tried
everything and nothing worked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
