<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bishops Meeting in Canada  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey will lead a
meeting of Anglican and Catholic bishops in examining relations
between the churches almost 500 years after they split.
</P>
<P>
   The six-day gathering that begins Sunday will ''review and
evaluate the accomplishment of thirty years of ecumenical dialogue
between the two traditions,'' said a statement from the Anglican
Communion Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It said the talks emerged from the 1996 meeting between Carey
and Pope John Paul II that concluded with a joint declaration that
the two churches should ''consult further'' about their relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of England emerged in 1534 when King Henry VIII
rejected papal authority because Pope Clement VIII refused to annul
his marriage so he could remarry.
</P>
<P>
   Carey and Cardinal Edward Idris Cassidy, president of the
Vatican's Pontifical Council for Promoting Christian Unity, will
jointly chair the meeting in Toronto, said the Anglican statement.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, considered the main vehicle for dialogue between
the churches, was set up after the 1966 meeting of Anglican
Archbishop Michael Ramsey and Pope Paul VI.
</P>
<P>
   Bishops attending will be from New Zealand, Canada, England, the
United States, Ireland, India, Nigeria, Papua New Guinea, Southern
Africa, Uganda, Australia, Brazil and the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.anglicancommunion.org, www.vatican.va
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
