<HEADLINE> Fate of Algerian in US Unclear  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The fate of an exiled Algerian detained by
U.S. immigration officials for more than three years remained
unclear Friday after his lawyer said he'd been granted asylum.
</P>
<P>
   An Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman said she
couldn't comment on the status of Anwar Haddam, former
representative in Washington of Algeria's banned Islamic Salvation
Front.
</P>
<P>
   Haddam's lawyer, Malea Kibaln, said she was notified Thursday by
mail that he was granted asylum May 5 on an application filed by
his wife, Nafimah. But she said that her client remained in jail in
Virginia a week later and that she had been unable to determine
why.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are investigating this issue and we will have more to say
about it at a later date,'' said INS spokeswoman Maria Cardona.
</P>
<P>
   Haddam ran for Algeria's parliament in 1992 and when it became
clear the Islamic Salvation Front was winning the elections, the
army canceled them and banned the party.
</P>
<P>
   The move triggered a bloody Islamic insurgency that has now
killed more than 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Haddam had been living in the Washington area from 1993 until
late 1996, when his visa status was revoked on Dec. 5, 1996. The
next day he was arrested and has been held in several different
detention centers in Virginia, Kibaln said.
</P>
<P>
   Kibaln said Haddam has been held for so long because of the use
of so-called secret evidence against him, meaning classified
information from secret sources that the government does not have
to reveal and that the accused therefore cannot rebut.
</P>
<P>
   The military arm of the Islamic Salvation Front -- the Islamic
Salvation Army -- was one of two main guerrilla groups fighting the
government.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer says Haddam denies any connection to the violence in
Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has never advocated violence and has always advocated a
peaceful resolution to the conflict in Algeria'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2021 </TRAILER>
