<DOCNO> APW20000512.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famed Authors Plane Said Found  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France (AP) -- A company preparing a documentary on
the author of the children's classic ''The Little Prince'' said
Friday they may have found traces of Antoine de Saint-Exupery's
missing warplane -- a finding that could shed light on his
disappearance during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers at a French maritime works company said they had
likely discovered a piece of the writer's Lockheed P-38 Lightning
plane as they probed the Mediterranean in a search for clues off
the coast of Marseille.
</P>
<P>
   Thierry Carlin, an engineer for Geocean Solmarine, said that all
the other P-38s that crashed in the area during World War II had
already been recovered, so the wreckage probably came from the
plane of Saint-Exupery, who vanished during a July 31, 1944 flight
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a strong chance that this left part of the tail comes
from his plane,'' Carlin, who headed the search team, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Saint-Exupery had taken off from the island of Corsica and was
flying near the French coast on an Allied mission against the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated searches of the coast have failed to turn up the plane,
leaving the author's disappearance shrouded in mystery for 56
years. Theories have ranged from hostile gunfire to mechanical
problems to suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin said his company and another underwater research group,
Comex, discovered the tail piece 132 feet underwater in April
during research for the documentary, to be aired Arte television
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin said the company will check with maritime authorities
before attempting to bring the wreckage to the surface. The
Marseille headquarters of Maritime Affairs was not immediately
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The tail piece was discovered less than about one mile from the
rocky inlet where a fisherman discovered a bracelet that may have
belonged to the author, Carlin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2031 </TRAILER>
