<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Paper Presses Ahead  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- No one's in Los Alamos, but they're going
to get their paper.
</P>
<P>
   Before fire forced evacuation of the town on Wednesday, the Los
Alamos Monitor managed to publish its afternoon edition. The two
dozen staffers scattered, so the paper could not publish its
Thursday and Friday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Help came from The Santa Fe New Mexican, which set up a
makeshift newsroom for the Monitor in its building in Sante Fe,
about 35 miles away. The Monitor planned to insert its own special
section in the Sante Fe newspaper on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're actually part of the story, it's just an enormous
challenge to cover it. It's exhausting,'' said Chris Dissinger,
Monitor general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The staff had taken refuge in Dissinger's home, in nearby White
Rock. But they had to flee that town early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Monitor, which has a circulation of about 5,100, hopes to
get back to the Los Alamos office next week. Landmark Community
Newspapers, the paper's parent publishing company, sent employees
from other Landmark papers to help out.
</P>
</TEXT>
