<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Game winner bought ticket with $98 in change from hot dog  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY BARKS HOFFMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- A swimming-pool installer who put down a
$100 bill for a hot dog and 98 lottery tickets stepped forward with
his wife and three children Friday to claim half of the
record-breaking $363 million jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess I'd like to start a new job playing golf,'' said Larry
Ross, a 47-year-old occasional lottery player accustomed to working
80 to 100 hours a week in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't had a summer vacation in 13 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's looking to retire, buy a boat, buy a house, and maybe
buy the purple Jaguar his wife has always wanted. He plans to save
some of the money and give some of it to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to do anything rash. We're going to invest
wisely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who spent his hot dog change on Big Game tickets at his
wife's urging, was the first of two mega-winners of Tuesday's
drawing to come forward. He said that when he he stopped at Mr. K's
Party Shoppe to buy a hot dog, all he had was a $100 bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked the guy to give me change in lotto tickets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other winning ticket was sold in Lake Zurich, Ill., 30 miles
northwest of Chicago. That winner has not yet contacted Illinois
lottery officials, a spokeswoman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross paused at the end of his news conference to wipe away
tears, but otherwise appeared as ''remarkably quite calm'' as
lottery officials said he was when he first called them on
Wednesday. But he says he was anything but calm when he started
calling family members to tell them of the win.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the voice got shriller and the tears got bigger, they
believed me,'' he said of his originally skeptical relatives.
</P>
<P>
   After he saw the winning numbers on television Wednesday
morning, ''I invented a new dance -- I started doing the lottery
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ''I haven't slept in three days. It's a great diet
program, win the lotto and lose weight. I haven't eaten in three
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross and his wife, Nancy, 45, have been married 25 years. They
have three children: Ian, 21, Eric, 25, Shannon, 12. All three
attended the news conference, along with Eric's wife, Jamie, and
Ian's fiancee, Katie Niemasz.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosses will take their share of the jackpot in a one-time
lump-sum payment of about $90.3 million before taxes. After the
lottery deducts 28 percent for federal taxes and 4.2 percent in
state income taxes, the Rosses will get about $61.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously we'll have more toys, but we'll be the same
people,'' he said, describing himself as someone who likes to joke
around and laugh.
</P>
<P>
   At Mr. K's Party Shoppe near Utica, 20 miles north of Detroit,
store owner George Kassab and his family cheered as they watched
the news conference on television.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the one, he's the one who called,'' said Melvin Kassab,
the owner's son, who sold the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he and his family hope to be able to weather the media
attention until his daughter, Shannon, finishes seventh grade next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Then his family plans to move from their four-bedroom ranch in
Shelby Township to a more secure neighborhood somewhere in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have the ecstasy of winning and then you start realizing
the agony of what might happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got security problems now. You think about your family,
who's at risk. We're not in a secure neighborhood. We don't have
security like rich people have.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross, his wife and two of his children came to Lansing on
Wednesday to claim the prize, but neither lottery officials nor the
Rosses were ready to hold a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials confirmed he had the winning ticket, then made
up a symbolic $150,000 check for the family to carry out of the
Lottery Commission so the media wouldn't catch on.
</P>
<P>
   The ploy worked, allowing the Rosses to keep their win a secret
for two more days. The family has already contacted a lawyer and
financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he wrote down the winning numbers incorrectly Tuesday
night on the way home and didn't realize one of his Easy Picks was
a winner until Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing pumped $29 million into Michigan's fund for K-12
schools. ''The real winners are the kids in Michigan,'' Michigan
Lottery Commissioner Don Gilmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's drawing capped days of frenzy that sent lottery
veterans and first-timers alike scurrying for $1 chances at the big
dream. By the time it was over, the seven states that jointly offer
the Big Game had sold some 358 million tickets after the previous
jackpot -- $15 million, in the Feb. 11 drawing, was claimed by L.E.
Bird of Warren.
</P>
<P>
   The winning numbers drawn Tuesday were 1, 2, 12, 33, 37 and Big
Money Ball 4. To win, a ticket had to match all six numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There were 72 tickets matching all the numbers except the Big
Money Ball. Each is worth $150,000 before taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The states that participate in the Big Game are Georgia,
Illinois, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey and
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The jackpot easily topped the previous American record, a $295.7
million Powerball jackpot split two years ago by 13 machinists in
Westerville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the largest Big Game jackpot was $197 million
awarded solely to Maria Grasso, a 54-year-old Chilean immigrant
living in Massachusetts. She won in the April 6, 1999 drawing.
</P>
<P>
   The world lottery record is $1.2 billion, set in December by
Spain's El Gordo, or the Fat One. But that game awards thousands of
prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Big Game: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
