<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shots Fired in Nicaragua Assembly  </HEADLINE>
By FILADELFO ALEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- A congressman accused of bigamy
repeatedly fired a pistol in the National Assembly on Friday and
threatened to kill himself before finally surrendering after a
five-hour standoff.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Marlon Boanerges Castillo, 41, fired at least 14
shots and held the gun to his head as friends and relatives begged
him to stop, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   After about five hours, he fell to his knees and wept as another
congressman read a psalm to calm him. Castillo prayed and turned
the gun over to a priest, said Msgr. Eddy Montenegro, Roman
Catholic vicar-general of Managua, who came to the scene at
Castillo's request.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro told reporters that Castillo admitted the allegations
made last week by his first wife, who said she had only recently
discovered that the congressman was the husband she had thought
died in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has congressional immunity, he was not arrested. It
was not immediately clear where Castillo had gone.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began last week when Maritza del Carmen Sequeira
Morales told reporters that Castillo was actually her husband, Jose
Antonio Alvarez Urbina, whom she married in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   She said the couple had four daughters before Alvarez went off
to fight with the U.S.-backed Contra rebels against the leftist
Sandinista government, which was finally defeated in a 1990
election.
</P>
<P>
   She said she thought he had died in 1984. But a friend
eventually pointed out the congressman. She said she discovered
that he had created a new identity with a false birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Castillo at first denied the charges and claimed that Sequeira
was trying to blackmail him.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked congress to remove his immunity this week,
Castillo denied her claims and accused her of trying to blackmail
him.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly weary, Castillo left the legislative chamber supported
by his current wife, Carolina Moreira, and followed by
anti-terrorist police, congressmen and nurses, one of whom carried
a straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   Congresswoman Angeles Rios said Castillo wanted to kill himself
before journalists to let the world know about his dilemma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
