<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia: US Sending Usable Arms  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARTAGENA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's military chief on Friday
played down reports that the Pentagon gave the Andean country old
and potentially dangerous ammunition for fighting the war on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't had any incidents, any problems,'' Gen. Fernando
Tapias told The Associated Press. ''The ammunition we have received
is perfectly usable.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapias spoke during a day of meetings in this Caribbean port
between top U.S. and Colombian officials to discuss a proposed $1.7
billion U.S. anti-narcotics aid package being debated on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Under Secretary of State Thomas Pickering met with President
Andres Pastrana, then held a news conference at which he criticized
congressional delays in approving the massive plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm convinced that every day we have to wait represents seven
days in the future to recover the time that has been lost,''
Pickering said, speaking in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether the funds for eradicating coca and opium
crops are approved, Pickering said officials were planning
''interim steps'' to attack drug production in Putumayo, the
southern state where coca is growing the fastest. He did not
provide details on those plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Times reported Thursday that the U.S. State
Department last year sent Colombia 17 million rounds of .50-caliber
ammunition made in 1952, despite a warning from the manufacturer
that the Korean war-era bullets were dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The warning was against using the ammunition in Gatling guns
mounted on U.S.-built Blackhawk helicopters, which are used in
attack roles and to ferry troops into combat with guerrillas or on
drug eradication missions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. embassy spokesman Robert Schmidt said the October 1999
shipment of Korean War-era ammunition included only 2 million
.50-caliber rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the only type of .50-caliber ammunition the Pentagon
had available at that time,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Pentagon did not inform the State Department of the manufacturer's
warning until May 1, six months after the rounds were shipped to
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians must fire the older ammunition at a slower rate
than possible with newer ammunition, but it still meets their
requirements, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2045 </TRAILER>
