<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds: Ecstasy Drug Gains Popularity  </HEADLINE>
By MAY WONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Customs agents intercepted nearly a half
million tablets of ecstasy that arrived on a passenger flight from
Paris, disguised inside cargo boxes that were shrink-wrapped and
labeled as cotton pants.
</P>
<P>
   The bust Monday was one of the largest ecstasy seizures in the
country and reflects a sharp increase in the popularity of the
hallucinogenic drug, said Robert Stiriti, an assistant agent in
charge of the Customs Service's San Francisco office.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the drug of choice of young partygoers today,'' Stiriti
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstasy, also known as MDMA, usually comes in a small powdery
pill. It is popular at nightclubs and sells for about $45 per
tablet.
</P>
<P>
   The 490,000 tablets confiscated from a United Airlines flight at
San Francisco International Airport top the 400,000 tablets seized
nationwide in 1997 and push this year's total to 5.2 million pills,
compared with 3.5 million seized all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure was the result of a yearlong sting operation and led
to the arrest of Ben Wizmann, 41, at his Los Angeles home. He
allegedly paid a federal informant $9,000 to smuggle three
100-pound packages past Customs officials at the San Francisco
airport.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with conspiracy, smuggling and other charges and
held without bail. It was unclear whether he had an attorney who
could comment.
</P>
<P>
   More arrests are expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
