<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Dead in Colombia Massacre  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Suspected rightist paramilitary gunmen
barged into a seaside village early Friday and killed nine people
they accused of being rebel informants, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 80 armed men carried out the attack in a town
on the outskirts of Buenaventura, a bustling Pacific seaport 215
miles west of the capital, Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the assassins left spray-painted slogans indicating
they were members of a ''self-defense'' group, the term Colombia's
rightist militias use to describe themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's national paramilitary umbrella organization claimed
in a communique that 12 people were executed in Friday's raid.
Police put the figure at nine.
</P>
<P>
   Founded by landowners and drug traffickers seeking protection
against extortion and kidnappings by leftist guerrillas, Colombia's
paramilitary groups have killed thousands of people in a
scorched-earth war against suspected leftists.
</P>
<P>
   The militias have made repeated inroads into areas previously
held by the rebels, often marking the incursions with massacres.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
