<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gretzky Mulls Stake in Coyotes  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Could the Great One remake a not-so-great team in
his image? Phoenix hockey fans might be about to find out.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky, who retired last year planning to spend two years
away from hockey, is considering becoming part owner of the Phoenix
Coyotes along with prospective lead investor Steve Ellman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely the right offer. It's just a question if it's
the right time,'' Gretzky told The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's home phone number is unlisted, and Michael Barnett,
his agent, did not immediately return phone calls to his office
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been discussions,'' said Jeffrey Hecht, a spokesman
for Ellman. ''We're hopeful that we can reach that agreement.
Obviously, bringing Wayne Gretzky aboard would be wonderful for the
Coyotes and their fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecht declined to discuss the timetable for reaching an
agreement with the Hall of Fame forward, but said it could take
place quickly. The NHL Board of Governors will meet to approve the
sale on June 20, and the ownership package must be finalized in
advance of that date.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman, the principal of a company building an arena for the
Coyotes in a Scottsdale mall, earned his fortune in real estate and
has no background in sports ownership.
</P>
<P>
   He has been looking for investors to help him buy the team from
Richard Burke for $87 million, and Gretzky, the biggest star in
hockey history, appears to be an ideal partner.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky holds most NHL scoring records, and the league retired
his No. 99 in Toronto during the All-Star week in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''His name is magic in hockey,'' NHL spokesman Frank Brown said.
''If this is something that Wayne wants, it would be delightful to
see it come to fruition. But there's a significant difference
between discussions and the consummation of a deal, so any reaction
from us would be purely speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have had big names before.
</P>
<P>
   The Winnipeg Jets broke into the World Hockey Association with
Bobby Hull as their star. But since the franchise joined the NHL in
1979, the Jets-Coyotes have made the playoffs 14 times and been
eliminated in the first round 12 times -- the last nine in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Burke bought the Jets in 1995 with Steve Gluckstern for $65
million and moved the franchise to Phoenix in 1996, buying out
Gluckstern two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman's first payment to Burke reportedly is set for Wednesday
-- a $10 million cash transfer, with an additional $17 million due
by June 30. The remaining $60 million would be financed by transfer
of French bank Societe Generale's loan from Burke to Ellman.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale has an interest in the sale because the $170 million,
18,000-seat arena is the centerpiece of a $535 redevelopment the
city believes will rejuvenate a deteriorating neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Coyotes hockey team is viewed as the key anchor tenant for
this project, and anything that strengthens and stabilizes the
organization is a major positive,'' city redevelopment director
Gary Roe said. ''Mr. Gretzky is synonymous with hockey, and his
reputation, his credentials are obviously of tremendous appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   He said adding Gretzky to the ownership mix would be consistent
with Ellman's approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Ellman Cos. have shown a pattern of trying to bring in the
best expertise they can,'' Roe said.
</P>
<P>
   Demolition is under way at the site of the new arena, but the
city is waiting for Ellman Cos. to revise the site plan before
committing to spend $352 million in public money on the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2105 </TRAILER>
