<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Justifies Nuclear Decision  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
justified Israel's refusal to sign the Nuclear Nonproliferation
Treaty on Friday, saying Iraq and Iran posed too great a threat to
be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a fact that the technology purchased by Iran is intended
in order to develop weapons of mass destruction and long range
missiles,'' Levy said, adding that some of the missiles could reach
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking to reporters as a monthlong conference reviewing
the treaty wrapped up its third week of work. Israel has come under
fire at the conference for being the only country in the Middle
East that hasn't signed the treaty or allowed its nuclear
facilities to be inspected by the International Atomic Energy
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has neither confirmed nor denied its nuclear capability
and has said it wants to work out issues of nuclear disarmament
regionally.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not reached a state of tranquility and calmness that
we can say the friends of Israel can guarantee the future,'' he
said, citing Iraq's nuclear capabilities as well as Iran's.
</P>
</TEXT>
