<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Mexico Fire Still Rages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A Los Alamos wildfire remained out of control today
in the nearby forests and canyons today and residents were told they could not
return to their houses for at least a week. Blowtorch winds and searing heat
that fed the fire eased. The fire, which began with a government-prescribed burn
to clear brush, damaged the town's nuclear weapons laboratory and forced 25,000
people to flee. The weapon lab appeared out of danger, and all of the facility's
major buildings were unscathed, said Richard Burick, deputy lab director for
operations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Bush Offering Gun Ideas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today announced grants to develop
''smart gun'' technology while Gov. George W. Bush said he will distribute free
trigger locks in Texas. Filling out the election-year debate, Vice President Al
Gore acknowledged that he often voted with the National Rifle Association during
his early years in Congress, but they have parted ways. Bush and Gore sat down
for interviews on morning television shows, raising their voices on one of the
most volatile issues of the presidential campaign season. Recent polls show
voters split between Gore and Bush on whom they trust on gun policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesia, Rebels OK Cease-Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BANDA ACEH, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesian government and separatist rebel
negotiators meeting in Switzerland signed the first cease-fire agreement in 25
years of fighting. One of the most striking examples of the positive reaction by
the war-weary people to the first ray of hope in the territory came from a rebel
stronghold south of the capital, Banda Aceh. There, dozens of young, heavily
armed guerrilla fighters put down their weapons and gave thanks as they heard
news that their leaders and Indonesia's reformist government had signed the
landmark accord and would begin the three-month cease-fire on June 2.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maine Negotiates Drug Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Maine is the first state to decide to use its bargaining
power to negotiate prices of prescription medicine for people without coverage.
Tired of waiting for Congress to act, many states are closely watching Maine's
bold experiment. Maine's plan was signed into legislation late yesterday. Maine
is also threatening to become the first state to enact price controls on
prescription drugs if the negotiations fail to hold down prices by 2003. The
pharmaceutical industry is expected to challenge the law in court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
German Leader: Welcome Foreigners
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Stepping into a national debate on immigration, Germany's
president urged his compatriots Friday to show more tolerance for foreigners and
condemned politicians who play on racist themes. In a speech marking his first
year in office, President Johannes Rau also said Germany must not be afraid to
think about controlling immigration if that would help ease the integration of 7
million foreigners already living here. ''That people of different origins and
cultures all live in our country will not change,'' Rau said. ''We need a new
effort so all people in Germany can live together -- an effort without fears,
and without getting dreamy.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Interactive TV: Shop by Remote
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- By unleashing the powers of interactivity, cable
businesses are partnering with software and technology companies to turn
television commerce into much more than home shopping channels. With a few
points and clicks of a remote, consumers could order a pizza with their favorite
toppings right off their TV screen, buy a CD during a live broadcast concert or
request information from a local dealer during a car commercial. Special
software added to cable boxes on consumers' TVs make possible interactive
functions such as shopping directly from the screen.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 63; Nasdaq Gains 29
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after the report of a decline in wholesale
prices in April helped quell worries about rising interest rates. The Dow Jones
industrial average ended up 63.40 points at 10,609.37. On the NYSE, gainers led
losers 1,604-1,330. The Nasdaq rose 29.48 to 3,529.06. For the week, the Dow
lost a total of 31.51 points and the Nasdaq lost 287.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Czechs Vs. Slovaks in Hockey Final
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- The two halves of former Czechoslovakia will
meet in a historic final at the World Hockey Championships. The world champion
Czech Republic beat Canada 2-1 in one semifinal Friday after Slovakia upset
Finland 3-1. The two nations have played before in the world championships, but
Sunday's game will mark the first time the Czechs and Slovaks will play for a
gold medal. Canada will play for the bronze on Sunday against Finland, which won
the silver medal the last two years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
