<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Remember Congo's Trouble, Too  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The peacekeeping crisis in Sierra Leone
should not cloud the international community's responsibility to
help restore peace in the Congo, a U.N. Security Council delegation
that traveled to the region warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the full 15-member council, the delegation headed
by U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said Congo's renewed
cease-fire -- though fragile -- ''is an important basis for future
peacemaking and must not be given up lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands' U.N. Ambassador Peter Van Walsum, who presented
the report, said the delegation came back from the continent with
''a positive impression'' of the current stage of implementation of
the cease-fire agreement signed last summer by the government and
rebel forces and their backers in Lusaka, Zambia and reaffirmed
April 14.
</P>
<P>
   Van Walsum delivered the report on the day that Ethiopia and
Eritrea renewed their two-year-old border conflict, and some 500
U.N. peacekeepers remained hostage to rebel forces in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Developments in Sierra Leone ''inevitably cast a shadow'' over
the Congo mission but ''should not be allowed to cloud the
international community's responsibility in the Democratic Republic
of the Congo and its capacity to make a real difference there,''
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Van Walsum called on council members to fight the negative
effects of the conflicts Sierra Leone and Ethiopia-Eritrea and
judge Congo on its own merits.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our problem is how do we sell this information to an
international public ... that feels that Africa is falling apart,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member council delegation visited the Congo and
neighboring countries which are signatories to last summer's
agreement to assess prospects for its implementation and the
deployment of a planned 5,537-member U.N. observer mission.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mission, which would include 3,700 fighting troops and
500 monitors, is part of the peace process to end the 22-month
civil war in which five foreign armies are entangled.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan must decide whether security
conditions are sufficient for the troops to do their job before
giving green light for deployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
