<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, May 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Mexico Fire Still Rages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A Los Alamos wildfire that began as a
government-prescribed burn to clear brush remained out of control today in the
nearby forests and canyons. Residents were told they could not return to their
houses for at least a week as blowtorch winds and searing heat that fed the fire
eased. The fire forced 25,000 people to flee their homes and also damaged the
town's nuclear weapons laboratory. The weapon lab appeared out of danger, and
all of the facility's major buildings were unscathed, said Richard Burick,
deputy lab director for operations.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ethiopia, Eritrea Fighting Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ignoring international pleas to end their
two-year border conflict, Ethiopia and Eritrea returned to open war on Friday
with fighting reported on three fronts. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
predicted ''a very brutal war,'' and expressed frustration that peace efforts
had failed. The two sides issued contradictory statements on the details of the
fighting, but both agreed that war had erupted once again along the 620-mile
frontier, which contains a now-evacuated stretch of fertile land of great value
in this drought-wracked region of Africa. The U.N. Security Council demanded the
two countries immediately stop fighting and hinted at a possible arms embargo if
Africa's newest war doesn't dissipate over the weekend.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indonesia, Rebels OK Cease-Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BANDA ACEH, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesian government and separatist rebel
negotiators meeting in Switzerland signed the first cease-fire agreement in 25
years of fighting. In a rebel stronghold south of the capital, Banda Aceh,
dozens of young, heavily armed guerrilla fighters put down their weapons and
gave thanks as they heard news that their leaders and Indonesia's reformist
government had signed the landmark accord and would begin the three-month
cease-fire on June 2.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Bush Offering Gun Ideas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today announced grants to develop
''smart gun'' technology while Gov. George W. Bush said he will distribute free
trigger locks in Texas. Filling out the election-year debate, Vice President Al
Gore acknowledged that he often voted with the National Rifle Association during
his early years in Congress, but they have parted ways. Bush and Gore sat down
for interviews on morning television shows, raising their voices on one of the
most volatile issues of the presidential campaign season. Recent polls show
voters split between Gore and Bush on whom they trust on gun policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maine Negotiates Drug Prices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Maine is the first state to decide to use its bargaining
power to negotiate prices of prescription medicine for people without coverage.
Tired of waiting for Congress to act, many states are closely watching Maine's
bold experiment. Maine's plan was signed into legislation late yesterday. Maine
is also threatening to become the first state to enact price controls on
prescription drugs if the negotiations fail to hold down prices by 2003. The
pharmaceutical industry is expected to challenge the law in court.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
German Leader: Welcome Foreigners
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Germany's president urged his compatriots Friday to show more
tolerance for foreigners and condemned politicians who play on racist themes. In
a speech marking his first year in office, President Johannes Rau also said
Germany must not be afraid to think about controlling immigration if that would
help ease the integration of 7 million foreigners already living here. ''We need
a new effort so all people in Germany can live together -- an effort without
fears, and without getting dreamy,'' Raud said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
World's Great Apes Are Disappearing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LISLE, Ill. (AP) -- The world's great apes are hurtling toward extinction at
a rate that is alarming scientists. At an urgent meeting this week of wildlife
and zoo researchers from 12 nations, experts said new estimates of the
populations of chimpanzees, gorillas and orangutans are far lower than they were
even a year or two ago, with some species down to a few thousand, or even a few
hundred.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 63; Nasdaq Gains 29
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after the report of a decline in wholesale
prices in April helped quell worries about rising interest rates. The Dow Jones
industrial average ended up 63.40 points at 10,609.37. On the NYSE, gainers led
losers 1,604-1,330. The Nasdaq rose 29.48 to 3,529.06. For the week, the Dow
lost a total of 31.51 points and the Nasdaq lost 287.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Red Sox Crush Orioles 9-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Pedro Martinez pitched a two-hitter and struck out 15 as
the Boston Red Sox beat the slumping Baltimore Orioles 9-0 tonight. Pitching for
the first time since May 6 because of a suspension, Martinez (6-1) allowed only
two baserunners. The 1999 Cy Young winner was suspended for hitting Cleveland's
Roberto Alomar with a pitch on April 30.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
