<HEADLINE> By The Associated Press  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressTories Attempt To Distinguish Themselves From Alliance
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEBEC (AP) -- Federal Tories began to stake their ground as a
fiscally conservative party with a heart Friday, putting in the
first planks of a policy platform that includes eliminating the
personal capital gains tax and a fixed schedule to reduce the
national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates at the four-day policy convention also approved a
motion that would increase the basic personal exemption on income
tax to $12,000 from the current $7,131 within two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tory rank and file grappled with how far they should go
on the economic front, debating the impact that policies would have
on poorer Canadians and social programs.
</P>
<P>
   They rejected a motion for a single flat income tax, similar to
the one their political rivals in the Canadian Alliance have
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance is a constant consideration at the Tory gathering,
given that it has attracted a number of high-profile Conservatives
to its ranks with the promise of tough fiscal measures and a shot
at forming government.
Alberta Man Wants Charges Against Tax Agents
</P>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta (AP) -- An Alberta man says Revenue Canada
harassed his wife so much she committed suicide and he wants
criminal charges laid against two tax agents.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stephan, 47, of Cardston, Alberta, has been in a battle
over back taxes with the Canada Customs and Revenue Agency,
formerly known as Revenue Canada, for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   When Debora Stephan, 40, killed herself in January 1994, the
mother of 10 left a note for her husband instructing him to use her
life insurance money to pay more than $27,000 in back taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan, along with his new wife and their children, held a
small rally in front of the federal building in Calgary on Friday
to draw attention to their plight.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Alliance MP Jason Kenney renewed his call for a
taxpayers' bill of rights that would include an ombudsManitoba
</P>
<P>
   He wants charges laid against two Revenue Canada agents,
alleging a breach of trust. He alleges the agents did not follow a
department manual that outlines how to deal with people in hardship
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan had filed a lawsuit against the federal department but
no longer wants to go that route.
Critics Slam Officials After Killers Moved to Same Jail
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Political pressure won't change Ottawa's decision
to imprison together the lesbian lovers who fatally stabbed a
Toronto police officer in 1998, says Correctional Services Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Cece, 41, and Mary Barbara Taylor, 31, were transferred
to the Joliette prison for women in Quebec last month after being
convicted in November 1999 in the stabbing death of Det.-Const.
William Hancox.
</P>
<P>
   They were moved to the medium-security facility -- often referred
to as ''Club Fed'' -- after a careful assessment of possible
rehabilitation and the risk they might pose to other inmates and
staff, corrections spokesman Jacques Belanger said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Political considerations or public opinion are never a factor in
such decisions, he added.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Connor, the lawyer who defended Taylor at trial, said
Friday the two inmates were not being housed in the same unit.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime victims' rights advocate Priscilla DeVilliers said
Friday it's wrong to incarcerate together two people whose crime
was clearly a mutual act.
Toronto Police Dog on Lam in Minnesota
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A valuable Canadian police dog who once sniffed
out criminals in downtown Toronto is now himself on the lam in
rural Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy, a street-smart Belgian Malinois who was in the U.S.
training to find bombs and bodies, escaped from his owner's truck
last weekend near Backus, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several sightings of Rudy in the woodsy U.S.
countryside, but trainer Joe Jasicki has as yet been unable to
apprehend the prized canine, estimated to be worth $20,000 US.
</P>
<P>
   So impressed was Jasicki with Rudy's talents, he was preparing
to sell the dog for a handsome price next week at a U.S. police
conference in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   But only if the canny canine turns himself in.
</P>
</TEXT>
