<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Associate editor fired over fabricated letters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- An editorial page editor was fired Friday
after admitting he made up letters to the editor that appeared in
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Donna M. Donovan, president and publisher of the Gannett-owned
Utica Observer-Dispatch, said that an internal investigation by the
newspaper found that 11 letters in last Sunday's newspaper -- all
commenting on a column written by Russ Davis -- were fabricated by
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said that Davis, who worked at the paper 20 years, also
admitted to making up several other letters that had appeared in
the approximately 50,000-daily and 60,000-Sunday circulation paper
during the past three months. He said he did not remember the
specifics, Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a standard practice for confirming letters to the
editor before they are published,'' said Donovan. ''Because Russ
Davis oversaw the page and also was the person who produced it, he
was able to circumvent that process without detection.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said she and others became suspicious when so many
letters on Davis' column regarding Vietnam appeared in last
Sunday's Observer-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were unable to confirm 11 people listed as letter
writers,'' Donovan said. ''After we called this to Russ' attention,
he admitted that he had created the letters to give the appearance
of high interest in his column. For this serious violation of
journalistic principles, we terminated Russ' employment.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Donovan, Davis said he made up letters that
appeared May 7 and were attributed to: William George, Utica; Peter
Murphy, Rome; Ronald Randolph, Utica; George Hawkins, Utica; Don
Barber, Utica; Rick Jackson, Rome; Kelly McDonough, Clinton; Jack
Potter, New Hartford; Norman Roberts, Utica; Gabe Richfield, Utica,
and Vivian Benning, Utica.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Gannett Newspaper Division and Observer-Dispatch
Principles of Ethical Conduct for Newsrooms, such practices are
prohibited. ''We are seeking to build trust with our readers. Such
activities cannot be allowed, and won't be,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wolber, Davis' lawyer, said his client ''felt very badly''
about the incident and was still looking into the specific
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of whatever may have been done, Mr. Davis feels very
badly,'' Wolber said. ''But there was definitely no one harmed by
anything that he did -- no malice to anyone, no harm to anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
