<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Editor Fired Over Fake Letters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- An editorial page editor was fired Friday
after admitting he fabricated letters to the editor that appeared
in the newspaper -- letters that commented on his own column.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Davis, who worked at the Gannett-owned Utica
Observer-Dispatch for 20 years, made up 11 letters published in
Sunday's newspaper, said publisher Donna Donovan, citing an
internal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also admitted making up several other letters that had
appeared over the past three months, Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a standard practice for confirming letters to the
editor before they are published,'' she said. ''Because Russ Davis
oversaw the page and also was the person who produced it, he was
able to circumvent that process without detection.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said she and others became suspicious when so many
letters on Davis' column regarding Vietnam appeared in last
Sunday's paper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were unable to confirm 11 people listed as letter
writers,'' Donovan said. ''After we called this to Russ' attention,
he admitted that he had created the letters to give the appearance
of high interest in his column.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wolber, Davis' lawyer, said his client was still looking
into the specific allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''In terms of whatever may have been done, Mr. Davis feels very
badly,'' Wolber said. ''But there was definitely no one harmed by
anything that he did -- no malice to anyone, no harm to anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
