<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Leader Supporting Rwanda  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi on Friday
pledged his support for Rwanda in an escalating crisis with its
ally Uganda, whose troops have clashed with the Rwandan army in
northern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Moi's one-day visit, the first in more than a decade, marks a
turnabout in Kenya's relations with Rwanda, which had been
estranged since the 1994 genocide of more than 500,000 people on
orders of the former Hutu extremist government that had enjoyed
support of Moi.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan President Paul Kagame, a former leader of the Tutsi-led
rebels who in July 1994 won power and stopped the genocide, said
the situation in the northern Congolese city of Kisangani, which is
divided between Rwandan and Ugandan troops, was for the moment
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan soldiers clashed with Ugandan forces in Kisangani last
week and again on Tuesday, leaving at least 28 civilians and 15
soldiers dead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.N. military observers already in Kisangani, said
British Col. James Baxter, head of the U.N. military observer team
already in Congo, landed there Friday on a mission to meet with
both the armies that had pledged to withdraw from the city and hand
it over to members of the 5,537-strong U.N. force that is supposed
to deploy in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Both armies are in Congo in support of the rebels opposed to
Congolese President Laurent Kabila. But the lack of common strategy
and support for rival rebel factions led to fighting in Kisangani
last August and again last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kagame said that Ugandan forces had massed troops on their
common border, something he said he hoped to discuss with Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni when they meet on Sunday in the Tanzanian
town of Mwanza on Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't consider Ugandans as our enemies,'' Kagame told
reporters. ''Given the history between the two countries ... the
good relations are important. We shall continue to seek
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Kagame said that Moi's visit will add weight to regional efforts
to resolve the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Landlocked Rwanda and Uganda are both dependent on Kenya's
Indian Ocean port of Mombasa through which they receive most of
their imports and particularly war materiel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2219 </TRAILER>
