<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressStanley Boxer:
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Stanley Boxer, an abstract artist known
for his thickly brushed paintings, died Monday of complications
from colon cancer. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's artistic interests ranged among painting, drawing,
sculpture and printmaking. And within his paintings, he explored a
variety of styles.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's works are in the permanent collections of many museums,
including the Museum of Modern Art and the Whitney Museum of
American Art in New York, the Boston Museum of Fine Art and the
Hirshhorn Museum in Washington, D.C.
Gervase Cowell:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Gervase Cowell, a British diplomat who was
expelled from the Soviet Union for having contact with an
informant, died May 2. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Posted to the British Embassy in Moscow in 1962, Cowell was
expelled the next year following the Soviets' discovery that Col.
Oleg Penkovsky, a member of the Soviet secret service, had been
passing information to U.S. and British contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Cowell was among 12 Americans and Britons identified by Soviet
authorities as Penkovsky's principal contacts. Penkovsky was
arrested and executed.
Maynard Hicks:
</P>
<P>
   PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Longtime Washington State University
journalism professor Maynard Hicks died May 5 of complications
following an automobile accident. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks taught journalism at the school's Edward R. Murrow School
of Communications for 35 years until 1972.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving WSU, he taught at Western Washington University in
Bellingham and for 10 years at California state universities in
Fullerton and Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a son and daughter-in-law, Hicks' survivors
include a daughter and her husband, three grandchildren and four
great-grandchildren.
Alex Kerr:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Alex ''Andy'' Kerr, a Navy captain who figured in
a key decision in the life of Lee Harvey Oswald, died Saturday of
cancer of the larynx. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy and went on to become
an aide to four secretaries of the Navy, most prominently with John
Connally in the Kennedy administration.
</P>
<P>
   A former academy colleague, Hank Searls, recalled the day that
Kerr received a letter from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ''The writer, one Lee Harvey Oswald, asked that the secretary
reverse his Marine Corps less-than-honorable discharge and grant
him an honorable one, but Kerr had never been a rubber-stamp
bureaucrat. He learned Oswald had been a lousy Marine,'' Searls
said. ''He advised Secretary Connally to turn down the request.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally, who went on to become governor of Texas, was wounded
when Oswald shot President John Kennedy to death on Nov. 22, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ''A Journey Amongst the Good and the Great,'' Kerr
speculated that Oswald might have been gunning for Connally rather
than the president.
C.E. Olsen:
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- C.E. ''Pat'' Olsen, the man for
whom Texas A&AMP;M's baseball facility is named, died Thursday. He was
97.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen was a three-year letterman as a pitcher at Texas A&AMP;M in
the 1920s. He went on to play in the New York Yankees farm system
and was Lou Gehrig's roommate for part of one summer.
</P>
<P>
   He was named to the Texas A&AMP;M Athletic Hall of Fame in 1978 and
a Distinguished Alumnus in 1981. He is also a member of the Texas
Baseball Hall of Fame.
Craig Stevens:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Craig Stevens, the actor who played the suave
private eye ''Peter Gunn'' in the 1950s TV series, died Wednesday
of cancer. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   ''Peter Gunn,'' which was created by filmmaker Blake Edwards,
debuted in 1958 and was known for its film noir style, deadpan
humor and jazzy theme song by Henry Mancini.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens appeared in many films throughout the 1940s and 1950s,
including ''Humoresque,'' ''Since You Went Away'' and ''Night Unto
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   He later appeared on television shows such as ''Dallas'' and
''Man of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   His last role in a major film was in Edwards' Hollywood satire
''S.O.B.'' in 1981.
Paula Wessely:
</P>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Paula Wessely, postwar Austria's foremost
theater and movie actress and one of the most acclaimed performers
in the German-speaking world, died Thursday. She was 93.
</P>
<P>
   While praised for some of the finest stage acting of the 20th
century, Wessely was also accused of being a tool of the Nazis for
having appeared in Nazi propaganda films throughout World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Wessely's career spanned more than six decades. ''The Wessely,''
as her fans would lovingly call her, was a household word in
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   She was the star in many Nazi-era movies, but the part most held
against her was the leading role in the Nazi propaganda movie
''Heimkehr'' (Homecoming) produced in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Wessely had regrets for that role, but some
critics remained unconvinced by her token repentance.
</P>
<P>
   She excelled in most key female roles of the German and
non-German drama, from Friedrich Schiller's ''Mary Stuart'' to
Arthur Schnitzler's ''Anatol,'' and from Henryk Ibsen's ''John
Gabriel Borkman'' to Tennessee Williams ''Glass Menagerie.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Laurence Olivier mentioned her name when asked to name the
world's best actresses, and Bette Davis is known to have watched
her movies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
