<HEADLINE> China Hands Out Life Sentences  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese court on Friday sentenced two people to
life imprisonment for their involvement in a fire at a small
theater that killed 74 people, state-run television said.
</P>
<P>
   Han Benyu and Niu Yuwen were among 17 defendants tried for the
March 29 fire by a court in Jiaozuo, a city 360 miles southwest of
Beijing in central China's Henan province, state television said in
its national evening news broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The cinema showed pornographic films, the television said. Han
and Niu were given life prison terms for disseminating obscene
materials and negligence, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other people, including the man that rented the building
to Han and Niu, were sentenced to prison terms ranging from eight
to three years for crimes including bribery, abuse of power and
forging documents, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Other defendants also got prison terms, the television said
without giving details. Defendants included two people who forgot
to switch off an electric heater that started the blaze, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cenema had no safety exits and no fire equipment, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 74 people killed were migrant workers who used the
cheap all-night theater as a flophouse because they couldn't afford
accommodations, according to Jiaozuo police.
</P>
<P>
   Rapid economic development and lax enforcement of public safety
regulations have played a role in disasters in China in recent
years -- from building collapses to mine explosions. Last year, a
badly overloaded ferry which set out in stormy seas sank, killing
all but 22 of the 302 people on board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
