<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rocker Gets Warm Welcome in Philly  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- John Rocker got a nice welcome in a most
unlikely city -- until he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   In the town that once booed Santa Claus, cheered the temporary
paralysis of Michael Irvin and just two days ago threw debris
during an NBA playoff game, Rocker was embraced before the Braves'
8-7 victory over the Phillies on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   He got a mixed reaction when he entered the game in the ninth.
Some fans booed Rocker while others gave him a standing ovation.
The boos didn't compare to those directed at Phillies reliever
Wayne Gomes, who blew his third save in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker earned his eighth save in nine tries by retiring Scott
Rolen with the tying run on second base. After the game, he went
through a 45-minute workout session. Rocker refused to comment when
he emerged from the weight room, accompanied by a team official and
flanked by a major league baseball security guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go away. I'm not answering any questions,'' Rocker said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised by the positive part of the reaction
from fans, he said, ''Y'all are precious.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Other than New York, this was one of the places that was
looked at as being tough on him,'' Braves left-hander Tom Glavine
said. ''It was no worse or no better.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs like ''You Can Rock Me John'' greeted Rocker when he
walked onto the field at Veterans Stadium at 5:42 p.m. Several
hundred fans were already in the ballpark when the reliever came
out before the Braves-Phillies game.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a heavy security presence, many fans flocked to him,
waving baseballs, caps and assorted items in hopes of getting an
autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ''I came to see the Braves, but John Rocker is OK in my book,''
said 25-year-old Joy Davis, who drew a chuckle and an autograph
from Rocker when she waved her ''Rock Me'' sign at him. ''If he
gets in tonight, you'll hear me cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, whose offensive comments about minorities, gays and
immigrants in New York made him baseball's most controversial
figure, was the most popular player on the field before the game.
</P>
<P>
   He chatted with fans along the left-field line, tossed baseballs
into the stands and signed autographs for several minutes. He was
the first player on either team to sign, was joined for a couple
minutes by Greg Maddux and Bobby Bonilla, and was the last player
off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's OK,'' said Bob Creech, a Yankees fan who drove down from
New York with his wife and two children. ''He has opinions. There's
bigots in New York, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, often a target of fans' heckling in Philadelphia,
wasn't surprised by Rocker's reception.
</P>
<P>
   ''It depends on where he goes,'' Bonilla said. ''Nothing is
going to be as bad as New York. He didn't say anything bad about
Philly.''
</P>
<P>
   Security at the Vet was increased in anticipation of Rocker's
arrival. Police officers lined the area above the Atlanta bullpen
before and during the game. Fans were not allowed to stand in that
area during batting practice while Rocker played catch in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hallinan, head of security for major league baseball, and
a couple staff members made the trip to Philadelphia. They've also
been to San Diego, Los Angeles and Miami before or during Rocker's
visit to those cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just here to tighten things up, to make sure we're all
on the same page,'' Hallinan said. ''We want this to be a ballgame,
not a security event.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan's son, Tom, and another staff member sat
inconspicuously in the left-field seats while Rocker warmed up
before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're paying attention to the areas that we should be
watching,'' Kevin Hallinan said. ''We're looking at the bullpen as
the area. We want to keep the concentration on the game. We'll be
around, but we don't want to make a big deal out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies general manager Ed Wade hoped to avoid a repeat of the
J.D. Drew debacle during St. Louis' trip to Philadelphia last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Fans, upset that Drew refused to sign with the Phillies after
being drafted No. 1 in 1997, tossed batteries at him in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just hoping for a good, clean game with no distractions,
and not what we went through last year when J.D. came back,'' Wade
said before the game. ''I would just hope that our fans voice their
opinions and leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker should get a harsher reaction when Atlanta goes to New
York for a four-game series against the Mets beginning June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Already, photocopied fliers have been passed out at Shea Stadium
advertising ''John Rocker Battery Day'' for Atlanta's first series
in New York, where fans are still outraged by the pitcher's
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ''Imagine having to take the 7 train to (Shea Stadium) looking
like you're (in) Beirut next to some kid with purple hair, next to
some queer with AIDS, right next to some dude who got out of jail
for the fourth time, right next to some 20-year-old mom with four
kids,'' Rocker told Sports Illustrated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2335 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0275 </DOCNO>
