<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITS to add Editors note  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo NYR126
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New York City Police have found a trailer in
Queens that was stolen from New Jersey earlier this week and was
filled with cyanide.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities cordoned off an area in an industrial park near the
Long Island Expressway in Long Island City.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known if the cyanide was still inside the
abandoned trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The trailer was reported missing May 4, after it was taken from
the Union County warehouse in Linden, N.J. It contained a shipping
container with 20 drums of potassium cyanide, each about as big as
a beer keg, along with machinery, car parts and tape measures.
</P>
<P>
   Linden police had said the trailer was hauled away by truck, and
the thieves were probably unaware of their deadly cargo.
</P>
<P>
   New York City was first informed of the missing trailer on
Thursday night, said Richard J. Sheirer, the director of the city's
Office of Emergency Management. The trailer, which was found
without a cab and without plates, was located by a police grid
search.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe it's terrorists,'' said Sheirer. People in
the area were being moved upwind of the trailer late Friday, as
workers dressed in protective gear prepared to enter the trailer.
There are no homes in the industrial park, which runs alongside the
Long Island Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   Potassium cyanide is used in electroplating, a process employed
to make silverware and jewelry, and can be fatal to anyone who
drinks or inhales it. The manmade liquid kills by preventing oxygen
from reaching vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   In case the orange barrels were removed from the trailer,
Sheirer advised anyone who sees one: ''Don't touch them, don't
remove them, call 911 immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-12-00 2336 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-12 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hearst CEO Defends Editorial Offer  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT ANDREWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Top Hearst Corp. executives testified
Friday that they had no knowledge of an offer to give Mayor Willie
Brown favorable editorials in the San Francisco Examiner in
exchange for his support of Hearst's purchase of the rival
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was horrified,'' said Hearst CEO Frank Bennack Jr. ''If
true, it is clearly outside and contrary to our policies ... and
Journalism 101.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst is being sued by Clint Reilly, a real estate investor and
former mayoral candidate, on antitrust grounds to block its
purchase of the Chronicle and the subsidized transfer of the
Examiner to a company set up by publisher Ted Fang.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the deal have said Hearst executives knew last year
about the offer by now-suspended Publisher Timothy White to Brown.
They also were accused of taking action against White only because
he disclosed the offer publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack and Hearst Newspapers President George Irish said they
were unaware of the offer until White testified about it in court
on May 1. Bennack said he would have disciplined White earlier if
he had known about the publisher's similar testimony in a
deposition in December.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has said he can't recall whether such an offer was made.
</P>
<P>
   Irish said he did not believe White had correctly answered the
question in court about his offer to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've known Tim White for nine years and I've known him to be a
very honorable person and I just think he was confused,'' Irish
testified.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle and Examiner are jointly run, except for editorial
functions, under a federal antitrust exemption. The owners of both
papers want to terminate the joint operating agreement five years
early.
</P>
<P>
   On the trial's first day, White testified that he made the offer
to Brown. He later recanted in a written statement to the media,
saying the editorial independence of the paper was never in
jeopardy. No attempt has been made in court to retract or
contradict his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack also testified about his negotiations for the Chronicle,
saying Hearst's first offer of $565 million was met with the
Chronicle Publishing Co.'s counteroffer of $700 million. The
companies eventually settled on $660 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bennack said he plans to improve the Chronicle editorially,
using increased profits he anticipates from shedding the Examiner,
which has about one-quarter the readers of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have the opportunity to give this region the kind
of world-class newspaper it is entitled to,'' he testified. ''That
is what we intend to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-12-00 2337 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000512.0277 </DOCNO>
